nited States [[National Cancer Institute]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dtp.nci.nih.gov/timeline/noflash/success_stories/S4_halichondrinB.htm | title = Success Story: Halichondrin B (NSC 609395) E7389 (NSC 707389) | publisher = Developmental Therapeutics Program, [[National Cancer Institute]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090710205200/http://dtp.nci.nih.gov/timeline/noflash/success_stories/S4_halichondrinB.htm | archivedate = 2009-07-10 }}</ref> and, in 1991, was the original test case for identification of mechanism of action (in this case, [[tubulin]]-targeted [[mitotic inhibitor]]) by NCI's then-brand-new \"[[NCI-60|60-cell line screen]]\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dtp.nci.nih.gov/branches/btb/ivclsp.html | title = NCI-60 DTP Human Tumor Cell Line Screen | publisher = Developmental Therapeutics Program, National Cancer Institute | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090710183850/http://dtp.nci.nih.gov/branches/btb/ivclsp.html | archivedate = 2009-07-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1874739\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Bai RL, Paull KD, Herald CL, Malspeis L, Pettit GR, Hamel E | title = Halichondrin B and homohalichondrin B, marine natural products binding in the vinca domain of tubulin. Discovery of tubulin-based mechanism of action by analysis of differential cytotoxicity data | journal = J. Biol. Chem. | volume = 266 | issue = 24 | pages = 15882\u20139 |date=August 1991 | pmid = 1874739 | doi = | url = }}</ref>  The complete chemical synthesis of halichondrin B was achieved by [[Yoshito Kishi]] and colleagues at [[Harvard University]] in 1992,<ref name=\"Aicher_1992\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Aicher TD, Buszek KR, Fang FG, Forsyth CJ, Jung SH, Kishi Y, Matelich MC, Scola PM, Spero DM, Yoon SK | author6-link = Kishi Y | title = Total synthesis of halichondrin B and norhalichondrin B | journal = J. Am. Chem. Soc. | year = 1992 | volume = 114 | issue = 8 | pages = 3162\u20133164 | doi = 10.1021/ja00034a086}}</ref>  an achievement that ultimately enabled the discovery and development of the structurally simplified and pharmaceutically optimized analog [[eribulin]] (E7389, ER-086526, NSC-707389).<ref name=\"pmid11221827\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Towle MJ, Salvato KA, Budrow J, Wels BF, Kuznetsov G, Aalfs KK, Welsh S, Zheng W, Seletsk BM, Palme MH, Habgood GJ, Singer LA, Dipietro LV, Wang Y, Chen JJ, Quincy DA, Davis A, Yoshimatsu K, Kishi Y, Yu MJ, Littlefield BA | author19-link = Kishi Y | title = In vitro and in vivo anticancer activities of synthetic macrocyclic ketone analogues of halichondrin B | journal = Cancer Res. | volume = 61 | issue = 3 | pages = 1013\u201321 |date=February 2001 | pmid = 11221827 | doi = | url = }}</ref><ref name=\"isbn0-8493-1863-7\">{{cite book | veditors = Newman DJ, ((Kingston DGI)), Cragg GM | title = Anticancer agents from natural products | edition = | publisher = Taylor & Francis | location = Washington, DC | year = 2005 | chapter = Discovery of E7389, a fully synthetic macrocyclic ketone analogue of halichondrin B | vauthors = Yu MJ, Kishi Y, Littlefield BA | author2-link = Kishi Y | isbn = 978-0-8493-1863-4 | oclc = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> [[Eribulin]] was approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration on November 15, 2010, to treat patients with metastatic breast cancer who have received at least two prior chemotherapy regimens for late-stage disease, including both anthracycline- and taxane-based chemotherapies.<ref>{{cite press release | title = FDA approves new treatment option for late-stage breast cancer | publisher = USFDA | date = 2010-11-15 | url = https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm233863.htm | accessdate = November 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Eribulin]] is marketed by [[Eisai Co.]] under the tradename Halaven.\n\n==Biosynthesis==\nWhile a producer organism for Halichondrin B has never been isolated in pure culture, the structural features of Halichondrin B, such as the 'odd-even' rule of methylation, and the presence of a fused ring polyethers, suggest it is a product of dinoflagellate polyether metabolism.<ref name=\"Van_Wagoner2014\">{{cite journal | last=Van Wagoner | first=Ryan M. | last2=Satake | first2=Masayuki | last3=Wright | first3=Jeffrey L. C. | title=Polyketide biosynthesis in dinoflagellates: what makes it different? | journal=Natural Product Reports | publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry (RSC) | volume=31 | issue=9 | date=2014-06-16 | issn=0265-0568 | doi=10.1039/c4np00016a | page=1101}}</ref> In support of this conjecture, the known dinoflagellate polyether okadeic acid was isolated from the same genus of sponge.<ref name=\"Tachibana_1981\">{{cite journal | last=Tachibana | first=Kazuo | last2=Scheuer | first2=Paul J. | last3=Tsukitani | first3=Yasumasa | last4=Kikuchi | first4=Hiroyuki | last5=Van Engen | first5=Donna | last6=Clardy | first6=Jon | last7=Gopichand | first7=Yalamanchili | last8=Schmitz | first8=Francis J. | title=Okadaic acid, a cytotoxic polyether from two marine sponges of the genus Halichondria | journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society | publisher=American Chemical Society (ACS) | volume=103 | issue=9 | year=1981 | issn=0002-7863 | doi=10.1021/ja00399a082 | pages=2469\u20132471}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Macrolides]]\n[[Category:Polyether toxins]]\n", "name_user": "Photocyte", "label": "safe", "comment": "add link to Okadaic acid", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halichondrin_B"}
{"title_page": "Thirumeni", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Thirumeni\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Kerala#India<!--India Kerala-->\n| pushpin_label_position  = left\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Kerala##Location in India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|12|15|N|75|25|E|display=inline,title|region:IN_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kannur]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = Cherupuzha Panchayat\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 8919\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 670511\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 91-4985\n| registration_plate      = \n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Payyanur]] and [[Thaliparamba]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1        = Kasaragod\n| blank3_name_sec1        = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank3_info_sec1        = Payyanur\n| blank4_name_sec1        = Civic agency\n| blank4_info_sec1        = Thirumeni village, Cherupuzha panchayat\n| website                 = \n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-KL]]\n| footnotes               =  \n}}\n[[File:Chathamangalam Theruvamala.jpg|thumb|Chathamangalam Theruvamala]]\n'''Thirumeni''' is a village in [[Kannur district]] in the [[Kerala]] state of [[India]].The village consists majorly of immigrants from various part of Travancore([[Kottayam_district|Kottayam]], [[Pathanamthitta_district|Pathanamthitta]] and [[Idukki_district|Idukki]] Districts) who settled in the famed Malabar migration period. Most of the inhabitants of the village reside in the valley of three major hills by name Chathammangalam Theruvamala alias Alumbumala, Kottathalachimala and Thevarkunnumala. Thirumeni is a small junction with a few government institutions, religious institutions and small shops in int. and is subdivided into smaller villages like Kokkadave, Prapoyil, [[Chathamangalam (Kannur)]], Thabore , Muthuvom, Korali, Chattivayal, Thannichal, Paruthikallu etc.<ref name=\"censusindia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Village_Directory/Population_data/Population_5000_and_Above.aspx|title=Census of India : Villages with population 5000 & above |publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India |accessdate=2008-12-10}}Geographically, the village is situated in the Western Ghats and is very close to the Coorg district of Karnataka state.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]], Thirumeni had a population of 8919 with 4466 males and 4453 females.<ref name=\"censusindia\" />\n\n==Politics==\nThirumeni is a place where Hindus and Christians mainly and a few Muslims live in harmony. The place is surrounded by mountains. Most of the people are migrated from [[travancore]]. The villagers are also politically interested. The main political parties are [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], [[Indian National Congress|INC]], [[Kerala Congress]]. The nearest educational institutions are Government Higher Secondary School Thirumeni, SNDPLP School.\n\n==Transportation==\nThe national highway passes through [[Perumba River|Perumba]] junction. [[Goa]] and [[Mumbai]] can be accessed on the northern side and [[Cochin]] and [[Thiruvananthapuram]] can be accessed on the southern side.  The road to the east of [[Iritty]] connects to [[Mysore]] and [[Bangalore]].   The nearest railway station is [[Payyanur railway station|Payyanur]] on [[Mangalore]]-[[Palakkad]] line. \nTrains are available to almost all parts of India subject to advance booking over the internet.  There are airports at [[Kannur International Airport|Kannur]], [[Mangalore Airport|Mangalore]] and [[Calicut International Airport|Calicut]]. All of them are international airports but direct flights are available only to Middle Eastern countries.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kannur district}}\n\n[[Category:Villages near Payyanur]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Thirumeni\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Kerala#India<!--India Kerala-->\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Kerala##Location in India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|12|15|N|75|25|E|display=inline,title|region:IN_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kannur]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = Cherupuzha Panchayat\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 8919\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 670511\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 91-4985\n| registration_plate      = \n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Payyanur]] and [[Thaliparamba]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1        = Kasaragod\n| blank3_name_sec1        = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank3_info_sec1        = Payyanur\n| blank4_name_sec1        = Civic agency\n| blank4_info_sec1        = Thirumeni village, Cherupuzha panchayat\n| website                 = \n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-KL]]\n| footnotes               =  \n}}\n[[File:Chathamangalam Theruvamala.jpg|thumb|Chathamangalam Theruvamala]]\n'''Thirumeni''' is a village in [[Kannur district]] in the [[Kerala]] state of [[India]].The village consists majorly of immigrants from various part of Travancore([[Kottayam_district|Kottayam]], [[Pathanamthitta_district|Pathanamthitta]] and [[Idukki_district|Idukki]] Districts) who settled in the famed Malabar migration period. Most of the inhabitants of the village reside in the valley of three major hills by name Chathammangalam Theruvamala alias Alumbumala, Kottathalachimala and Thevarkunnumala. Thirumeni is a small junction with a few government institutions, religious institutions and small shops in int. and is subdivided into smaller villages like Kokkadave, Prapoyil, [[Chathamangalam (Kannur)]], Thabore , Muthuvom, Korali, Chattivayal, Thannichal, Paruthikallu etc.<ref name=\"censusindia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Village_Directory/Population_data/Population_5000_and_Above.aspx|title=Census of India : Villages with population 5000 & above |publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India |accessdate=2008-12-10}}Geographically, the village is situated in the Western Ghats and is very close to the Coorg district of Karnataka state.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]], Thirumeni had a population of 8919 with 4466 males and 4453 females.<ref name=\"censusindia\" />\n\n==Politics==\nThirumeni is a place where Hindus and Christians mainly and a few Muslims live in harmony. The place is surrounded by mountains. Most of the people are migrated from [[travancore]]. The villagers are also politically interested. The main political parties are [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], [[Indian National Congress|INC]], [[Kerala Congress]]. The nearest educational institutions are Government Higher Secondary School Thirumeni, SNDPLP School.\n\n==Transportation==\nThe national highway passes through [[Perumba River|Perumba]] junction. [[Goa]] and [[Mumbai]] can be accessed on the northern side and [[Cochin]] and [[Thiruvananthapuram]] can be accessed on the southern side.  The road to the east of [[Iritty]] connects to [[Mysore]] and [[Bangalore]].   The nearest railway station is [[Payyanur railway station|Payyanur]] on [[Mangalore]]-[[Palakkad]] line. \nTrains are available to almost all parts of India subject to advance booking over the internet.  There are airports at [[Kannur International Airport|Kannur]], [[Mangalore Airport|Mangalore]] and [[Calicut International Airport|Calicut]]. All of them are international airports but direct flights are available only to Middle Eastern countries.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kannur district}}\n\n[[Category:Villages near Payyanur]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thirumeni"}
{"title_page": "Newcastle-under-Lyme", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Newcastle upon Tyne}}\n{{about|the town|the larger local government district|Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|the constituency|Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country= England\n|official_name= Newcastle-under-Lyme\n|static_image_name= Liverpool Road, Newcastle-Under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 2101373.jpg\n|static_image_caption= \n|coordinates = {{coord|53.0109|-2.2278|display=inline,title}}\n|population= 75,082\n|population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|shire_district= [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n|shire_county= [[Staffordshire]]\n|region= West Midlands\n|constituency_westminster= [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n|post_town= NEWCASTLE<ref name=posttown>The county name is no longer required for postcoded mail and the suffix \"-under-Lyme\" is not part of the official [[Royal Mail]] name of the [[post town]], despite the potential for confusion with similarly named places.</ref>\n|postcode_district= ST5\n|postcode_area= ST\n|dial_code= 01782\n|os_grid_reference= SJ848459\n}}\n\n'''Newcastle-under-Lyme''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|nj|u\u02d0|k|\u0251\u02d0|s|\u0259l|-}} {{respell|NEW|kahss|\u0259l|-}}, locally {{IPAc-en|-|k|\u00e6|s|-}} {{respell|-kass-}};), is a [[market town]] in [[Staffordshire]], England. At the 2011 census it had a population of 75,082.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NEWCASTLE-UNDER-LYME in Staffordshire (West Midlands) Built-up Area Subdivision [url=https://www.citypopulation.de/en/uk/westmidlands/staffordshire/E35001436__newcastle_under_lyme/ |publisher=City Population |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref> It is part of the borough of [[Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|Newcastle-under-Lyme]], which had a population of 128,264 in 2016, up from 123,800 in the 2011 Census.<ref>[http://www.ukcensusdata.com/newcastle-under-lyme-e07000195#sthash.iWOL8G4y.ekwVkSxO.dpbs Wards. Retrieved 20 December 2018.]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Etymology===\nThe \"Newcastle\" part of the name derives from being the location of a new castle in the 12th century.<ref name=\"bchistory\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/leisure_content.asp?id=-A78083C8&cat=1263 |title=History of Newcastle |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=20 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321182014/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/leisure_content.asp?id=-A78083C8&cat=1263 |archivedate=21 March 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The \"Lyme\" section could refer to the [[Lyme Brook]] or (as in the family name Lindhurst) the extensive [[Forest of Lyme]] that covered the area with [[lime (tree)|lime trees]] in the [[Middle Ages]].<ref name=\"bchistory\"/><ref name=\"ekwall\">{{Cite book |title=The Concise Dictionary of English Place-names; 2nd ed. |last=Ekwall |first=Eilert |year=1940 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford |isbn= |page=294}}</ref>\n\n===12th\u201319th centuries===\nNewcastle is not mentioned in the 1086 [[Domesday Book]], as it grew up around the 12th-century castle, but it must have rapidly become a place of importance, because a [[charter]], known only through a reference in another charter to [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], was given to the town by [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] in 1173. The new castle was built to supersede an older fortress at [[Chesterton, Staffordshire|Chesterton]] about {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} to the north, the ruins of which were visible up to the end of the 16th century.\n\nIn 1235 [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] constituted it a free borough, granting a [[guild]] merchant and other privileges.<ref name=\"bchistory\" /> In 1251 he leased it under a [[fee farm grant]] to the burgesses. In 1265 Newcastle was granted by the [[The Crown|Crown]] to [[Simon de Montfort, 6th Earl of Leicester|Simon de Montfort]], and subsequently to [[Edmund Crouchback]], through whom it passed to [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]]. In [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland's]] time the castle had disappeared \"save one great Toure\".\n\n[[File:Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 2101001.jpg|thumb|Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme]]\n\nNewcastle did not feature much in the [[English Civil War]], except for a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] [[plundering]].<ref name=\"brithist\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dmhospice.org.uk/ |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme |work=British History Online |publisher=University of London & History of Parliament Trust |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref> However, it was the home town of Major General [[Thomas Harrison (soldier)|Thomas Harrison]], a [[Cromwellian]] army officer and leader of the [[Fifth Monarchy Men]].\n\nThe governing charter in 1835,<ref name=\"bchistory\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10002795&c_id=10001043 |title=Relationships / unit history of NEWCASTLE UNDER LYME |work=A Vision of Britain |publisher=[[University of Portsmouth]] Department of [[Geography]] |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930204304/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10002795&c_id=10001043 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> which created the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme Municipal Borough]], absorbed the previous borough created through the charters of 1590 and 1664, under which the title of the corporation, was the \"mayor, bailiffs and burgesses of Newcastle-under-Lyme\".<ref name=\"bchistory\" />\n\nNewcastle sent two members to Parliament from 1355 to 1885, when it lost one of the members.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/constituencies/newcastle-under-lyme The History of Parliament Trust, Newcastle-under-Lyme, Borough, from 1386 to 1481] Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\n[[File:Nelsonplace1900.jpg|right|thumb|Nelson Place and view up King Street, from a postcard, c. 1900]]\n\n===20th century===\nWhen [[Stoke-on-Trent]] was [[Federation of Stoke-on-Trent|formed by the 1910 amalgamation]] of the \"six towns\" ([[Stoke-upon-Trent|Stoke]], [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]], [[Fenton, Staffordshire|Fenton]], [[Longton, Staffordshire|Longton]], [[Burslem]] and [[Tunstall, Staffordshire|Tunstall]]), Newcastle remained separate. \n\nDespite its close proximity, it was not directly involved in the pottery industry, and it strongly opposed attempts to join the amalgamation in 1930,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Stoke-on-Trent Bill: Extension of the City |publisher=The Times |date=2 May 1930}}</ref> with a postcard poll showing residents opposing the Stoke-on-Trent Extension Bill by a majority of 97.4 per cent. Although passed by the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], the Bill was rejected by the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=\"brithist\" />\n\nFollowing the [[Local Government Act 1972]], it became the principal settlement of the Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme.\n\n===Economy===\nLike neighbouring Stoke-on-Trent, Newcastle's early economy was based around the hatting trade, silk and [[cotton mill]]s. Later [[coal mining]], [[brick]] manufacture, [[iron]] casting and [[engineering]] rose to prominence.<ref name=\"bchistory\" /> Very fine red earthenware and also [[soft-paste porcelain]] [[tableware]] (the first such production in Staffordshire) was produced in Newcastle at Samuel Bell's factory in Lower Street between 1724 and 1754, when production ceased. With the exception of a failed enterprise between 1790 and 1797, which then switched to [[brewing]], there was no further commercial production of pottery within the town of Newcastle. Production of earthenware tiles, however, continued at several locations within the borough. Manufacture of fine [[bone china]] was re-established in the borough in 1963 by [[Mayfair Pottery]] at [[Chesterton, Staffordshire|Chesterton]].\n\nThe manufacture in the borough of clay [[smoking pipe (tobacco)|tobacco-smoking pipes]] started about 1637 and grew rapidly, until it was second only to hatting as an industry. Nationally, the town ranked with [[Chester]], [[York]] and [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] as the four major pipe producers. The industry continued until the mid-19th century, when decline set in rapidly, so that by 1881 there was only one tobacco-pipe maker left.\n\nIn the 17th, 18th and 19th centuries, the town had a flourishing [[felt]] hat manufacturing industry,<ref name=\"bchistory\" /> which was probably at its peak locally in the 1820s, when a third of the town's population were involved in over 20 factories, but by 1892 there was only one manufacturer still in production.\n\nIn 1944, the [[Rolls-Royce Derwent]] engine for the [[Gloster Meteor]] fighter was made in the borough.\n\nNewcastle's 20th-century industries include: iron-working, construction materials, clothing (especially military, police and transport uniforms), computers, publishing, electric motors and machinery.\n\nNear the turn of the 20th and 21st centuries, the town received major redevelopment to incorporate a new street (Castle Walk) into the town centre, providing Newcastle with a new [[bus station]] and bringing in more companies. Various business centres in the town provide offices for companies that operate in the service sector.\n\n===Politicians===\n[[File:Vera Brittain.jpg|thumb|Vera Brittain]]\nThe town has been the birthplace of several notable politicians and activists. [[Fanny Deakin]] was a campaigner for better nourishment for babies and young children and better maternity care for mothers. The former [[chairwoman]] of [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]] ([[CND]]), [[Janet Bloomfield]] (n\u00e9e Hood) is a peace and disarmament campaigner. [[Vera Brittain]]  writer, [[feminist]] (and mother of [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Shirley Williams]]) was born in the town.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXA203-A77FA129 |title=Vera Brittain 1893\u20131970 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901100123/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=SXA203-A77FA129 |archivedate=1 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThere have been two particularly notable [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] (MPs). [[Josiah Wedgwood, 1st Baron Wedgwood|Josiah Wedgwood IV]] was a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]], Independent and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP, who served as [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] in the [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] of [[Ramsay MacDonald]], in the first ever Labour government. He was an MP from 1909 to 1942. [[John Golding (British politician)|John Golding]] was elected a Labour MP for [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]] at a by-election in 1969. He served in the governments of [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Jim Callaghan]], as PPS to [[Eric Varley]] as [[Minister of Technology]], a Labour whip in opposition, and Minister for Employment, stepping down in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,,322315,00.html |title=Right at the heart of Labour |work=Guardian Unlimited |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |first=Paul |last=Farrelly |date=22 January 1999 |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe current MP is [[Aaron Bell (politician)|Aaron Bell]].\n\n===Transport===\nThe town was once served by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]], its station being on a branch line from [[Stoke-on-Trent]] via Newcastle, [[Silverdale, Staffordshire|Silverdale]] and [[Keele]], to [[Market Drayton]] in [[Shropshire]]. [[Newcastle-under-Lyme railway station]] opened in September 1852, after numerous construction difficulties involving the two tunnels of {{convert|605|yd|m}} and {{convert|96|yd|m}} respectively at Hartshill. There were also two halts to the west of Newcastle railway station, located at [[Brampton Halt railway station|Brampton]] and [[Liverpool Road Halt railway station|Liverpool Road]].<ref name=\"Christiansen\">{{cite book |last2=Miller |first2=R. W. |last=Christiansen |first=Rex |year=1971 |title=The North Staffordshire Railway |page=124 |publisher=David & Charles |isbn=0-7153-5121-4}}</ref>\n\nThe section from [[Silverdale (Staffordshire) railway station|Silverdale]] to [[Market Drayton railway station|Market Drayton]] closed to passengers in May 1956 and the rest of the line in March 1964. Only small sections remained from Madeley to Silverdale, and from Silverdale to Holditch, for coal traffic from the local collieries. The line from Newcastle Junction to Silverdale has been removed, with the site of Newcastle railway station and the Hartshill tunnels being filled in.\n\nNewcastle was on the national [[canal]] network, but the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme Canal]], running from the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]] at Stoke-on-Trent to [[Sir Nigel Gresley's Canal]] has been disused since 1935 and most of it filled in.\n\nToday the town relies on buses for its public transport. [[FirstGroup]] runs a network of services connecting Newcastle to the towns of [[The Potteries Urban Area|the Potteries]] as well as [[Stafford]] whilst Arriva buses run to [[Shrewsbury]] via [[Market Drayton]]\n\n==Geography==\nSituated in a valley alongside the [[Lyme Brook]], the town is immediately west of the neighbouring city of [[Stoke-on-Trent]], its [[suburb]]s running into those of the city. Newcastle town centre is less than {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} from [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Stoke-on-Trent City Centre]] and about {{convert|17|mi|km|0}} north of the [[county town]] of [[Stafford]].\n\n===Green belt===\n{{main|Stoke-on-Trent Green Belt}}\nNewcastle and Stoke form the [[Stoke-on-Trent Built-up Area|main urban area]] at the centre of the Stoke-on-Trent Green Belt, which is an [[environmental policy|environmental]] and [[Planning in the United Kingdom|planning]] area that regulates the rural space in Staffordshire,<ref name=\"new-staffs-belt\"/> to prevent [[urban sprawl]] and minimise convergence with outlying settlements. First defined in 1967,<ref name=\"new-staffs-belt\">{{cite web |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council and Stoke-on-Trent City Council Green Belt Assessment Final Report Issue \u2013 21 November 2017 |url=https://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/sites/default/files/IMCE/Planning/Planning_Policy/Newc_Stoke_GBA_Final_Report_21_11_17.pdf |website=www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk}}</ref> most of the area extends into the wider borough, but there are some landscape features and places of interest within that are covered or surrounded by the designation. They include the Michelin Sports Facility, Newcastle golf course, Keele University, Apedale Winding Wheel, Watermills Chimney, and [[Bignall Hill]]. The [[West Coast Main Line]] forms the western boundary of the green belt.\n\n==Demography==\n{{for|district-wide demographic details|Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)}}<!--Only include info about the town, not the Borough-->\n{| id=\"toc\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 2em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"3\"\n!colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |'''Comparative Census Information'''\n|-\n|'''[[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 UK Census]]'''||'''Newcastle-under-Lyme'''||'''[[Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|Borough]]'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22530/nbcEconomic1.pdf |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme Economic Profile |format=PDF |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=21 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201401/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22530/nbcEconomic1.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22519/nbcSocial1.pdf |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme Social Profile |format=PDF |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=21 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201903/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22519/nbcSocial1.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>||'''England'''\n|-\n|Total population||73,944||122,030||49,138,831\n|-\n|White||97.8%||98%||91%\n|-\n|Asian||0.6%||0.6%||4.6%\n|-\n|Black||0.2%||0.2%||2.3%\n|-\n|Christian||78.2%||78.5%||72%\n|-\n|Muslim||0.7%||0.5%||3.1%\n|-\n|Hindu||0.2%||0.2%||1.1%\n|-\n|No religion||14%||13.1%||15%\n|-\n<!-- |Bachelor's degree or higher||12%||20%||20% -->\n|-\n|Unemployed||2.3%||2%||3.3%\n|}\nOf the 73,944 residents recorded in the 2001 census, 51.7 per cent (38,210) were female and 48.3 per cent (35,734) male.<ref name=\"social\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22571/NewcastleSocial.pdf |title=2001 Census \u2013 Social Profile for Towns in Staffordshire \u2013 Newcastle-under-Lyme |format=PDF |publisher=Staffordshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201910/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22571/NewcastleSocial.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Of these, 78.2 per cent (57,819) stated that their religion was [[Christians|Christian]], and 12.9 per cent (9,570) said they had no religion. [[Islam]], [[Judaism]], [[Buddhism]] and [[Sikhism]] each covered less than 1 per cent of the population. Racially, 97.8 per cent of the population defined themselves as [[white people|white]], with the balance being [[Multiracial|mixed race]] (0.6 per cent), [[India]]n (0.4 per cent), [[Pakistan]]i (0.2 per cent), [[black people|black]] (0.2 per cent), [[Chinese people|Chinese]] (0.2 per cent), and other ethnic groups 0.4 per cent.<ref name=\"social\" />\n\nIn employment, 62.2 per cent (21,586) of the population work [[Full-time job|full-time]] and 19.4 per cent (6,746) [[Part-time job|part time]].<ref name=\"economic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22589/Newcastleeconomic.pdf |title=2001 Census \u2013 Economic Profile for Towns in Staffordshire \u2013 Newcastle-under-Lyme |format=PDF |publisher=Staffordshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201417/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22589/Newcastleeconomic.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The largest employment types are [[manufacturing]] with 7,058 (21.5 per cent), [[wholesale]] and [[retail]] 6,157 (18.7 per cent), [[health]] and [[social work]] 4,097 (12.5 per cent) and [[finance]], [[real estate]] and [[business]] activity 3,823 (11.6 per cent).<ref name=\"economic\" />\n\n[[Jewish]] residency of the area stretches back into the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/JCR-UK/Community/stoke/history.htm |title=Stoke-on-Trent Hebrew Congregation |accessdate=21 January 2007}}</ref> In 1873 the community purchased an old [[Wales|Welsh]] [[chapel]] to be used as a [[synagogue]]. In 1923 a new synagogue was built in Hanley. This was closed in 2004 and the [[Wiktionary:Congregation|congregation]] moved to a smaller synagogue in Newcastle.<ref>[http://jscn.org.uk/small-communities/stoke-on-trent-and-nortstaffordshire-hebrew-congregation/ Stoke-on-Trent and North Staffordshire Hebrew Congregation website] retrieved Jan 2017</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:A34 road Newcastle-under-Lyme.jpg|thumb|The [[A34 road (England)|A34]] London Road]]\nNewcastle-under-Lyme is served by the [[M6 motorway]] to the south and west of Newcastle and by the [[A500 road]] to the north and east. There are access points from the M6 at junctions 15 and 16, to the south and north respectively. The [[A34 road (England)|A34]] [[trunk road]] runs through Newcastle from north to south and was the main road between [[Birmingham]] and [[Manchester]] until the [[M6 motorway]] opened. There is a large bus station in the town centre.\n\n[[File:Newcastle-Under-Lyme station site.jpg|thumb|Newcastle-Under-Lyme station site, now Stations Walk.]]\n[[Newcastle-under-Lyme railway station]], which was not within the town but towards Water Street on the [[Stoke to Market Drayton Line]], closed in 1964 under the [[Beeching cuts]]. The line from Silverdale to Pipe Gate remained open to serve Silverdale Colliery and a creamery at Pipe Gate until 1998, when the line closed to all stone and mineral traffic. It now forms part of a green way from Silverdale to Newcastle-Under-Lyme, with the station site being called \"Station Walks\". The nearest station to the town is [[Stoke-on-Trent railway station]] which is between the town centre of Newcastle and city centre of Stoke-on-Trent and serves the Potteries as a whole. The loss of the railway station has made Newcastle Under Lyme the third largest town without a railway station.\n\nMost of the bus network is run by [[First Potteries]] Limited and [[D&G Bus]].\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|Keele University}}\n\nThe town also has an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]]: [[Newcastle-under-Lyme School]], which was established in the 17th century, whose alumni includes [[T. E. Hulme]], [[John Wain]] and [[William Watkiss Lloyd]]. It also has a number of [[primary school|primary]] and [[secondary school]]s in the [[state school|state-funded sector]]. The latter include [[Newcastle Academy|Newcastle Community Academy]], [[Clayton Hall Academy]], [[St John Fisher Catholic College]], [[Sir Thomas Boughey High School]] and [[Wolstanton High School]]. There is also a private [https://www.edenhurst.co.uk Edenhurst Preparatory School], founded in 1961. \n\nThe town's largest sixth form college is [[Newcastle-under-Lyme College]], which was established in the 1966. \n\n[[Keele University]] main campus is situated {{convert|3|mi|km|0}} from the centre of the town.\n\n==Sites and attractions==\n===Parks and gardens===\n[[File:Queens gardens newcastle under lyme.jpg|thumb|Queen's Gardens]]\nNewcastle excels in the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] [[Britain in Bloom]] competition. In 2005 it was national winner in the \"small city/large town\" category (35K\u2013100K).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhs.org.uk/britaininbloom/heart_of_england/newcastlewinner2005.asp |publisher=Royal Horticultural Society |work=Britain in Bloom |title=2005 winners |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612114448/http://www.rhs.org.uk/britaininbloom/heart_of_england/newcastlewinner2005.asp |archivedate=12 June 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The town features several parks, including the Queen's Gardens at the eastern end of Ironmarket, which won the Britain in Bloom Judges' Award for Horticultural Excellence in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXFBE1-A77F7BB2&cat=325 |title=Britain in Bloom |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210033010/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXFBE1-A77F7BB2&cat=325 |archivedate=10 December 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Queens Gardens now contains a statue of [[Queen Victoria]] funded by Sir [[Alfred Seale Haslam]] and unveiled by [[Grand Duke Michael Mikhailovich of Russia]] on 5 November 1903. It is the only park within the [[ring road]].\n\nGrosvenor Gardens is in the centre of one of the town's roundabouts, but hidden away below road level. Queen Elizabeth Garden is located outside the town centre and was due for refurbishment using [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery Heritage Fund]] money.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/6439721.stm |title=Lottery cash to restore town park |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=6 May 2007 |date=11 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nTo the north west of the town centre is Brampton Park, home to a museum and art gallery.<ref>[https://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/all-services/sport-and-culture/brampton-museum/brampton-park Borough Council website, Brampton Park] retrieved Jan 2017</ref>\n\n===Traditional market===<!-- This section is linked from [[The Stones (market)]] -->\n[[File:Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 2101001.jpg|thumb|Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme]]\nDating back to 1173 Newcastle's [[market (place)|market]], known as the Stones, operates on the High Street.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=-A77F7A70 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |title=Markets and Town Centres Information |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210033015/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=-A77F7A70 |archivedate=10 December 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The market was originally held on Sunday; in the reign of [[John of England|John]] it was changed to Saturday; by the charter of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]] it was fixed on Monday. Grants of fairs were given by [[Edward I of England|Edward I]], [[Edward III of England|Edward III]] and [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]].\n\nToday the market is open six days a week, and there are over 80 stalls. Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays see a general market, on Tuesdays there is an [[antique]]s market and Thursdays are for the sale of bric-a-brac. A [[cattle]] and [[livestock]] market was held on Mondays until the early 1990s; the site of the cattle market is now a branch of Morrison's supermarket.\n\n[[File:Guildhall newcastle under lyme.jpg|thumb|left|The Guildhall]]\n\n===The Guildhall===\nThe current Guildhall was built in 1713 and has undergone a number of changes.<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/023.htm Website of Potteries.org \u2013 Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries Retrieved February 2017] has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative on The Guildhall, Newcastle.</ref> Originally the ground floor was open and was used for markets, until the Market Hall was built in 1854. In 1860, in order to provide more space, the ground floor arches were bricked up and clock tower with four clocks were added. The top rooms in the Guildhall were used for meetings by the Borough council and its committees, until 1860. It is now a grade II listed building.\n\n===The Barracks===\nThe Italian styled Militia Barracks were built in 1855 from red brick. They were the headquarters of the 3rd King's Own Staffordshire Rifle Regiment until 1880. In 1882 W. H. Dalton bought the Barracks and settled them in trust for use by the Rifle Volunteers of Newcastle, which became the Territorial Force in 1907. In 2002 the Barracks were let to small businesses.<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/022.htm Website of Potteries.org - Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries Retrieved Feb 2017] This has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative about the Barracks.</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Newcastle-under-Lyme Museum & Art Gallery (1).jpg|thumb|Newcastle-under-Lyme Museum & Art Gallery]]\nThe [[New Vic Theatre]] was Europe's first purpose-built [[theatre in the round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newvictheatre.org.uk/about/about.html |publisher=New Vic Theatre |title=History of the New Vic theatre |accessdate=5 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928011242/http://www.newvictheatre.org.uk/about/about.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=28 September 2007}}</ref> Just outside the town centre, it offers a programme of entertainment that includes modern or classic plays and concert performances.\n\nThe Borough Museum and Art Gallery (Brampton Museum) depicts the civic history of the Borough of Newcastle under Lyme and an authentic, life-size [[Victorian era|Victorian]] street-scene whilst the art gallery hosts work by local and national artists as well as travelling exhibitions.<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/026.htm Website of Potteries.org - Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries Retrieved Feb 2017] This has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative about Newcastle-under-Lyme Museum.</ref><ref>[https://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/all-services/sport-and-culture/brampton-museum Brampton Museum on town's website] retrieved Jan 2017</ref> \n\nNotable residents who contributed to the arts and entertainment include [[Philip Astley]], founder of the modern circus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXA16E-A77F9F88 |title=Philip Astley 1742\u20131814 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070902001318/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=SXA16E-A77F9F88 |archivedate=2 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Jackie Trent]], the singer and songwriter, was born in the town.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jackie-trent.org.uk/biog.html |title=Jackie Trent Biography |accessdate=6 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501203152/http://www.jackie-trent.org.uk/biog.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 May 2007}}</ref> [[Arnold Bennett]], the novelist, playwright, and essayist, completed his schooling at the Middle School,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/bennett.htm |title=Arnold Bennett Profile |work=Literary Heritage |publisher=Shropshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503012007/http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/bennett.htm |archivedate=3 May 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and called the town Oldcastle in his ''[[Clayhanger]]'' trilogy of novels. [[Dinah Maria Mulock]], who wrote under her married name of Mrs Craik, lived in the town (in Lower Street and Mount Pleasant) and attended Brampton House Academy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/craik.htm |title=Dinah Craik |work=Literary Heritage |publisher=Shropshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701151408/http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/craik.htm |archivedate=1 July 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[E. S. Turner]], social commentator, was educated in the town.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/07/17/db1701.xml |title=ES Turner Obituary |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited |date=17 July 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref> Newcastle was also home to Dr Philip Willoughby-Higson (1933\u20132012), poet, translator and historian, and author of 33 books. He was founder and president (1974\u20131992) of the Chester Poets, the oldest poetry group in the North West, and President of the Baudelaire Society of France from 1992 to 2012 \u2013 the only Englishman ever to receive that position.\n\nHistorically, the town had a tradition of festivities marking the start of a new [[municipal year]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Sport==\nThe wide range of sports clubs and associations includes [[Newcastle Town F.C.]], an [[association football]] club currently playing in the Northern Premier League First Division South. \n\nThe largest rugby union club is Newcastle Staffs Rugby Union Club.\n\nCycle Staffordshire organises many local cycling events, as does the Newcastle [[Track cycling|Track Cycling]] Association. The town has a [[velodrome]] used by the Lyme Racing Club,<ref>[http://www.lymeracingclub.co.uk/ Lyme Racing Club website] retrieved Jan 2017</ref> which has over 150 members, including an increasing junior membership. It is active in many areas, including time trials, track racing, road racing, Audax riding, mountain biking, and regular Sunday Club runs and general leisure cycling.\n[[File:Newcastle Golf Club - Clubhouse - geograph.org.uk - 407961.jpg|thumb|Newcastle Golf Club]]\nNewcastle Athletic Club<ref>[http://newcastlestaffsac.org.uk/information/who-we-are/ Newcastle (Staffs) AC website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref> is based at the Ashfield Road track next to Newcastle College. This ash track was constructed in 1964. The club competes in the North Staffs XC League and the Local, National and Heart of England League 3.\n\nThe town is home to one of the most prominent volleyball clubs in England, [[Newcastle (Staffs) Volleyball Club]]. Established in 1980, it has teams playing in the National Volleyball League, producing numerous England and Great Britain international players over the years. \n\nNewcastle under Lyme College is home to Castle Korfball Club, one of the nation's oldest such clubs.<ref>[http://www.castlekorfball.co.uk Castle Korfball Club website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref>\n\nThe town has a successful swimming club; Newcastle (Staffs) Swimming Club, which was founded in 1908.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastleasc.net/ |title=Newcastle (Staffs) ASC {{!}} Newcastle Staffs Amateur Swimming Club, founded 1908 |language=en-GB |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThere are golf courses at Kidsgrove, Wolstanton, Keele and Westlands.<ref>[http://www.newcastlegolfclub.co.uk/index.php/en/ Newcastle Golf Club website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.wolstantongolfclub.co.uk/ Wolstanton Golf Clubwebsite] Retrieved January 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.keelegolfrange.co.uk/drivingrange/ Keele Golf Range website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref>\n\nKeele University is home to one of the UK's first [[quidditch]] teams, the Keele Squirrels.<ref> [https://keelesu.com/activities/society/quidditch/ Keele university quidditch society website] retrieved April 2018 </ref>. It hosted the first ever quidditch game in the UK in 2011 against the [[Leicester]] Thestrals.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Giles' Church Street Newcastle-under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 558236.jpg|thumb|left|St Giles' Church, Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\nThe town was the birthplace of [[John James Blunt]], a [[Anglicanism#Anglican divines|divine]] and [[Anglican]] priest. [[Josiah Wedgwood]] was a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] and he and his family attended meetings at the Old Meeting House, adjacent to St Giles' Church, which is still in use for the purpose.\n\nThe town has a large number of Anglican churches, including St Giles, the medieval parish church dating from 1290.<ref>[http://www.stgilesnewcastle.org.uk/ Website of The Parish Church of St Giles] Retrieved January 2017.</ref> There are several [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] churches, notably Holy Trinity,<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/021.htm Website of Potteries.org - Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries. Retrieved February 2017.] This has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative about Holy Trinity Church, Newcastle,</ref><ref>[http://www.holytrinitynewcastle.org.uk/parish-history Website of Holy Trinity Catholic Church, Newcastle Retrieved January 2017.]</ref> whose style is [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] in blue engineering bricks, described as \"''the finest modern specimen of ornamental brickwork in the kingdom\"'' at the time.\n[[File:Jewish cemetery and Synagogue - geograph.org.uk - 335713.jpg|thumb|Jewish cemetery and Synagogue on the A34]]\nIn the 18th century [[John Wesley]] made repeated visits to the area, which was becoming industrialised, and recruited many residents to [[Methodism]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepotteries.org/history/spiritual_history.html |title=The Christian History of Stoke-on-Trent |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref> This is reflected in a large number of [[Methodist]] churches.<ref>[http://www.northstaffordshiremethodists.org.uk/churches/church-profiles/newcastle-methodist-church.php Newcastle Methodist Church Circuit website Retrieved January 2017].</ref> There is a [[Baptist]] church in [[Clayton, Staffordshire|Clayton]].<ref>[http://www.newcastlebaptist.org.uk/ Newcastle Baptist Church website Retrieved January 2017.]</ref>\n\nOf interest also is [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church), across from the Brampton Park, which serves as the \"[[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|Stake Centre]]\" for the church in the region and has an on-site [[Family History Center (LDS Church)|Family History Centre]], where the public can research their ancestry at little or no charge.\n\n==International network==\nThe town is part of a worldwide network of towns and cities with the name [[Newcastle (disambiguation)|Newcastle]]<!--intentional link to DAB page-->.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/stoke/content/articles/2006/08/11/newcastle_under_lyme_towns_feature.shtml |publisher=BBC Stoke |title=Towns and Villages - Newcastle-under-Lyme |accessdate=6 May 2007}}.</ref> These include well-known [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] (also in England), [[Neuburg an der Donau]] (Germany), [[Neuch\u00e2tel]] (Switzerland), [[Neufch\u00e2teau, Vosges|Neufch\u00e2teau]] (France), [[New Castle, Indiana]] (US), [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]] (US), [[New Castle, Delaware]] (US), [[Newcastle, KwaZulu-Natal]] (South Africa) and [[Shinshiro]] (Japan).\n\nThis small international network of eight towns, formed in 1998, is designed to encourage friendship and cooperation between them. Accordingly, a school in the South African town benefited in 2004 from gifts of computing equipment surplus to Newcastle-under-Lyme's needs. The annual ''Newcastles of the World'' Summit was held in Newcastle-under-Lyme for six days from 17 June 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/newsarticle.asp?id=SX9F7A-A7801EF2 |title=Warm welcome for summit delegates |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |date=15 June 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311045229/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/newsarticle.asp?id=SX9F7A-A7801EF2 |archivedate=11 March 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n*[[Neuburg an der Donau]], Germany\n*[[Neuch\u00e2tel]], Switzerland\n*[[Neufch\u00e2teau, Vosges|Neufch\u00e2teau]], France\n*[[New Castle, Delaware]], United States\n*[[New Castle, Indiana]], United States\n\n*[[New Castle, Pennsylvania]], United States\n*[[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n*[[Shinshiro]], Japan\n*[[Newcastle, KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa\n\n==Notable people==\n===Earlier centuries===\n*[[Humphrey Wollrich]] (1633\u20131707), Quaker writer<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Wolrich,_Humphrey_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900, Volume 62, Wolrich, Humphrey. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Philip Astley]] (1742\u20131814), equestrian, circus owner, inventor and father of the modern circus<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/2929565.stm BBC News Channel, Tuesday, 8 April, 2003. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Silvester Harding]] (1745\u20131809), artist and publisher, who aged 14 ran away and joined a company of strolling actors<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Harding,_Silvester_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900, Volume 24, Harding, Silvester. Retrieved December 2017].</ref> \n*[[John James Blunt]] (1794\u20131855), Anglican priest. His writings included studies of the early Church.<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop\u00e6dia_Britannica/Blunt,_John_James 1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Volume 4 Blunt, John James. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref><ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Blunt,_John_James_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 5, Blunt, John James. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n*[[Henry Moseley (mathematician)|Henry Moseley]] (1801\u20131872), churchman, mathematician, and scientist<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Moseley,_Henry_(1801-1872)_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 39, Moseley, Henry (1801-1872). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Joseph Mayer (antiquary)|Joseph Mayer]] (1803\u20131886), goldsmith, antiquary and collector<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Mayer,_Joseph_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 37, Mayer, Joseph. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Emma Darwin|Emma Darwin (n\u00e9e Wedgwood)]] (1808\u20131896), granddaughter of [[Josiah Wedgwood]] and wife of [[Charles Darwin]]<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6532176 Emma Darwin at Find a Grave. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Hungerford Crewe, 3rd Baron Crewe]] [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1812\u20131894), landowner and peer, inherited the Jacobean mansion of [[Crewe Hall]] and unsuccessfully opposed the construction of a Silverdale and Madeley Railway Company line<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p23241.htm The Peerage.com website, Hungerford Crewe, 3rd Baron Crewe] Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n\n*Sir [[Oliver Lodge]] (1851\u20131940), physicist, inventor and writer<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop\u00e6dia_Britannica/Lodge,_Sir_Oliver_Joseph 1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Volume 16, Lodge, Sir Oliver Joseph. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Arthur Heath|Arthur Howard Heath]] TD (1856\u20131930), industrialist, cricketer, Rugby Union international and local Conservative MP<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-arthur-heath-1 HANSARD 1803\u20132005, Mr Arthur Heath. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Joseph Cook]], GCMG, PC (1860 in Silverdale \u2013 1947), worked in the local coalmines and emigrated to Australia in 1885; Prime Minister of Australia from 1913 to 1914<ref>[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cook-sir-joseph-5763 Australian Dictionary of Biography, Cook, Sir Joseph (1860\u20131947) Retrieved 11 February 2018.]</ref> \n*[[Grand Duke Michael Mikhailovich of Russia]], (1861\u20131929), lived in [[Keele Hall]] from 1900 to 1909.<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27331/page/4569 The London Gazette, publication date: 9 July 1901, Issue:27331, Page:4569. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Arnold Bennett]] (1867\u20131931), writer<ref>[http://biography.yourdictionary.com/arnold-bennett YourDictionary Arnold Bennett, Facts. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Ada Nield Chew]] (1870\u20131945), suffragist\n*[[Alfred Herbert Richardson]] (1874\u20131951), policeman and Chief Constable of Newcastle-under-Lyme 1901/1903\n*[[Oliver W. F. Lodge|Oliver William Foster Lodge]] (1878\u20131955), poet and author born in Newcastle\n*[[Fanny Deakin]] (1883\u20131968), local politician born in Silverdale, who campaigned to improve nourishment of children and maternity care for mothers.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070902001036/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=SXEA55-A77FA208 Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council, 15 June 2004, Fanny Deakin 1883-1968. Retrieved December 2017].</ref>\n*[[Vera Brittain]] (1893\u20131970), author, reformer and pacifist, and mother of [[Shirley Williams]]<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/aug/30/featuresreviews.guardianreview18 The Guardian, 30 August 2003, The making of a peacenik, Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Reginald Mitchell]] (1895\u20131937), aeroplane designer of the [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]<ref>[http://www.rjmitchell-spitfire.co.uk/aboutrjmitchell/index.asp?sectionID=1 RJ Mitchell website, A life in aviation. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n*[[Ernest Sackville Turner|E. S. Turner]] (1909\u20132006), freelance journalist and author, went to school in the town.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/18/pressandpublishing.obituaries ''The Guardian'', 18 July 2006, Obituary: E. S. Turner, Stalwart of Punch. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Fred Kite]] (1921\u20131993), only Second World War British soldier to receive the [[Military Medal]] three times<ref>[https://www.tracesofwar.com/persons/44073/Kite-Frederick-William-Buck.htm?c=aw TracesOfWar.com, Kite, Frederick William \"Buck\". Retrieved 8 February 2018.]</ref> \n*[[Freddie Garrity]] (1936\u20132006), singer, frontman in [[Freddie and the Dreamers]], lived in the town near the end of his life.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0308484/ IMDb Database Retrieved December 2017.]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/5000396.stm BBC News, 20 May 2006. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Jackie Trent]] (1940\u20132015), singer, songwriter and actress<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/22/jackie-trent ''The Guardian'', March 22, 2015, Jackie Trent obituary. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Neil Baldwin (Keele University)|Neil Baldwin]] (born 1946), clown, former [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] kit-man and honorary graduate of [[Keele University]]\n*[[Kevin Dunn (bishop)|Kevin John Dunn]] (1950\u20132008), twelfth Roman Catholic [[Bishop of Hexham and Newcastle]]<ref>[http://rcdhn.org.uk/rest_in_peace/formerbishops/kd/kd_bio.php The Diocese of Hexham & Newcastle, Bishop Kevin Dunn RIP]. Retrieved 8 February 2018.</ref> \n*Professor [[Alan Sinclair (scientist)|Alan Sinclair]] (born 1952), clinical scientist and diabetes specialist<ref>[https://expertfile.com/experts/profalan.jsinclair International Federation of Ageing, profile for Professor Alan Sinclair. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Dylan Waldron]] (born 1953), artist who works in traditional techniques such as painting in [[Tempera|egg tempera]] and [[silverpoint]]<ref>[http://www.dylanwaldronartist.co.uk/Biography.htm Dylan Waldron website, Biography. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Janet Bloomfield]] (1953\u20132007), peace and disarmament campaigner\n*[[Fran Unsworth]] (born 1957), journalist, head of BBC News since January 2018<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3801135/ IMDb Database]. Retrieved December 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42365321 BBC News, 15 December 2017, BBC appoints Fran Unsworth as next head of news. Retrieved 30 January 2018.]</ref>\n*[[Emma Amos (actress)|Emma Amos]] (born 1967), actress<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0025099/ IMDb Database] Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Andrew Van Buren]] (living), illusionist showman performer, co-founder of the Philip Astley Project\n*[[Hugh Dancy]], (born 1975), actor<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0199215/ IMDb Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Dan Croll]], (born 1990) singer and songwriter<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/480801c6-bd47-4d0d-b9fc-c20289529760 BBC Music, Don Croll. Retrieved 8 February 2018.]</ref>\n*[[Leon Cooke]] (born 1991), actor,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2654510/ IMDb Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> singer and dancer\n\n===Notable sports people===\n*[[Dick Ray]] (1876\u20131952) professional footballer and manager played for [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=374 SoccerBase database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Frederick Bailey (cricketer)|Frederick Bailey]] (1919\u20131985), left-handed English cricketer<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/9448.html ESPN cricinfo Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Don Ratcliffe]] (1934\u20132014), footballer who played for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]<ref>[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/donratcliffe.html Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Mike Pejic]] (born 1950), footballer for Stoke City and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]<ref>{{Citation |title=Mike Pejic |date=2019-02-13 |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mike_Pejic&oldid=883149634 |work=Wikipedia |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> \n*[[Ian Moores]] (1954\u20131998) footballer for Stoke City and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]<ref>{{Citation |title=Ian Moores |date=2018-12-10 |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ian_Moores&oldid=873064249 |work=Wikipedia |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> \n*[[Robbie Earle]] (born 1965), footballer who played for Port Vale and [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=2254 SoccerBase Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Graham Shaw (footballer, born 1967)|Graham Shaw]] (born 1967) footballer for Stoke City<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=7211 SoccerBase Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Dominic Cork]], (born 1971) cricketer<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/10816.html ESPN cricinfo Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Simon Wakefield]] (born 1974), professional golfer\n*[[Lizzie Neave]] (born 1987), slalom canoeist in women's kayak, competed in London [[2012 Summer Olympics]] \n*[[Oliver Sadler]] (born 1987), first-class cricketer\n*[[Peter Wilshaw]] (born 1987), cricketer<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/22704.html ESPN cricinfo Database]=. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Eddie Hall]] (born 1988), professional strongman<ref>[http://theworldsstrongestman.com/athletes/eddie-hall/ The World\u2019s Strongest Man website. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Danielle Wyatt]] (born 1991), professional England cricketer\n*[[Curtis Nelson]] (born 1993), footballer for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=54429 SoccerBase Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Aaron Ramsdale]] (born 1998), footballer<ref>{{Citation |title=Aaron Ramsdale |date=2019-02-03 |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Aaron_Ramsdale&oldid=881584565 |work=Wikipedia |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\n===Notable politicians===\n*[[John Merrick (MP)|Sir John Merrick]] (1584\u20131659), politician and MP from 1640 to 1648. In 1640, he was elected MP for Newcastle under Lyme in the [[Short Parliament]]. He was re-elected in 1640 for the [[Long Parliament]].<ref>[https://h2g2.com/edited_entry/A13911806 h2g2 Parliamentary Generals in the 1640s \u2013 Sir John Merrick. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Robert Needham, 2nd Viscount Kilmorey]] (1587/88\u20131653), supporter of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]. He was MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme in the [[Addled Parliament]] in 1614.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/needham-robert-15878-1653 The History of Parliament Trust, NEEDHAM, Robert (1587/8\u20131653). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Richard Leveson]] (1598\u20131661), English politician elected MP for [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle]] in the [[Long Parliament]]<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/leveson-richard-1598-1661 The History of Parliament Trust, LEVESON, Richard (1598-1661). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Samuel Terrick]] (1602\u20131675), local politician.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/terrick-samuel-1602-75 The History of Parliament Trust, TERRICK, Samuel (c. 1602-1675). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> In 1658 he went bankrupt for \u00a320,000.\n*[[Thomas Harrison (soldier)|Major-General Thomas Harrison]] (1606\u20131660) sided with Parliament in the English Civil War. In 1649 he signed the death warrant of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] and in 1660, shortly after the Restoration, he was found guilty of regicide and [[hanged, drawn and quartered]].\n*[[Richard Lloyd (Royalist)|Sir Richard Lloyd]] (1606\u20131676), English politician who sat in the House of Commons at various times between 1628 and 1676. In April 1640, Lloyd was MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme in the [[Short Parliament]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/lloyd-%28floyd%29-sir-richard-i-1606-76 The History of Parliament Trust, LLOYD (FLOYD), Sir Richard I (1606\u201376). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Alfred Seale Haslam]] (1844\u20131927) engineer, three times Mayor of Newcastle and MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1900 to 1906<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/sir-alfred-haslam/Hansard 1803\u20132005, Sir Alfred Haslam. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Josiah Wedgwood, 1st Baron Wedgwood]] (1872\u20131943), ''Josiah Wedgwood IV'', great-great-grandson of [[Josiah Wedgwood]] and Liberal MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1906 to 1919, then its Labour MP for from 1919 to 1942<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/colonel-josiah-wedgwood/HANSARD 1803\u20132005, Colonel Josiah Wedgwood. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Oswald Mosley]] (1896\u20131980), founder of the [[British Union of Fascists]] lived in [[Apedale Hall]] in the early 1900s\n*[[John Mack (British politician)|John David Mack]] (c. 1899\u20131957) was a Labour Party MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1942 to 1951.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0608846/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm IMDb Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Stephen Swingler]] (1915\u20131969) Labour MP for [[Stafford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stafford]] from 1945 to 1950 and MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1951 to 1969<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-stephen-swingler/Hansard 1803\u20132005, contributions in Parliament by Stephen Swingler. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[John Golding (British politician)|John Golding]] (1931\u20131999), Labour MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1969 to 1986<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-john-golding/ Hansard 1803\u20132005, contributions in Parliament by Mr John Golding. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Llin Golding, Baroness Golding]] (born 1933), Labour MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1986 to 2001<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mrs-llin-golding/Hansard 1803\u20132005, contributions in Parliament by Mrs Llin Golding. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Jeremy Lefroy]] (born 1959) Westlands councillor, MP for Stafford since 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/24760/jeremy_lefroy/stafford|title=Jeremy Lefroy MP, Stafford|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Paul Farrelly]] (born 1962), MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme and former journalist<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/10882/paul_farrelly/newcastle-under-lyme |title=Paul Farrelly MP, Newcastle-under-Lyme |website=TheyWorkForYou |language=en |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Karen Bradley]] (born 1970), MP for the [[Staffordshire Moorlands (UK Parliament constituency)|Staffordshire Moorlands]] and [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/24725/karen_bradley/staffordshire_moorlands |title=Karen Bradley MP, Staffordshire Moorlands |website=TheyWorkForYou |language=en |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Gareth Snell]] (born 1986), graduate of [[Keele University]] 2008, leader of the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council]] 2012\u20132014 and MP for [[Stoke-on-Trent Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent Central]] since 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/25601/gareth_snell/stoke-on-trent_central |title=Gareth Snell MP, Stoke-on-Trent Central |website=TheyWorkForYou |language=en |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Cite book |last=Jenkins |first=J G |title=A History of Newcastle-under-Lyme |year=1983 |publisher=Staffordshire County Library |id=}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Briggs |first=J |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme, 1173\u20131973 |year=1973 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |isbn=978-0-9502745-1-5}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Morris |first=Dennis |last2=Priestley |first2=Anthony |last3=Priestley |first3=Joy |last4=Simmons |first4=Roger |last5=Watkin |first5=Edward |title=The Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme : A Portrait in Old Picture Postcards |year=1987 |publisher=Brampton Publications |id=ASIN B000IBSQAW}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Adams |title=Wartime Newcastle-under-Lyme |year=1988 |publisher=Hendon Publishing Co Ltd |isbn=978-0-86067-113-8 |first=D W}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Adams |first=D W |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme as it was |year=1986 |publisher=Hendon Publishing Co Ltd |isbn=978-0-86067-106-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Newcastle-under-Lyme}}\n*{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Newcastle-under-Lyme |volume=19 |short=x}}\n*[http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/ Newcastle-under-Lyme borough council]\n\n\n{{Staffordshire}}\n{{West Midlands}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newcastle-Under-Lyme}}\n[[Category:Newcastle-under-Lyme| ]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Towns in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Newcastle upon Tyne}}\n{{about|the town|the larger local government district|Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|the constituency|Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country= England\n|official_name= Newcastle-under-Lyme\n|static_image_name= Liverpool Road, Newcastle-Under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 2101373.jpg\n|static_image_caption= \n|coordinates = {{coord|53.0109|-2.2278|display=inline,title}}\n|population= 75,082\n|population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|shire_district= [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n|shire_county= [[Staffordshire]]\n|region= West Midlands\n|constituency_westminster= [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n|post_town= NEWCASTLE<ref name=posttown>The county name is no longer required for postcoded mail and the suffix \"-under-Lyme\" is not part of the official [[Royal Mail]] name of the [[post town]], despite the potential for confusion with similarly named places.</ref>\n|postcode_district= ST5\n|postcode_area= ST\n|dial_code= 01782\n|os_grid_reference= SJ848459\n}}\n\n'''Newcastle-under-Lyme''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|nj|u\u02d0|k|\u0251\u02d0|s|\u0259l|-}} {{respell|NEW|kahss|\u0259l|-}}, locally {{IPAc-en|-|k|\u00e6|s|-}} {{respell|-kass-}};), is a [[market town]] in [[Staffordshire]], England. At the 2011 census it had a population of 75,082.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NEWCASTLE-UNDER-LYME in Staffordshire (West Midlands) Built-up Area Subdivision [url=https://www.citypopulation.de/en/uk/westmidlands/staffordshire/E35001436__newcastle_under_lyme/ |publisher=City Population |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref> It is part of the borough of [[Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|Newcastle-under-Lyme]], which had a population of 128,264 in 2016, up from 123,800 in the 2011 Census.<ref>[http://www.ukcensusdata.com/newcastle-under-lyme-e07000195#sthash.iWOL8G4y.ekwVkSxO.dpbs Wards. Retrieved 20 December 2018.]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Etymology===\nThe \"Newcastle\" part of the name derives from being the location of a new castle in the 12th century.<ref name=\"bchistory\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/leisure_content.asp?id=-A78083C8&cat=1263 |title=History of Newcastle |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=20 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321182014/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/leisure_content.asp?id=-A78083C8&cat=1263 |archivedate=21 March 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The \"Lyme\" section could refer to the [[Lyme Brook]] or (as in the family name Lindhurst) the extensive [[Forest of Lyme]] that covered the area with [[lime (tree)|lime trees]] in the [[Middle Ages]].<ref name=\"bchistory\"/><ref name=\"ekwall\">{{Cite book |title=The Concise Dictionary of English Place-names; 2nd ed. |last=Ekwall |first=Eilert |year=1940 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford |isbn= |page=294}}</ref>\n\n===12th\u201319th centuries===\nNewcastle is not mentioned in the 1086 [[Domesday Book]], as it grew up around the 12th-century castle, but it must have rapidly become a place of importance, because a [[charter]], known only through a reference in another charter to [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], was given to the town by [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] in 1173. The new castle was built to supersede an older fortress at [[Chesterton, Staffordshire|Chesterton]] about {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} to the north, the ruins of which were visible up to the end of the 16th century.\n\nIn 1235 [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] constituted it a free borough, granting a [[guild]] merchant and other privileges.<ref name=\"bchistory\" /> In 1251 he leased it under a [[fee farm grant]] to the burgesses. In 1265 Newcastle was granted by the [[The Crown|Crown]] to [[Simon de Montfort, 6th Earl of Leicester|Simon de Montfort]], and subsequently to [[Edmund Crouchback]], through whom it passed to [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]]. In [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland's]] time the castle had disappeared \"save one great Toure\".\n\n[[File:Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 2101001.jpg|thumb|Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme]]\n\nNewcastle did not feature much in the [[English Civil War]], except for a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] [[plundering]].<ref name=\"brithist\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dmhospice.org.uk/ |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme |work=British History Online |publisher=University of London & History of Parliament Trust |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref> However, it was the home town of Major General [[Thomas Harrison (soldier)|Thomas Harrison]], a [[Cromwellian]] army officer and leader of the [[Fifth Monarchy Men]].\n\nThe governing charter in 1835,<ref name=\"bchistory\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10002795&c_id=10001043 |title=Relationships / unit history of NEWCASTLE UNDER LYME |work=A Vision of Britain |publisher=[[University of Portsmouth]] Department of [[Geography]] |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930204304/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10002795&c_id=10001043 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> which created the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme Municipal Borough]], absorbed the previous borough created through the charters of 1590 and 1664, under which the title of the corporation, was the \"mayor, bailiffs and burgesses of Newcastle-under-Lyme\".<ref name=\"bchistory\" />\n\nNewcastle sent two members to Parliament from 1355 to 1885, when it lost one of the members.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/constituencies/newcastle-under-lyme The History of Parliament Trust, Newcastle-under-Lyme, Borough, from 1386 to 1481] Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\n[[File:Nelsonplace1900.jpg|right|thumb|Nelson Place and view up King Street, from a postcard, c. 1900]]\n\n===20th century===\nWhen [[Stoke-on-Trent]] was [[Federation of Stoke-on-Trent|formed by the 1910 amalgamation]] of the \"six towns\" ([[Stoke-upon-Trent|Stoke]], [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]], [[Fenton, Staffordshire|Fenton]], [[Longton, Staffordshire|Longton]], [[Burslem]] and [[Tunstall, Staffordshire|Tunstall]]), Newcastle remained separate. \n\nDespite its close proximity, it was not directly involved in the pottery industry, and it strongly opposed attempts to join the amalgamation in 1930,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Stoke-on-Trent Bill: Extension of the City |publisher=The Times |date=2 May 1930}}</ref> with a postcard poll showing residents opposing the Stoke-on-Trent Extension Bill by a majority of 97.4 per cent. Although passed by the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], the Bill was rejected by the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=\"brithist\" />\n\nFollowing the [[Local Government Act 1972]], it became the principal settlement of the Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme.\n\n===Economy===\nLike neighbouring Stoke-on-Trent, Newcastle's early economy was based around the hatting trade, silk and [[cotton mill]]s. Later [[coal mining]], [[brick]] manufacture, [[iron]] casting and [[engineering]] rose to prominence.<ref name=\"bchistory\" /> Very fine red earthenware and also [[soft-paste porcelain]] [[tableware]] (the first such production in Staffordshire) was produced in Newcastle at Samuel Bell's factory in Lower Street between 1724 and 1754, when production ceased. With the exception of a failed enterprise between 1790 and 1797, which then switched to [[brewing]], there was no further commercial production of pottery within the town of Newcastle. Production of earthenware tiles, however, continued at several locations within the borough. Manufacture of fine [[bone china]] was re-established in the borough in 1963 by [[Mayfair Pottery]] at [[Chesterton, Staffordshire|Chesterton]].\n\nThe manufacture in the borough of clay [[smoking pipe (tobacco)|tobacco-smoking pipes]] started about 1637 and grew rapidly, until it was second only to hatting as an industry. Nationally, the town ranked with [[Chester]], [[York]] and [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] as the four major pipe producers. The industry continued until the mid-19th century, when decline set in rapidly, so that by 1881 there was only one tobacco-pipe maker left.\n\nIn the 17th, 18th and 19th centuries, the town had a flourishing [[felt]] hat manufacturing industry,<ref name=\"bchistory\" /> which was probably at its peak locally in the 1820s, when a third of the town's population were involved in over 20 factories, but by 1892 there was only one manufacturer still in production.\n\nIn 1944, the [[Rolls-Royce Derwent]] engine for the [[Gloster Meteor]] fighter was made in the borough.\n\nNewcastle's 20th-century industries include: iron-working, construction materials, clothing (especially military, police and transport uniforms), computers, publishing, electric motors and machinery.\n\nNear the turn of the 20th and 21st centuries, the town received major redevelopment to incorporate a new street (Castle Walk) into the town centre, providing Newcastle with a new [[bus station]] and bringing in more companies. Various business centres in the town provide offices for companies that operate in the service sector.\n\n===Politicians===\n[[File:Vera Brittain.jpg|thumb|Vera Brittain]]\nThe town has been the birthplace of several notable politicians and activists. [[Fanny Deakin]] was a campaigner for better nourishment for babies and young children and better maternity care for mothers. The former [[chairwoman]] of [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]] ([[CND]]), [[Janet Bloomfield]] (n\u00e9e Hood) is a peace and disarmament campaigner. [[Vera Brittain]]  writer, [[feminist]] (and mother of [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Shirley Williams]]) was born in the town.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXA203-A77FA129 |title=Vera Brittain 1893\u20131970 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901100123/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=SXA203-A77FA129 |archivedate=1 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThere have been two particularly notable [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] (MPs). [[Josiah Wedgwood, 1st Baron Wedgwood|Josiah Wedgwood IV]] was a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]], Independent and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP, who served as [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] in the [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] of [[Ramsay MacDonald]], in the first ever Labour government. He was an MP from 1909 to 1942. [[John Golding (British politician)|John Golding]] was elected a Labour MP for [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]] at a by-election in 1969. He served in the governments of [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Jim Callaghan]], as PPS to [[Eric Varley]] as [[Minister of Technology]], a Labour whip in opposition, and Minister for Employment, stepping down in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,,322315,00.html |title=Right at the heart of Labour |work=Guardian Unlimited |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |first=Paul |last=Farrelly |date=22 January 1999 |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe current MP is [[Aaron Bell (politician)|Aaron Bell]].\n\n===Transport===\nThe town was once served by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]], its station being on a branch line from [[Stoke-on-Trent]] via Newcastle, [[Silverdale, Staffordshire|Silverdale]] and [[Keele]], to [[Market Drayton]] in [[Shropshire]]. [[Newcastle-under-Lyme railway station]] opened in September 1852, after numerous construction difficulties involving the two tunnels of {{convert|605|yd|m}} and {{convert|96|yd|m}} respectively at Hartshill. There were also two halts to the west of Newcastle railway station, located at [[Brampton Halt railway station|Brampton]] and [[Liverpool Road Halt railway station|Liverpool Road]].<ref name=\"Christiansen\">{{cite book |last2=Miller |first2=R. W. |last=Christiansen |first=Rex |year=1971 |title=The North Staffordshire Railway |page=124 |publisher=David & Charles |isbn=0-7153-5121-4}}</ref>\n\nThe section from [[Silverdale (Staffordshire) railway station|Silverdale]] to [[Market Drayton railway station|Market Drayton]] closed to passengers in May 1956 and the rest of the line in March 1964. Only small sections remained from Madeley to Silverdale, and from Silverdale to Holditch, for coal traffic from the local collieries. The line from Newcastle Junction to Silverdale has been removed, with the site of Newcastle railway station and the Hartshill tunnels being filled in.\n\nNewcastle was on the national [[canal]] network, but the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme Canal]], running from the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]] at Stoke-on-Trent to [[Sir Nigel Gresley's Canal]] has been disused since 1935 and most of it filled in.\n\nToday the town relies on buses for its public transport. [[FirstGroup]] runs a network of services connecting Newcastle to the towns of [[The Potteries Urban Area|the Potteries]] as well as [[Stafford]] whilst Arriva buses run to [[Shrewsbury]] via [[Market Drayton]]\n\n==Geography==\nSituated in a valley alongside the [[Lyme Brook]], the town is immediately west of the neighbouring city of [[Stoke-on-Trent]], its [[suburb]]s running into those of the city. Newcastle town centre is less than {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} from [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Stoke-on-Trent City Centre]] and about {{convert|17|mi|km|0}} north of the [[county town]] of [[Stafford]].\n\n===Green belt===\n{{main|Stoke-on-Trent Green Belt}}\nNewcastle and Stoke form the [[Stoke-on-Trent Built-up Area|main urban area]] at the centre of the Stoke-on-Trent Green Belt, which is an [[environmental policy|environmental]] and [[Planning in the United Kingdom|planning]] area that regulates the rural space in Staffordshire,<ref name=\"new-staffs-belt\"/> to prevent [[urban sprawl]] and minimise convergence with outlying settlements. First defined in 1967,<ref name=\"new-staffs-belt\">{{cite web |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council and Stoke-on-Trent City Council Green Belt Assessment Final Report Issue \u2013 21 November 2017 |url=https://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/sites/default/files/IMCE/Planning/Planning_Policy/Newc_Stoke_GBA_Final_Report_21_11_17.pdf |website=www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk}}</ref> most of the area extends into the wider borough, but there are some landscape features and places of interest within that are covered or surrounded by the designation. They include the Michelin Sports Facility, Newcastle golf course, Keele University, Apedale Winding Wheel, Watermills Chimney, and [[Bignall Hill]]. The [[West Coast Main Line]] forms the western boundary of the green belt.\n\n==Demography==\n{{for|district-wide demographic details|Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)}}<!--Only include info about the town, not the Borough-->\n{| id=\"toc\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 2em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"3\"\n!colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |'''Comparative Census Information'''\n|-\n|'''[[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 UK Census]]'''||'''Newcastle-under-Lyme'''||'''[[Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|Borough]]'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22530/nbcEconomic1.pdf |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme Economic Profile |format=PDF |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=21 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201401/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22530/nbcEconomic1.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22519/nbcSocial1.pdf |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme Social Profile |format=PDF |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=21 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201903/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22519/nbcSocial1.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>||'''England'''\n|-\n|Total population||73,944||122,030||49,138,831\n|-\n|White||97.8%||98%||91%\n|-\n|Asian||0.6%||0.6%||4.6%\n|-\n|Black||0.2%||0.2%||2.3%\n|-\n|Christian||78.2%||78.5%||72%\n|-\n|Muslim||0.7%||0.5%||3.1%\n|-\n|Hindu||0.2%||0.2%||1.1%\n|-\n|No religion||14%||13.1%||15%\n|-\n<!-- |Bachelor's degree or higher||12%||20%||20% -->\n|-\n|Unemployed||2.3%||2%||3.3%\n|}\nOf the 73,944 residents recorded in the 2001 census, 51.7 per cent (38,210) were female and 48.3 per cent (35,734) male.<ref name=\"social\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22571/NewcastleSocial.pdf |title=2001 Census \u2013 Social Profile for Towns in Staffordshire \u2013 Newcastle-under-Lyme |format=PDF |publisher=Staffordshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201910/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22571/NewcastleSocial.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Of these, 78.2 per cent (57,819) stated that their religion was [[Christians|Christian]], and 12.9 per cent (9,570) said they had no religion. [[Islam]], [[Judaism]], [[Buddhism]] and [[Sikhism]] each covered less than 1 per cent of the population. Racially, 97.8 per cent of the population defined themselves as [[white people|white]], with the balance being [[Multiracial|mixed race]] (0.6 per cent), [[India]]n (0.4 per cent), [[Pakistan]]i (0.2 per cent), [[black people|black]] (0.2 per cent), [[Chinese people|Chinese]] (0.2 per cent), and other ethnic groups 0.4 per cent.<ref name=\"social\" />\n\nIn employment, 62.2 per cent (21,586) of the population work [[Full-time job|full-time]] and 19.4 per cent (6,746) [[Part-time job|part time]].<ref name=\"economic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22589/Newcastleeconomic.pdf |title=2001 Census \u2013 Economic Profile for Towns in Staffordshire \u2013 Newcastle-under-Lyme |format=PDF |publisher=Staffordshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201417/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/8541174C-7ECB-4763-9BDE-A9819AE6E865/22589/Newcastleeconomic.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The largest employment types are [[manufacturing]] with 7,058 (21.5 per cent), [[wholesale]] and [[retail]] 6,157 (18.7 per cent), [[health]] and [[social work]] 4,097 (12.5 per cent) and [[finance]], [[real estate]] and [[business]] activity 3,823 (11.6 per cent).<ref name=\"economic\" />\n\n[[Jewish]] residency of the area stretches back into the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/JCR-UK/Community/stoke/history.htm |title=Stoke-on-Trent Hebrew Congregation |accessdate=21 January 2007}}</ref> In 1873 the community purchased an old [[Wales|Welsh]] [[chapel]] to be used as a [[synagogue]]. In 1923 a new synagogue was built in Hanley. This was closed in 2004 and the [[Wiktionary:Congregation|congregation]] moved to a smaller synagogue in Newcastle.<ref>[http://jscn.org.uk/small-communities/stoke-on-trent-and-nortstaffordshire-hebrew-congregation/ Stoke-on-Trent and North Staffordshire Hebrew Congregation website] retrieved Jan 2017</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:A34 road Newcastle-under-Lyme.jpg|thumb|The [[A34 road (England)|A34]] London Road]]\nNewcastle-under-Lyme is served by the [[M6 motorway]] to the south and west of Newcastle and by the [[A500 road]] to the north and east. There are access points from the M6 at junctions 15 and 16, to the south and north respectively. The [[A34 road (England)|A34]] [[trunk road]] runs through Newcastle from north to south and was the main road between [[Birmingham]] and [[Manchester]] until the [[M6 motorway]] opened. There is a large bus station in the town centre.\n\n[[File:Newcastle-Under-Lyme station site.jpg|thumb|Newcastle-Under-Lyme station site, now Stations Walk.]]\n[[Newcastle-under-Lyme railway station]], which was not within the town but towards Water Street on the [[Stoke to Market Drayton Line]], closed in 1964 under the [[Beeching cuts]]. The line from Silverdale to Pipe Gate remained open to serve Silverdale Colliery and a creamery at Pipe Gate until 1998, when the line closed to all stone and mineral traffic. It now forms part of a green way from Silverdale to Newcastle-Under-Lyme, with the station site being called \"Station Walks\". The nearest station to the town is [[Stoke-on-Trent railway station]] which is between the town centre of Newcastle and city centre of Stoke-on-Trent and serves the Potteries as a whole. The loss of the railway station has made Newcastle Under Lyme the third largest town without a railway station.\n\nMost of the bus network is run by [[First Potteries]] Limited and [[D&G Bus]].\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|Keele University}}\n\nThe town also has an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]]: [[Newcastle-under-Lyme School]], which was established in the 17th century, whose alumni includes [[T. E. Hulme]], [[John Wain]] and [[William Watkiss Lloyd]]. It also has a number of [[primary school|primary]] and [[secondary school]]s in the [[state school|state-funded sector]]. The latter include [[Newcastle Academy|Newcastle Community Academy]], [[Clayton Hall Academy]], [[St John Fisher Catholic College]], [[Sir Thomas Boughey High School]] and [[Wolstanton High School]]. There is also a private [https://www.edenhurst.co.uk Edenhurst Preparatory School], founded in 1961. \n\nThe town's largest sixth form college is [[Newcastle-under-Lyme College]], which was established in the 1966. \n\n[[Keele University]] main campus is situated {{convert|3|mi|km|0}} from the centre of the town.\n\n==Sites and attractions==\n===Parks and gardens===\n[[File:Queens gardens newcastle under lyme.jpg|thumb|Queen's Gardens]]\nNewcastle excels in the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] [[Britain in Bloom]] competition. In 2005 it was national winner in the \"small city/large town\" category (35K\u2013100K).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhs.org.uk/britaininbloom/heart_of_england/newcastlewinner2005.asp |publisher=Royal Horticultural Society |work=Britain in Bloom |title=2005 winners |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612114448/http://www.rhs.org.uk/britaininbloom/heart_of_england/newcastlewinner2005.asp |archivedate=12 June 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The town features several parks, including the Queen's Gardens at the eastern end of Ironmarket, which won the Britain in Bloom Judges' Award for Horticultural Excellence in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXFBE1-A77F7BB2&cat=325 |title=Britain in Bloom |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210033010/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXFBE1-A77F7BB2&cat=325 |archivedate=10 December 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Queens Gardens now contains a statue of [[Queen Victoria]] funded by Sir [[Alfred Seale Haslam]] and unveiled by [[Grand Duke Michael Mikhailovich of Russia]] on 5 November 1903. It is the only park within the [[ring road]].\n\nGrosvenor Gardens is in the centre of one of the town's roundabouts, but hidden away below road level. Queen Elizabeth Garden is located outside the town centre and was due for refurbishment using [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery Heritage Fund]] money.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/6439721.stm |title=Lottery cash to restore town park |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=6 May 2007 |date=11 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nTo the north west of the town centre is Brampton Park, home to a museum and art gallery.<ref>[https://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/all-services/sport-and-culture/brampton-museum/brampton-park Borough Council website, Brampton Park] retrieved Jan 2017</ref>\n\n===Traditional market===<!-- This section is linked from [[The Stones (market)]] -->\n[[File:Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 2101001.jpg|thumb|Ironmarket, Newcastle-Under-Lyme]]\nDating back to 1173 Newcastle's [[market (place)|market]], known as the Stones, operates on the High Street.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=-A77F7A70 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |title=Markets and Town Centres Information |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210033015/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=-A77F7A70 |archivedate=10 December 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The market was originally held on Sunday; in the reign of [[John of England|John]] it was changed to Saturday; by the charter of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]] it was fixed on Monday. Grants of fairs were given by [[Edward I of England|Edward I]], [[Edward III of England|Edward III]] and [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]].\n\nToday the market is open six days a week, and there are over 80 stalls. Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays see a general market, on Tuesdays there is an [[antique]]s market and Thursdays are for the sale of bric-a-brac. A [[cattle]] and [[livestock]] market was held on Mondays until the early 1990s; the site of the cattle market is now a branch of Morrison's supermarket.\n\n[[File:Guildhall newcastle under lyme.jpg|thumb|left|The Guildhall]]\n\n===The Guildhall===\nThe current Guildhall was built in 1713 and has undergone a number of changes.<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/023.htm Website of Potteries.org \u2013 Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries Retrieved February 2017] has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative on The Guildhall, Newcastle.</ref> Originally the ground floor was open and was used for markets, until the Market Hall was built in 1854. In 1860, in order to provide more space, the ground floor arches were bricked up and clock tower with four clocks were added. The top rooms in the Guildhall were used for meetings by the Borough council and its committees, until 1860. It is now a grade II listed building.\n\n===The Barracks===\nThe Italian styled Militia Barracks were built in 1855 from red brick. They were the headquarters of the 3rd King's Own Staffordshire Rifle Regiment until 1880. In 1882 W. H. Dalton bought the Barracks and settled them in trust for use by the Rifle Volunteers of Newcastle, which became the Territorial Force in 1907. In 2002 the Barracks were let to small businesses.<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/022.htm Website of Potteries.org - Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries Retrieved Feb 2017] This has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative about the Barracks.</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Newcastle-under-Lyme Museum & Art Gallery (1).jpg|thumb|Newcastle-under-Lyme Museum & Art Gallery]]\nThe [[New Vic Theatre]] was Europe's first purpose-built [[theatre in the round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newvictheatre.org.uk/about/about.html |publisher=New Vic Theatre |title=History of the New Vic theatre |accessdate=5 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928011242/http://www.newvictheatre.org.uk/about/about.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=28 September 2007}}</ref> Just outside the town centre, it offers a programme of entertainment that includes modern or classic plays and concert performances.\n\nThe Borough Museum and Art Gallery (Brampton Museum) depicts the civic history of the Borough of Newcastle under Lyme and an authentic, life-size [[Victorian era|Victorian]] street-scene whilst the art gallery hosts work by local and national artists as well as travelling exhibitions.<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/026.htm Website of Potteries.org - Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries Retrieved Feb 2017] This has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative about Newcastle-under-Lyme Museum.</ref><ref>[https://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/all-services/sport-and-culture/brampton-museum Brampton Museum on town's website] retrieved Jan 2017</ref> \n\nNotable residents who contributed to the arts and entertainment include [[Philip Astley]], founder of the modern circus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/General.asp?id=SXA16E-A77F9F88 |title=Philip Astley 1742\u20131814 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070902001318/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=SXA16E-A77F9F88 |archivedate=2 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Jackie Trent]], the singer and songwriter, was born in the town.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jackie-trent.org.uk/biog.html |title=Jackie Trent Biography |accessdate=6 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501203152/http://www.jackie-trent.org.uk/biog.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 May 2007}}</ref> [[Arnold Bennett]], the novelist, playwright, and essayist, completed his schooling at the Middle School,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/bennett.htm |title=Arnold Bennett Profile |work=Literary Heritage |publisher=Shropshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503012007/http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/bennett.htm |archivedate=3 May 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and called the town Oldcastle in his ''[[Clayhanger]]'' trilogy of novels. [[Dinah Maria Mulock]], who wrote under her married name of Mrs Craik, lived in the town (in Lower Street and Mount Pleasant) and attended Brampton House Academy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/craik.htm |title=Dinah Craik |work=Literary Heritage |publisher=Shropshire County Council |accessdate=6 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701151408/http://www3.shropshire-cc.gov.uk/craik.htm |archivedate=1 July 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[E. S. Turner]], social commentator, was educated in the town.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/07/17/db1701.xml |title=ES Turner Obituary |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited |date=17 July 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref> Newcastle was also home to Dr Philip Willoughby-Higson (1933\u20132012), poet, translator and historian, and author of 33 books. He was founder and president (1974\u20131992) of the Chester Poets, the oldest poetry group in the North West, and President of the Baudelaire Society of France from 1992 to 2012 \u2013 the only Englishman ever to receive that position.\n\nHistorically, the town had a tradition of festivities marking the start of a new [[municipal year]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Sport==\nThe wide range of sports clubs and associations includes [[Newcastle Town F.C.]], an [[association football]] club currently playing in the Northern Premier League First Division South. \n\nThe largest rugby union club is Newcastle Staffs Rugby Union Club.\n\nCycle Staffordshire organises many local cycling events, as does the Newcastle [[Track cycling|Track Cycling]] Association. The town has a [[velodrome]] used by the Lyme Racing Club,<ref>[http://www.lymeracingclub.co.uk/ Lyme Racing Club website] retrieved Jan 2017</ref> which has over 150 members, including an increasing junior membership. It is active in many areas, including time trials, track racing, road racing, Audax riding, mountain biking, and regular Sunday Club runs and general leisure cycling.\n[[File:Newcastle Golf Club - Clubhouse - geograph.org.uk - 407961.jpg|thumb|Newcastle Golf Club]]\nNewcastle Athletic Club<ref>[http://newcastlestaffsac.org.uk/information/who-we-are/ Newcastle (Staffs) AC website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref> is based at the Ashfield Road track next to Newcastle College. This ash track was constructed in 1964. The club competes in the North Staffs XC League and the Local, National and Heart of England League 3.\n\nThe town is home to one of the most prominent volleyball clubs in England, [[Newcastle (Staffs) Volleyball Club]]. Established in 1980, it has teams playing in the National Volleyball League, producing numerous England and Great Britain international players over the years. \n\nNewcastle under Lyme College is home to Castle Korfball Club, one of the nation's oldest such clubs.<ref>[http://www.castlekorfball.co.uk Castle Korfball Club website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref>\n\nThe town has a successful swimming club; Newcastle (Staffs) Swimming Club, which was founded in 1908.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastleasc.net/ |title=Newcastle (Staffs) ASC {{!}} Newcastle Staffs Amateur Swimming Club, founded 1908 |language=en-GB |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThere are golf courses at Kidsgrove, Wolstanton, Keele and Westlands.<ref>[http://www.newcastlegolfclub.co.uk/index.php/en/ Newcastle Golf Club website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.wolstantongolfclub.co.uk/ Wolstanton Golf Clubwebsite] Retrieved January 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.keelegolfrange.co.uk/drivingrange/ Keele Golf Range website] Retrieved January 2017.</ref>\n\nKeele University is home to one of the UK's first [[quidditch]] teams, the Keele Squirrels.<ref> [https://keelesu.com/activities/society/quidditch/ Keele university quidditch society website] retrieved April 2018 </ref>. It hosted the first ever quidditch game in the UK in 2011 against the [[Leicester]] Thestrals.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Giles' Church Street Newcastle-under-Lyme - geograph.org.uk - 558236.jpg|thumb|left|St Giles' Church, Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\nThe town was the birthplace of [[John James Blunt]], a [[Anglicanism#Anglican divines|divine]] and [[Anglican]] priest. [[Josiah Wedgwood]] was a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] and he and his family attended meetings at the Old Meeting House, adjacent to St Giles' Church, which is still in use for the purpose.\n\nThe town has a large number of Anglican churches, including St Giles, the medieval parish church dating from 1290.<ref>[http://www.stgilesnewcastle.org.uk/ Website of The Parish Church of St Giles] Retrieved January 2017.</ref> There are several [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] churches, notably Holy Trinity,<ref>[http://www.thepotteries.org/tour/021.htm Website of Potteries.org - Neville Malkin's \"Grand Tour\" of the Potteries. Retrieved February 2017.] This has several old pictures, drawings and historical narrative about Holy Trinity Church, Newcastle,</ref><ref>[http://www.holytrinitynewcastle.org.uk/parish-history Website of Holy Trinity Catholic Church, Newcastle Retrieved January 2017.]</ref> whose style is [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] in blue engineering bricks, described as \"''the finest modern specimen of ornamental brickwork in the kingdom\"'' at the time.\n[[File:Jewish cemetery and Synagogue - geograph.org.uk - 335713.jpg|thumb|Jewish cemetery and Synagogue on the A34]]\nIn the 18th century [[John Wesley]] made repeated visits to the area, which was becoming industrialised, and recruited many residents to [[Methodism]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepotteries.org/history/spiritual_history.html |title=The Christian History of Stoke-on-Trent |accessdate=6 May 2007}}</ref> This is reflected in a large number of [[Methodist]] churches.<ref>[http://www.northstaffordshiremethodists.org.uk/churches/church-profiles/newcastle-methodist-church.php Newcastle Methodist Church Circuit website Retrieved January 2017].</ref> There is a [[Baptist]] church in [[Clayton, Staffordshire|Clayton]].<ref>[http://www.newcastlebaptist.org.uk/ Newcastle Baptist Church website Retrieved January 2017.]</ref>\n\nOf interest also is [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church), across from the Brampton Park, which serves as the \"[[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|Stake Centre]]\" for the church in the region and has an on-site [[Family History Center (LDS Church)|Family History Centre]], where the public can research their ancestry at little or no charge.\n\n==International network==\nThe town is part of a worldwide network of towns and cities with the name [[Newcastle (disambiguation)|Newcastle]]<!--intentional link to DAB page-->.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/stoke/content/articles/2006/08/11/newcastle_under_lyme_towns_feature.shtml |publisher=BBC Stoke |title=Towns and Villages - Newcastle-under-Lyme |accessdate=6 May 2007}}.</ref> These include well-known [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] (also in England), [[Neuburg an der Donau]] (Germany), [[Neuch\u00e2tel]] (Switzerland), [[Neufch\u00e2teau, Vosges|Neufch\u00e2teau]] (France), [[New Castle, Indiana]] (US), [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]] (US), [[New Castle, Delaware]] (US), [[Newcastle, KwaZulu-Natal]] (South Africa) and [[Shinshiro]] (Japan).\n\nThis small international network of eight towns, formed in 1998, is designed to encourage friendship and cooperation between them. Accordingly, a school in the South African town benefited in 2004 from gifts of computing equipment surplus to Newcastle-under-Lyme's needs. The annual ''Newcastles of the World'' Summit was held in Newcastle-under-Lyme for six days from 17 June 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/newsarticle.asp?id=SX9F7A-A7801EF2 |title=Warm welcome for summit delegates |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |date=15 June 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311045229/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/newsarticle.asp?id=SX9F7A-A7801EF2 |archivedate=11 March 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n*[[Neuburg an der Donau]], Germany\n*[[Neuch\u00e2tel]], Switzerland\n*[[Neufch\u00e2teau, Vosges|Neufch\u00e2teau]], France\n*[[New Castle, Delaware]], United States\n*[[New Castle, Indiana]], United States\n\n*[[New Castle, Pennsylvania]], United States\n*[[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n*[[Shinshiro]], Japan\n*[[Newcastle, KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa\n\n==Notable people==\n===Earlier centuries===\n*[[Humphrey Wollrich]] (1633\u20131707), Quaker writer<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Wolrich,_Humphrey_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900, Volume 62, Wolrich, Humphrey. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Philip Astley]] (1742\u20131814), equestrian, circus owner, inventor and father of the modern circus<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/2929565.stm BBC News Channel, Tuesday, 8 April, 2003. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Silvester Harding]] (1745\u20131809), artist and publisher, who aged 14 ran away and joined a company of strolling actors<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Harding,_Silvester_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900, Volume 24, Harding, Silvester. Retrieved December 2017].</ref> \n*[[John James Blunt]] (1794\u20131855), Anglican priest. His writings included studies of the early Church.<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop\u00e6dia_Britannica/Blunt,_John_James 1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Volume 4 Blunt, John James. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref><ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Blunt,_John_James_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 5, Blunt, John James. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n*[[Henry Moseley (mathematician)|Henry Moseley]] (1801\u20131872), churchman, mathematician, and scientist<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Moseley,_Henry_(1801-1872)_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 39, Moseley, Henry (1801-1872). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Joseph Mayer (antiquary)|Joseph Mayer]] (1803\u20131886), goldsmith, antiquary and collector<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Mayer,_Joseph_(DNB00) Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 37, Mayer, Joseph. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Emma Darwin|Emma Darwin (n\u00e9e Wedgwood)]] (1808\u20131896), granddaughter of [[Josiah Wedgwood]] and wife of [[Charles Darwin]]<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6532176 Emma Darwin at Find a Grave. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Hungerford Crewe, 3rd Baron Crewe]] [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1812\u20131894), landowner and peer, inherited the Jacobean mansion of [[Crewe Hall]] and unsuccessfully opposed the construction of a Silverdale and Madeley Railway Company line<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p23241.htm The Peerage.com website, Hungerford Crewe, 3rd Baron Crewe] Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n\n*Sir [[Oliver Lodge]] (1851\u20131940), physicist, inventor and writer<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop\u00e6dia_Britannica/Lodge,_Sir_Oliver_Joseph 1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Volume 16, Lodge, Sir Oliver Joseph. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Arthur Heath|Arthur Howard Heath]] TD (1856\u20131930), industrialist, cricketer, Rugby Union international and local Conservative MP<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-arthur-heath-1 HANSARD 1803\u20132005, Mr Arthur Heath. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Joseph Cook]], GCMG, PC (1860 in Silverdale \u2013 1947), worked in the local coalmines and emigrated to Australia in 1885; Prime Minister of Australia from 1913 to 1914<ref>[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cook-sir-joseph-5763 Australian Dictionary of Biography, Cook, Sir Joseph (1860\u20131947) Retrieved 11 February 2018.]</ref> \n*[[Grand Duke Michael Mikhailovich of Russia]], (1861\u20131929), lived in [[Keele Hall]] from 1900 to 1909.<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27331/page/4569 The London Gazette, publication date: 9 July 1901, Issue:27331, Page:4569. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Arnold Bennett]] (1867\u20131931), writer<ref>[http://biography.yourdictionary.com/arnold-bennett YourDictionary Arnold Bennett, Facts. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Ada Nield Chew]] (1870\u20131945), suffragist\n*[[Alfred Herbert Richardson]] (1874\u20131951), policeman and Chief Constable of Newcastle-under-Lyme 1901/1903\n*[[Oliver W. F. Lodge|Oliver William Foster Lodge]] (1878\u20131955), poet and author born in Newcastle\n*[[Fanny Deakin]] (1883\u20131968), local politician born in Silverdale, who campaigned to improve nourishment of children and maternity care for mothers.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070902001036/http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/general.asp?id=SXEA55-A77FA208 Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council, 15 June 2004, Fanny Deakin 1883-1968. Retrieved December 2017].</ref>\n*[[Vera Brittain]] (1893\u20131970), author, reformer and pacifist, and mother of [[Shirley Williams]]<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/aug/30/featuresreviews.guardianreview18 The Guardian, 30 August 2003, The making of a peacenik, Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Reginald Mitchell]] (1895\u20131937), aeroplane designer of the [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]<ref>[http://www.rjmitchell-spitfire.co.uk/aboutrjmitchell/index.asp?sectionID=1 RJ Mitchell website, A life in aviation. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n*[[Ernest Sackville Turner|E. S. Turner]] (1909\u20132006), freelance journalist and author, went to school in the town.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/18/pressandpublishing.obituaries ''The Guardian'', 18 July 2006, Obituary: E. S. Turner, Stalwart of Punch. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Fred Kite]] (1921\u20131993), only Second World War British soldier to receive the [[Military Medal]] three times<ref>[https://www.tracesofwar.com/persons/44073/Kite-Frederick-William-Buck.htm?c=aw TracesOfWar.com, Kite, Frederick William \"Buck\". Retrieved 8 February 2018.]</ref> \n*[[Freddie Garrity]] (1936\u20132006), singer, frontman in [[Freddie and the Dreamers]], lived in the town near the end of his life.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0308484/ IMDb Database Retrieved December 2017.]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/5000396.stm BBC News, 20 May 2006. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Jackie Trent]] (1940\u20132015), singer, songwriter and actress<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/22/jackie-trent ''The Guardian'', March 22, 2015, Jackie Trent obituary. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Neil Baldwin (Keele University)|Neil Baldwin]] (born 1946), clown, former [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] kit-man and honorary graduate of [[Keele University]]\n*[[Kevin Dunn (bishop)|Kevin John Dunn]] (1950\u20132008), twelfth Roman Catholic [[Bishop of Hexham and Newcastle]]<ref>[http://rcdhn.org.uk/rest_in_peace/formerbishops/kd/kd_bio.php The Diocese of Hexham & Newcastle, Bishop Kevin Dunn RIP]. Retrieved 8 February 2018.</ref> \n*Professor [[Alan Sinclair (scientist)|Alan Sinclair]] (born 1952), clinical scientist and diabetes specialist<ref>[https://expertfile.com/experts/profalan.jsinclair International Federation of Ageing, profile for Professor Alan Sinclair. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Dylan Waldron]] (born 1953), artist who works in traditional techniques such as painting in [[Tempera|egg tempera]] and [[silverpoint]]<ref>[http://www.dylanwaldronartist.co.uk/Biography.htm Dylan Waldron website, Biography. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Janet Bloomfield]] (1953\u20132007), peace and disarmament campaigner\n*[[Fran Unsworth]] (born 1957), journalist, head of BBC News since January 2018<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3801135/ IMDb Database]. Retrieved December 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42365321 BBC News, 15 December 2017, BBC appoints Fran Unsworth as next head of news. Retrieved 30 January 2018.]</ref>\n*[[Emma Amos (actress)|Emma Amos]] (born 1967), actress<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0025099/ IMDb Database] Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Andrew Van Buren]] (living), illusionist showman performer, co-founder of the Philip Astley Project\n*[[Hugh Dancy]], (born 1975), actor<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0199215/ IMDb Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Dan Croll]], (born 1990) singer and songwriter<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/480801c6-bd47-4d0d-b9fc-c20289529760 BBC Music, Don Croll. Retrieved 8 February 2018.]</ref>\n*[[Leon Cooke]] (born 1991), actor,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2654510/ IMDb Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> singer and dancer\n\n===Notable sports people===\n*[[Dick Ray]] (1876\u20131952) professional footballer and manager played for [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=374 SoccerBase database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Frederick Bailey (cricketer)|Frederick Bailey]] (1919\u20131985), left-handed English cricketer<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/9448.html ESPN cricinfo Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Don Ratcliffe]] (1934\u20132014), footballer who played for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]<ref>[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/donratcliffe.html Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Mike Pejic]] (born 1950), footballer for Stoke City and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]<ref>{{Citation |title=Mike Pejic |date=2019-02-13 |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mike_Pejic&oldid=883149634 |work=Wikipedia |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> \n*[[Ian Moores]] (1954\u20131998) footballer for Stoke City and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]<ref>{{Citation |title=Ian Moores |date=2018-12-10 |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ian_Moores&oldid=873064249 |work=Wikipedia |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> \n*[[Robbie Earle]] (born 1965), footballer who played for Port Vale and [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=2254 SoccerBase Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Graham Shaw (footballer, born 1967)|Graham Shaw]] (born 1967) footballer for Stoke City<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=7211 SoccerBase Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Dominic Cork]], (born 1971) cricketer<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/10816.html ESPN cricinfo Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Simon Wakefield]] (born 1974), professional golfer\n*[[Lizzie Neave]] (born 1987), slalom canoeist in women's kayak, competed in London [[2012 Summer Olympics]] \n*[[Oliver Sadler]] (born 1987), first-class cricketer\n*[[Peter Wilshaw]] (born 1987), cricketer<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/22704.html ESPN cricinfo Database]=. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Eddie Hall]] (born 1988), professional strongman<ref>[http://theworldsstrongestman.com/athletes/eddie-hall/ The World\u2019s Strongest Man website. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Danielle Wyatt]] (born 1991), professional England cricketer\n*[[Curtis Nelson]] (born 1993), footballer for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=54429 SoccerBase Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Aaron Ramsdale]] (born 1998), footballer<ref>{{Citation |title=Aaron Ramsdale |date=2019-02-03 |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Aaron_Ramsdale&oldid=881584565 |work=Wikipedia |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\n===Notable politicians===\n*[[John Merrick (MP)|Sir John Merrick]] (1584\u20131659), politician and MP from 1640 to 1648. In 1640, he was elected MP for Newcastle under Lyme in the [[Short Parliament]]. He was re-elected in 1640 for the [[Long Parliament]].<ref>[https://h2g2.com/edited_entry/A13911806 h2g2 Parliamentary Generals in the 1640s \u2013 Sir John Merrick. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Robert Needham, 2nd Viscount Kilmorey]] (1587/88\u20131653), supporter of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]. He was MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme in the [[Addled Parliament]] in 1614.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/needham-robert-15878-1653 The History of Parliament Trust, NEEDHAM, Robert (1587/8\u20131653). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Richard Leveson]] (1598\u20131661), English politician elected MP for [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle]] in the [[Long Parliament]]<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/leveson-richard-1598-1661 The History of Parliament Trust, LEVESON, Richard (1598-1661). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> \n*[[Samuel Terrick]] (1602\u20131675), local politician.<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/terrick-samuel-1602-75 The History of Parliament Trust, TERRICK, Samuel (c. 1602-1675). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref> In 1658 he went bankrupt for \u00a320,000.\n*[[Thomas Harrison (soldier)|Major-General Thomas Harrison]] (1606\u20131660) sided with Parliament in the English Civil War. In 1649 he signed the death warrant of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] and in 1660, shortly after the Restoration, he was found guilty of regicide and [[hanged, drawn and quartered]].\n*[[Richard Lloyd (Royalist)|Sir Richard Lloyd]] (1606\u20131676), English politician who sat in the House of Commons at various times between 1628 and 1676. In April 1640, Lloyd was MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme in the [[Short Parliament]].<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/lloyd-%28floyd%29-sir-richard-i-1606-76 The History of Parliament Trust, LLOYD (FLOYD), Sir Richard I (1606\u201376). Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Alfred Seale Haslam]] (1844\u20131927) engineer, three times Mayor of Newcastle and MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1900 to 1906<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/sir-alfred-haslam/Hansard 1803\u20132005, Sir Alfred Haslam. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Josiah Wedgwood, 1st Baron Wedgwood]] (1872\u20131943), ''Josiah Wedgwood IV'', great-great-grandson of [[Josiah Wedgwood]] and Liberal MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1906 to 1919, then its Labour MP for from 1919 to 1942<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/colonel-josiah-wedgwood/HANSARD 1803\u20132005, Colonel Josiah Wedgwood. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*Sir [[Oswald Mosley]] (1896\u20131980), founder of the [[British Union of Fascists]] lived in [[Apedale Hall]] in the early 1900s\n*[[John Mack (British politician)|John David Mack]] (c. 1899\u20131957) was a Labour Party MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1942 to 1951.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0608846/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm IMDb Database. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Stephen Swingler]] (1915\u20131969) Labour MP for [[Stafford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stafford]] from 1945 to 1950 and MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1951 to 1969<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-stephen-swingler/Hansard 1803\u20132005, contributions in Parliament by Stephen Swingler. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[John Golding (British politician)|John Golding]] (1931\u20131999), Labour MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1969 to 1986<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-john-golding/ Hansard 1803\u20132005, contributions in Parliament by Mr John Golding. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Llin Golding, Baroness Golding]] (born 1933), Labour MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme from 1986 to 2001<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mrs-llin-golding/Hansard 1803\u20132005, contributions in Parliament by Mrs Llin Golding. Retrieved December 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Jeremy Lefroy]] (born 1959) Westlands councillor, MP for Stafford since 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/24760/jeremy_lefroy/stafford|title=Jeremy Lefroy MP, Stafford|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Paul Farrelly]] (born 1962), MP for Newcastle-under-Lyme and former journalist<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/10882/paul_farrelly/newcastle-under-lyme |title=Paul Farrelly MP, Newcastle-under-Lyme |website=TheyWorkForYou |language=en |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Karen Bradley]] (born 1970), MP for the [[Staffordshire Moorlands (UK Parliament constituency)|Staffordshire Moorlands]] and [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/24725/karen_bradley/staffordshire_moorlands |title=Karen Bradley MP, Staffordshire Moorlands |website=TheyWorkForYou |language=en |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Gareth Snell]] (born 1986), graduate of [[Keele University]] 2008, leader of the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council]] 2012\u20132014 and MP for [[Stoke-on-Trent Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent Central]] since 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/25601/gareth_snell/stoke-on-trent_central |title=Gareth Snell MP, Stoke-on-Trent Central |website=TheyWorkForYou |language=en |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Cite book |last=Jenkins |first=J G |title=A History of Newcastle-under-Lyme |year=1983 |publisher=Staffordshire County Library |id=}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Briggs |first=J |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme, 1173\u20131973 |year=1973 |publisher=Newcastle-under-Lyme Borough Council |isbn=978-0-9502745-1-5}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Morris |first=Dennis |last2=Priestley |first2=Anthony |last3=Priestley |first3=Joy |last4=Simmons |first4=Roger |last5=Watkin |first5=Edward |title=The Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme : A Portrait in Old Picture Postcards |year=1987 |publisher=Brampton Publications |id=ASIN B000IBSQAW}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Adams |title=Wartime Newcastle-under-Lyme |year=1988 |publisher=Hendon Publishing Co Ltd |isbn=978-0-86067-113-8 |first=D W}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Adams |first=D W |title=Newcastle-under-Lyme as it was |year=1986 |publisher=Hendon Publishing Co Ltd |isbn=978-0-86067-106-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Newcastle-under-Lyme}}\n*{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Newcastle-under-Lyme |volume=19 |short=x}}\n*[http://www.newcastle-staffs.gov.uk/ Newcastle-under-Lyme borough council]\n\n\n{{Staffordshire}}\n{{West Midlands}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newcastle-Under-Lyme}}\n[[Category:Newcastle-under-Lyme| ]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Towns in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newcastle-under-Lyme"}
