     = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--><ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nThe '''Nova Scotia killings''' were a series of killings that took place over a thirteen-hour period from April 18 and April 19, 2020 in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. The perperatror, Gabriel Wortman, shot and killed at least 18<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to at least five buildings in various locations [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]]<ref name=\"CBC0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among 17 confirmed dead in Nova Scotia killing spree|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> before being killed by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP).<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Latest known victims of N.S. rampage include young father, retired nursing home worker, former firefighter|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> It is the deadliest attack involving the use of [[firearm]]s in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has not yet established a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n=== April 18 ===\n\nAt approximately 11:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]], RCMP officers responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> Three houses on Portapique Beach Road were found on fire, and at least five victims were located; they were \"gunned down as they tried to escape the flames\".  One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they had yet to locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, but no [[emergency population warning]] using [[Alert Ready]] was made. The investigation developed overnight, and by the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n=== April 19 ===\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Gabriel Wortman, age 51, as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was [[Police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica police vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was sighted in or near the communities of [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating he was travelling south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /> A law enforcement source told [[CNN]] that during this time, Wortman began randomly pulling drivers over and killing them.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nSometime shortly before 11:24 a.m., Wortman encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Highway 2]], in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]]. Witnesses reported seeing Wortman run towards Stevenson and hearing an exchange of gunfire, which killed Stevenson and injured another officer.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Two burning cars were observed at the scene, including an RCMP cruiser which may have been Wortman's replica.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Thereafter, he continued south in a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] stolen from one of his victims, and he was next seen in [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nFinally, at 11:40 a.m., more than 12 hours after police responded to the first 9-1-1 calls, Wortman was shot and killed by police at the [[Irving Oil|Irving]] Big Stop gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo official motive has been established for the rampage, which is not considered an act of [[Terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires, which were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nCiting an unnamed law enforcement source, CNN reported that the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at one of the homes in Portapique, where Wortman was allegedly trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used [[Twitter]] to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed at least 18<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, one of them a RCMP Constable. He shot and wounded a second RCMP officer, who is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of his first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP said it expects to find more bodies within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in [[New Brunswick]] and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a house-proud and polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCanadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref name=name>{{cite news |url=https://www.macleans.ca/opinion/the-killers-name/|first=Terry|last=Glavin|title=The killer's name|work=Maclean's|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, stating that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RoyalFamily |number=1252556264971919360 |date = April 21, 2020 |title=The Queen's message to the people of Nova Scotia}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.3972|-63.7067}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Shubenacadie\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = left\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Enfield\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--><ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nThe '''Nova Scotia killings''' were a series of killings that took place over a thirteen-hour period from April 18 and April 19, 2020 in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. The perperatror, Gabriel Wortman, shot and killed at least 18<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to at least five buildings in various locations [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]]<ref name=\"CBC0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among 17 confirmed dead in Nova Scotia killing spree|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> before being killed by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP).<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Latest known victims of N.S. rampage include young father, retired nursing home worker, former firefighter|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> It is the deadliest attack involving the use of [[firearm]]s in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has not yet established a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n=== April 18 ===\n\nAt approximately 11:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]], RCMP officers responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> Three houses on Portapique Beach Road were found on fire, and at least five victims were located; they were \"gunned down as they tried to escape the flames\".  One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they had yet to locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, but no [[emergency population warning]] using [[Alert Ready]] was made. The investigation developed overnight, and by the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n=== April 19 ===\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Gabriel Wortman, age 51, as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was [[Police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica police vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was sighted in or near the communities of [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating he was travelling south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /> A law enforcement source told [[CNN]] that during this time, Wortman began randomly pulling drivers over and killing them.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nSometime shortly before 11:24 a.m., Wortman encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Highway 2]], in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]]. Witnesses reported seeing Wortman run towards Stevenson and hearing an exchange of gunfire, which killed Stevenson and injured another officer.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Two burning cars were observed at the scene, including an RCMP cruiser which may have been Wortman's replica.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Thereafter, he continued south in a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] stolen from one of his victims, and he was next seen in [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nFinally, at 11:40 a.m., more than 12 hours after police responded to the first 9-1-1 calls, Wortman was shot and killed by police at the [[Irving Oil|Irving]] Big Stop gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo official motive has been established for the rampage, which is not considered an act of [[Terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires, which were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nCiting an unnamed law enforcement source, CNN reported that the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at one of the homes in Portapique, where Wortman was allegedly trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used [[Twitter]] to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed at least 18<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, one of them a RCMP Constable. He shot and wounded a second RCMP officer, who is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of his first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP said it expects to find more bodies within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in [[New Brunswick]] and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a house-proud and polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCanadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref name=name>{{cite news|url=https://www.macleans.ca/opinion/the-killers-name/|first=Terry|last=Glavin|title=The killer's name|publisher=Maclean's|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, stating that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RoyalFamily |number=1252556264971919360 |date = April 21, 2020 |title=The Queen's message to the people of Nova Scotia}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReactions:macleans is a 'work'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "Etsy", "text_new": "{{short description|E-commerce website focused on handmade or vintage items}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Etsy\n| logo = Etsy_logo.svg\n| screenshot = \n| caption = \n| url = {{URL|etsy.com}}\n| commercial = Yes\n| type = [[E-commerce]]\n| registration = Required to buy or sell\n| owner = Etsy, Inc.\n| country = United States<ref>https://www.nasdaq.com/market-activity/ipos/overview?dealId=716408-77778</ref>\n| traded_as = {{NASDAQ|ETSY}}<br>[[S&P 400]] Component<br>[[Russell 1000 Index|Russell 1000 Component]]\n| author = Robert Kalin, Chris Maguire, Haim Schoppik, and later Jared Tarbell\n| launch_date = {{start date and age|2005|6|18}}\n| current_status = \n| alexa = {{Decrease}} 151 ({{as of|2020|04|11|alt=April 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/Etsy.com |title= Etsy.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate=2020-04-20 }}</ref>\n| revenue = US$603.7 million (2018)\n}}\n\n'''Etsy''' is an American [[e-commerce]] [[website]] focused on [[handicraft|handmade]] or [[Vintage (design)|vintage]] items and [[craft]] supplies. These items fall under a wide range of categories, including [[jewelry]], bags, clothing, [[home d\u00e9cor]] and furniture, toys, art, as well as craft supplies and tools. All vintage items must be at least 20 years old.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.etsy.com/help/article/483#vintage |title= Etsy Help: DOs and DON'Ts |author= Etsy |date= June 7, 2012 |publisher= Etsy |accessdate=16 June 2012}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> The site follows in the tradition of open [[craft fair]]s, giving sellers personal storefronts where they list their goods for a fee of US$0.20 per item.<ref name=\"NYT-Walker-2007-12-16\">{{cite news | first= Rob | last= Walker | authorlink= Rob Walker (journalist) | title= Handmade 2.0 | date= 2007-12-16 | url   =https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/magazine/16Crafts-t.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&ref=magazine&pagewanted=all | work = The New York Times Magazine | pages = | accessdate = 2007-12-17 }}</ref>\n\nAs of December 31, 2018, Etsy had over 60 million items in its marketplace,<ref name=\"sec.gov\">https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1370637/000137063719000028/etsy1231201810k.htm</ref> and the [[online marketplace]] for handmade and vintage goods connected 2.1 million sellers with 39.4 million buyers.<ref name=\"sec.gov\"/> At the end of 2018, Etsy had 874 employees.<ref name=\"sec.gov\"/> In 2018, Etsy had total sales, or Gross Merchandise Sales (GMS), of US$3.93 billion on the platform.<ref name=\"sec.gov\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Etsy garnered a revenue of US$603.7 million and registered a net income of US$41.25 million.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/etsy-inc-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2018-financial-results-300801469.html |title= Etsy, Inc. Reports Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2018 Financial Results |author= Etsy |date= February 25, 2019 |publisher= Etsy |accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref> The platform generates revenue primarily from three streams: its Marketplace revenue includes a fee of <ref name=\"etsy.com\">\"https://www.etsy.com/seller-news/2018-june-update?ref=SELLER_NEWS\"</ref> 5% of final sale value, which an Etsy seller pays for each completed transaction, on top of a listing fee of 20 cents per item; Seller Services, Etsy's fastest growing revenue stream, includes fees for services such as \"Promoted Listings\", payment processing, and purchases of shipping labels through the platform; while Other revenue includes fees received from [[wikt:third-party|third-party]] [[payment processors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amigobulls.com/stock-analysis-videos/etsy-ipo-all-you-need-to-know|title=Alibaba video, Etsy IPO All You Need To Know|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402171455/http://amigobulls.com/stock-analysis-videos/etsy-ipo-all-you-need-to-know|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Etsy disclosed that it paid US$32.5 million to purchase [[Blackbird Technologies]], a startup that developed [[AI]] software used for shopping context/search applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/03/etsy-paid-32-5-million-for-ai-startup-blackbird-technologies/|title=Etsy paid $32.5 million for AI startup Blackbird Technologies|website=VentureBeat|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== General ==\n\n=== Selling ===\nCreating a shop on Etsy is free; however, each listing that is posted in the shop costs $0.20. Each listing will remain on the shop's page for a maximum of 4 months, or until someone buys the product. The prices of products are set by the shop owner, but Etsy claims 5% of the final sale price of each listing.<ref name=\"etsy.com\" /> Shop owners are sent a bill at the end of every month detailing the fees Etsy has charged them, and they have until the 15th of the following month to pay the fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/sell|title=Etsy \u2013 Learn How to Sell on Etsy|work=Etsy}}</ref> Sellers can choose which payment options to offer buyers, including credit cards, debit cards, and [[PayPal]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/cart?ref=si_cart|title=Etsy \u2013 Shopping Cart|work=Etsy}}</ref>\n\n=== Buying ===\nOn the Etsy [[homepage]], potential buyers can type a \"product description\" into the search bar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/?ref=si_home|title=Etsy \u2013 Your place to buy and sell all things handmade, vintage, and supplies|work=Etsy}}</ref> or, alternatively, they can \"browse\" through a list of options on the left side of the homepage, which includes Art, Home & Living, Jewelry, Women, Men, Kids, Vintage, Weddings, Craft Supplies, Trending Items, Gift Ideas, Mobile Accessories, and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/blog/news/2012/better-ways-to-browse-a-new-look-at-the-marketplace|title=Better Ways to Browse: A New Look at the Marketplace|work=etsy.com}}</ref> Furthermore, buyers may choose from a list of categories by clicking on the \"categories\" link under \"More Ways to Shop\". This will bring the user to a page of over 30 categories, each containing subcategories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/categories?ref=fp_nav_colors|title=Etsy \u2013 Browse Shopping Categories|work=Etsy}}</ref>\n\nWhen a buyer views a product, they can choose to view the positive percentage feedback of each seller to determine the reliability of the shop. Once a buyer finds a product they would like to buy, they click \"Add to Cart\", and that product is added to their virtual \"Shopping Cart\". The buyer may then either continue shopping, or purchase the selected item. In order to purchase items, buyers do not have to have an account with Etsy, and can instead register with a [[Facebook]] or [[Google Account|Google account]].\n\nEtsy has received criticism for its handling of [[customer data]] and [[Internet privacy|privacy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2011/03/etsy-users-irked-after-buyers-purchases-exposed-to-the-world/?comments=1|title=Etsy users irked after buyers, purchases exposed to the world|publisher=}}</ref> {{As of|2016||df=|lc=|since=}}, according to the \"Privacy Policy\" section on the website: \"By using Etsy, you authorise Etsy to use your information in the United States, Ireland and any other country where Etsy operates \".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/uk/legal/privacy/|title=Privacy Policy \u2013 Our House Rules \u2013 Etsy|website=Etsy}}</ref>\n\n== Operations ==\n[[File:Etsy Labs.jpg|thumb|Etsy Labs community [[workspace]] area]]\n[[File:Etsy, Hudson, NY.jpg|thumb|Office in [[Hudson, New York]]]]\nEtsy is popular as a side-business,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/LIVING/personal/01/15/money.for.your.stuff/index.html|title=Turn your skills or your stuff into extra cash|last=Haley|first=Jen|date=2009-01-15|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=CNN}}</ref> as well as a place to buy goods made from [[recycle]]d and [[upcycle]]d materials,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2009/04/24/artists-share-love-earth-and-crafts/|title=Artists share love of Earth and crafts|last=Choi|first=April|date=2009-04-24|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=Columbia Missourian|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723130611/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2009/04/24/artists-share-love-earth-and-crafts/|archive-date=2012-07-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> along with less expensive or more unusual versions of [[mass-produced]] items.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/lifestyle/chi-tc-fash-etsy-0504-0503may03,0,3856316.story|title=An Etsy bitsy fashion secret: Spring trends, affordable and online|last=Arain|first=Fauzia|date=2009-05-03|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=Tribune Newspapers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510063256/http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/lifestyle/chi-tc-fash-etsy-0504-0503may03,0,3856316.story|archive-date=2009-05-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> The unique nature of many of the items for sale is part of their appeal to some shoppers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/people/magazine/17-03/st_thompson|title=Clive Thompson on the Revolution in Micromanufacturing|last=Thompson|first=Clive|date=2009-02-23|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=Wired Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/TECH/science/09/18/craft.revival/|title=A crafty way to beat the chain stores|last=Tutton|first=Mark|date=2008-09-19|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Product photos on Etsy tend to be [[editorial]] or [[Artistic photo|artistic]] instead of commercial catalog style.<ref name=\"inc-money2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/guides/2010/05/sell-handmade-crafts-on-etsy.html|title=How to Make Money on Etsy|last1=Silberman|first1=Lindsay|date=May 11, 2010|publisher=Inc.|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> Sellers can add tags to their products to help buyers find them,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://readwrite.com/2007/06/28/ebay_etsy_dawanda_lovli|title=Swap Meet 2.0: Selling Handmade Goods Online|last1=Catone|first1=Josh|date=June 28, 2007|publisher=ReadWriteWeb|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> and buyers can choose to search for items available locally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/01/business/la-fi-etsy-20110101|title=Online crafts marketplace is vast but not impersonal|author=Kelsey Ramos|date=January 1, 2011|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> Etsy staffers publish lists of featured items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/localnews/ci_16776130|title=Heavens to Etsy: Online artisan marketplace makes shopping local a cinch|last1=Copeland|first1=Laura|date=December 4, 2010|publisher=Santa Cruz Sentinel|accessdate=December 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613002640/http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/localnews/ci_16776130|archive-date=June 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMost sellers are women,<ref name=\"BusinessWeek-6-12-07\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/smallbiz/content/jun2007/sb20070611_488723.htm|title=Etsy: A Site for Artisans Takes Off|last=Miller|first=Kerry|date=2007-06-12|accessdate=2007-12-19|publisher=BusinessWeek}}</ref> who tend to be college-educated and in their twenties and thirties.<ref name=\"emarketer-recession2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1007066|title=Etsy Crafts a Recession Success|date=2009-05-01|publisher=eMarketer Digital Intelligence|accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref> Individual Etsy sellers decide which payment options to offer buyers; these options may include [[credit card]], [[cheque]], [[money order]], [[PayPal]], [[bank transfer]], and Etsy [[gift card]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/help/article/189|title=Etsy Help: How do I select payment methods for my shop?|author=Etsy|publisher=Etsy|accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/help/article/2024|title=Etsy Help: How do I accept credit cards and Etsy Gift Cards in my shop?|author=Etsy|publisher=Etsy|accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nEtsy sellers range from [[hobbyists]] to [[professional]] artists who use the site to make a living.<ref>needs citation</ref> According to artists who have developed their Etsy stores into their primary jobs, scaling up production of handmade items can require [[Overtime|more than full-time work]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/17/fashion/17etsy.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all|title=That Hobby Looks Like a Lot of Work|author=Alex Williams|date=December 16, 2009|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref> especially during the [[holiday shopping season]].<ref name=\"businessweek-nosleep2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-12-05/no-sleep-till-christmas-etsy-sellers-haggard-holidays|title=No Sleep Till Christmas: Etsy Sellers' Haggard Holidays|author=John Tozzi|date=December 5, 2012|work=Small Business|publisher=Businessweek|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nEtsy's main office is in [[Dumbo, Brooklyn]], and it has hosted open crafting classes in the \"Etsy Labs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecommercebytes.com/cab/abu/y209/m04/abu0236/s02|title=Touring Etsy.com's Brooklyn Headquarters|author=Ina Steiner|date=April 5, 2009|publisher=EcommerceBytes|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> The site's technology, customer support, marketing, PR, business, and communications teams operate out of this office. Etsy Labs has a [[workspace]] that provides equipment and donated materials, where members gather to make items, take and teach [[workshop]]s, and attend special events.<ref name=\"NYT-Walker-2007-12-162\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/magazine/16Crafts-t.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&ref=magazine&pagewanted=all|title=Handmade 2.0|last=Walker|first=Rob|date=2007-12-16|work=The New York Times Magazine|accessdate=2007-12-17|pages=|authorlink=Rob Walker (journalist)}}</ref> Etsy also has an office in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.de/society/20100401-26269.html#.UM6F4OOe_Kw|title=Etsy gets made in Berlin|last1=Allen|first1=Kristen|date=April 1, 2012|publisher=[[The Local]] Germany|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, Etsy announced that it was taking steps to hire more women engineers to improve the gender balance of its team, as a website with majority women users but few women engineers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielnyegriffiths/2012/04/06/etsy-hacker-school/|title=Etsy To Fund \"Hacker School\" Grants For Women|author=Daniel Nye Griffiths|date=April 6, 2012|work=Tech|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 16, 2012}}</ref> By 2019, 30 percent of Etsy's engineers identified as \"women or non-binary\", and over 30 percent were people of color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://triplepundit.com/story/2019/etsy-shows-leadership-diversity-tech/81936/|title=Etsy Shows Leadership on Diversity in Tech|last=Mazzoni|first=Mary|date=January 22, 2019|website=TriplePundit|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\nEtsy was one of the main members of the Handmade Consortium, a 2007 effort to encourage buying handmade holiday gifts.<ref name=\"IHT-Walker-12-15-072\">{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/12/14/business/wbcraft.php|title=Craft capitalism: Just do it yourself|last=Walker|first=Rob|date=2007-12-15|accessdate=2007-12-19|publisher=International Herald Tribune|authorlink=Rob Walker (journalist)}}</ref> Etsy has partnered with the retail chain West Elm to sell some Etsy products in its stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/features/npr.php?id=167080018|title=Etsy Crafts A Strategy For Staying Handmade And Profitable|last1=Blair|first1=Elizabeth|date=December 13, 2012|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio News|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://life.nationalpost.com/2011/06/03/we-love-etsy-and-so-does-west-elm-%E2%80%94-the-store-will-host-etsy-sellers-june-4/|title=We love Etsy, and so does West Elm \u2014 the store will host Etsy sellers June 4|last1=Guthrie|first1=Becky|date=June 3, 2011|work=Homes|publisher=National Post|accessdate=December 16, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129115931/http://life.nationalpost.com/2011/06/03/we-love-etsy-and-so-does-west-elm-\u2014-the-store-will-host-etsy-sellers-june-4/|archive-date=January 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In December 2012, Etsy opened a temporary holiday storefront in [[SoHo]], New York City.<ref name=\"businessweek-nosleep2\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n===2005\u20132014===\n[[File:Etsy Work Space.jpg|thumb|Etsy staff at work, July 2010]]\n[[File:Etsy Lamps.jpg|thumb|Art in the Etsy office in [[Brooklyn]]]]\n\nThe site was launched in 2005<ref name=\"Marketing 2014\">{{cite book | title=Marketing 2014 | publisher=South Western Educational Publishing | author=Pride, Ferrell | year=2014 | pages=486 | isbn=978-1133939252}}</ref> by iospace, a small company composed of Robert Kalin, Chris Maguire, and Haim Schoppik. The initial version had taken two and a half months to build.<ref>{{cite web | first = Kat | last = Orland | title = Web 2.0 Awards (2006) \u2013 Interview with Robert Kalin of Etsy | publisher = [[SEOmoz]] | url = http://www.seomoz.org/web2.0/interview/etsy/2006 | accessdate = 2010-10-06 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100914204643/http://www.seomoz.org/web2.0/interview/etsy/2006 | archive-date = 2010-09-14 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Later Jared Tarbell joined the team. Former [[National Public Radio|NPR]] executive Maria Thomas joined as COO in 2008, was promoted to CEO and left Etsy in December 2009.  Robert Kalin resumed his role as CEO from December 2009 until July 2011.<ref name=\"Etsy-2008-07-22\">{{cite web | title=New Roles at Etsy Inc. | publisher=Etsy | date=2008-07-22 | url=http://www.etsy.com/storque/section/etsyNews/article/etsy-announcement-new-roles-at-etsy-inc/2268/ | work=Storque | accessdate=2008-07-28 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728093118/http://www.etsy.com/storque/section/etsyNews/article/etsy-announcement-new-roles-at-etsy-inc/2268/ | archive-date=2008-07-28 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Investors include Sean Meenan,<ref>Forbes 2013-08-07 by Adriana Lopez. Sean Meenan, Passion Before Profit, Etsy.com [https://www.forbes.com/sites/adrianalopez/2013/08/07/passion-before-profit-following-your-passion-is-the-essential-entrepreneurial-trait/]</ref> [[Albert Wenger]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/funding_round/etsy-series-a--56f16066#section-lead-investors|title=Series A Etsy|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> Spencer and Judson Ain, [[Union Square Ventures]], and founders of [[Flickr]] and [[Delicious (website)|Delicious]].<ref name=\"USV-2006-6-5\">{{cite web | first=Fred | last=Wilson | authorlink=Fred Wilson (financier) | title=Etsy | publisher=Union Square Ventures | date=2006-06-05 | url=http://www.unionsquareventures.com/2006/06/etsy_1.html | accessdate=2007-12-19 | url-status=dead | archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091005213249/http%3A//www.unionsquareventures.com/2006/06/etsy_1.html | archive-date=2009-10-05 | df= }}</ref>\n\nKalin said that he named the site Etsy because he \"wanted a nonsense word because I wanted to build the brand from scratch. I was watching Fellini's ''[[8 \u00bd]]'' and writing down what I was hearing. In Italian, you say ''etsi'' a lot. It means 'oh, yes' (actually it's \"''eh, si''\"). And in Latin and French, it means 'what if'.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/LIVING/04/22/website.name.origins.mf/index.html?hpt=C2 | title=How Etsy, eBay, Reddit got their names | author = Rob Lammle | date=2011-04-22 | work= Mental Floss | publisher = CNN }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Etsy means whatsy? 35 iconic brand names explained| author=Alex Dalenberg| date=December 2, 2014| publisher=Upstart Business Journal| accessdate=January 14, 2015| url=http://upstart.bizjournals.com/multimedia/interactives/2014/12/etsy-means-whatsy-35-iconic-brand-names-explained.html}}</ref>\n\nIn Etsy's first year, it attracted attention for frequently adding new tools and functionality to the site to help sellers gain exposure and traffic, including [[Adobe Flash]]-based visualizations and a [[Taxonomy (general)|taxonomy]] of categories with [[Tag (metadata)|tags]].<ref name=\"Techrunch-Arrington-2005-11-8\">{{cite web | first = Michael | last = Arrington | authorlink = Michael Arrington | title = Etsy \u2013 P2P Commerce with Tagging | publisher = Techcrunch | date = 2005-11-08 | url = https://techcrunch.com/2005/11/08/etsy-is-ebay-20/ | accessdate   =2007-12-19}}</ref> Etsy passed $1.7 million in sales in May 2007.<ref name=\"NYT-Ryzik-2007-6-24\">{{cite news | first= Melena | last= Ryzik | title= Where the Crafts Babes and D.I.Y. Dudes Are | date= 2007-06-24 |work=The New York Times| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/24/fashion/24renegade.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&ref=style&pagewanted=all&oref=slogin | accessdate=2007-12-19 }}</ref>  On July 29, Etsy had its one-millionth sale and anticipated its two-millionth sale would occur mid-December 2007. In November 2007, buyers spent $4.3 million purchasing 300,000 items for sale on Etsy, an increase of 43 percent from October 2007.<ref name=\"NYT-Walker-2007-12-16\"/> In June 2007, it expected to be profitable by the fall,<ref name=\"BusinessWeek-6-12-07\"/> but in December 2007 it was not a profitable company.<ref name=\"IHT-Walker-12-15-07\">{{cite news | first= Rob | last= Walker | authorlink= Rob Walker (journalist) |title= Craft capitalism: Just do it yourself |date= 2007-12-15 |publisher= International Herald Tribune |url= http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/12/14/business/wbcraft.php |accessdate= 2007-12-19 }}</ref> In January 2008, Etsy received an additional $27 million in funding from Union Square Ventures, [[Hubert Burda Media]], and [[Jim Breyer]].<ref name=\"CNET-McCarthy\">{{cite web | first = Caroline | last = McCarthy | title = Crafty commerce site Etsy gets $27 million in funding | publisher = CNET News | date = 2008-01-30 | url = http://www.news.com/8301-13577_3-9861216-36.html | work = The Social | accessdate = 2008-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, trouble at eBay, including a strike by some dissatisfied sellers, brought speculation that Etsy could be an increasing competitor.<ref>{{cite news | title = Ebay, After Meg | publisher = Knowledge@Wharton | date = 2008-02-19 | url = https://www.forbes.com/entrepreneurstechnology/2008/02/19/ebay-google-amazon-ent-tech-cx_kw_0219whartonebay.html | accessdate = 2008-02-27}}</ref> At the same time, however, some Etsy sellers expressed discontentment with how Etsy was handling complaints about stores.<ref>{{cite web | first = Meg | last = Marco | title = Sellers Growing Increasingly Unhappy With Lack Of Professionalism At Etsy | publisher = Consumerist | date = 2008-02-26 | url = http://consumerist.com/360889/sellers-growing-increasingly-unhappy-with-lack-of-professionalism-at-etsy | accessdate = 2008-02-27}}</ref> At the time, a comparison of the two websites included complaints that on Etsy, items are difficult to find, the interface \"feels slow\", and the buying and selling process is United States-centric.<ref name=\"Guardian-Schofiled-2008-2-18\">{{cite news | first= Jack | last= Schofield | authorlink = Jack Schofield (journalist) | title= Arts and crafts for the space age | date= 2008-02-18 | publisher= Guardian.co.uk | url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/feb/18/etsy.crafts | work = Netbytes | accessdate=2008-02-27 | location=London}}</ref> Other reviewers enjoyed using Etsy's specialized search options,<ref>{{cite news | first = Micki | last = Takac | title = Etsy's Handmade Goods Inspire the Shopper in All of Us | publisher = Invention and Technology News | date = 2009-02-16 | url = http://news.inventhelp.com/Articles/Internet/Inventions/etsy-shop-12587.aspx | accessdate = 2009-05-12 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090422130559/http://news.inventhelp.com/Articles/Internet/Inventions/etsy-shop-12587.aspx | archive-date = 2009-04-22 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | first = Arlene | last = Lott | title = Do You Etsy? | publisher = CBC.ca | date = 2009-02-24 | url = http://longlivetheinternet.com/do-you-etsy-viable-ecommerce-option/ | work = Steven and Chris| accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref> including the \"Shop Local\" tool.<ref>{{cite news | first = Alexander | last = Baxevanis | title = Etsy brings handmade crafts closer to home | publisher = Marketing Week | date = 2009-02-19 | url = http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/cgi-bin/item.cgi?id=64373&u=pg_dtl_art_news&m=271 | accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Rob Kalin ceded the position of CEO to Maria Thomas.<ref name=\"Storque-The-Long-View-2008-7-2\">{{cite web | first = Robert | last = Kalin | title = The Long View: Rob & Maria | publisher = Etsy | date = 2008-07-09 | url = http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/the-long-view-rob-maria-2150/ | work = Storque | accessdate = 2008-12-08 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081225103402/http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/the-long-view-rob-maria-2150/ | archive-date = 2008-12-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Some longtime Etsy employees left the company in August 2008, including founders Haim Schoppik and Chris Maguire.<ref name=\"Storque-A-Fond-Farewell-2008-12-8\">{{cite web | first = Chris | last = Maguire | authorlink = Chris Maguire | title = A Fond Farewell | publisher = Etsy | date = 2008-08-28 | url = http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/a-fond-farewell-2483/ | work = Storque | accessdate = 2008-12-08 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081225183223/http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/a-fond-farewell-2483/ | archive-date = 2008-12-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In September 2008, Etsy hired Chad Dickerson, who formerly worked at [[Yahoo!]], as Chief Technology Officer.<ref>{{cite news | first = Ina | last = Steiner | title = Touring Etsy.com's Brooklyn Headquarters | publisher = AuctionBytes.com | date = 2009-04-05 | url = http://www.auctionbytes.com/cab/abu/y209/m04/abu0236/s02 | accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref> The company acknowledged concerns about vendors selling other people's work as their own.<ref>{{cite news | first = Bobbie | last = Johnson | title = Etsy: eBay for arts and crafts | publisher = Guardian.co.uk | date = 2008-10-15 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/oct/15/etsy-arts-and-crafts-online | accessdate = 2009-05-12 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, users organized an \"etsyday\" promotion on [[Twitter]] that brought extra attention to the site.<ref>{{cite news | first = Geoffrey A. | last= Fowler | title = How #etsyday Grew on Twitter |publisher=The Wall Street Journal| date = 2009-04-24 | url = https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2009/04/24/how-etsyday-grew-on-twitter/ | work = Digits | accessdate = 2009-05-12 }}</ref> As of May 2009, it had approximately 60 employees and sales of $10 to 13 million per month,<ref name=\"emarketer-recession\">{{cite web | title = Etsy Crafts a Recession Success | publisher = eMarketer Digital Intelligence | date = 2009-05-01 | url = http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1007066 | accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref> possibly boosted by consumer interest in cheaper and more personalized goods due to the United States recession.<ref>{{cite news | first = Claire Cain | last = Miller | title = For Craft Sales, the Recession Is a Help |work=The New York Times| date   =2008-12-22 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/23/business/23craft.html?_r=2&partner=rss&pagewanted=all | accessdate= 2009-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Kalin said that the company is profitable and \"plans to go public, though not until at least next year\".<ref>{{cite news | first = Teri | last = Evans | title = Creating Etsy's Handmade Marketplace |work=The Wall Street Journal| date = 2010-03-30 | url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304370304575152133860888958 | accessdate = 2010-03-30}}</ref> Financial statements required to be filed by Etsy in order to go public show that due to reinvestment of annually increasing gross profits in [[marketing]], [[Web development|product development]], and [[SG&A|management]], the company has not reported a net profit as of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1370637/000119312515129455/d806992ds1a.htm#toc806992_9|title=Amendment No.2 to Form S-1|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Etsy said it had seven million registered users, and that it would continue to focus on a personal community feel as it grows larger, as that is part of what distinguishes it from eBay.<ref>{{cite news | first = Jenna | last = Wortham | title = Online Bazaar Builds on Its Base With Sense of Community |work=The New York Times| date = 2010-12-26 | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/27/technology/27etsy.html | accessdate = 2011-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, Etsy \"introduced a Facebook-style social networking system called People Search...to help buyers and sellers connect with each other and become friends\". By doing so, Etsy made any past purchase with feedback easily searchable, which caused many complaints. Etsy then made changes to the site to better guard information regarding users' purchases.<ref>{{cite web |last=Grant |first=Drew |title=Etsy's social media DIY-saster |url=http://proimexers.com/ |publisher=Professional Imexers|accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Chad Dickerson, CTO since September 2008, became CEO, upon the firing of Rob Kalin. Later CTOs were Kellan Elliot-McCrea and John Allspaw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitchensoap.com/2012/10/25/on-being-a-senior-engineer/|title=On Being A Senior Engineer|first1=I. like making things go! At the|last1=moment|first2=I. am Etsy's|last2=CTO|first3=I. just recently finished my master's degree in Human|last3=Factors|first4=Systems Safety at Lund|last4=University|date=25 October 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, a newspaper article about Etsy covered its fraud detection efforts;<ref name=\"WSJ-Crafts-Cops\">{{cite news | first = Sarah | last = Nassauer | title = Busted by the Crafts Cops | date= 2012-04-17 |work=The Wall Street Journal| url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304299304577349731690704306 | accessdate = 2012-04-26 }}</ref> Etsy had been criticized in the past for inconsistently applying its rules about items having to be handmade.<ref name=\"Etsy-Closings-2012-01-27\">{{cite news | first = Jeff | last = F. | title = Etsy Closes Azreal's Accomplice. Cites Policy Infringement | date= 2012-01-27 | publisher= Houston Press | url = http://blogs.houstonpress.com/artattack/2012/01/etsy_closes_azreals_accomplice.php | accessdate = 2012-01-27 }}</ref> Later in April 2012, the writer of Regretsy, a popular blog, did independent research into a specific featured vendor, Ecologica Malibu, and found evidence to accuse the vendor of being a reseller, which would be against the Etsy Terms of Service.<ref name=\"Regretsy-Killer-2012-04-21\">{{cite news | first = Helen | last = Killer | title = The Etsy Featured Reseller: Ecologica Malibu | date= 2012-04-21 | publisher= Regretsy | url = http://www.regretsy.com/2012/04/21/the-etsy-featured-reseller-ecologica-malibu/ | accessdate = 2012-04-21 }}</ref> The vendor asserted that it was in line with the Terms of Service, stating that the shop had simply failed to identify itself as a \"collective\" that included the work of several individuals, and many Etsy community members posted on the Etsy forum expressing unhappiness with the action (or lack of action) taken by Etsy.<ref>{{cite news | first = Chris | last = Morran | title = Etsy Features Seller Who May Be Blatantly Violating Etsy Policy | date= 2012-04-23 | publisher= The Consumerist | url = http://consumerist.com/2012/04/etsy-features-seller-who-may-be-blatantly-violating-etsy-policy.html | accessdate = 2012-04-26 }}</ref> As of June 2012, the vendor's account is no longer active on Etsy.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://betabeat.com/2012/06/controversial-etsy-seller-disappears-from-etsy/ |title= Controversial Etsy Seller Disappears From Etsy After High-Profile Protest |author= Adrianne Jeffries |date= June 5, 2012 |publisher= BetaBeat |accessdate=June 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Etsy raised $40 million in Series F funding, and announced the company had become a [[B Corporation certification|B Corp]].<ref>{{cite news | first = Jessica | last = Roy | title = With New B Corp. Certification, Etsy Raises $40M for International Growth | date= 2012-05-09 | publisher= Betabeat | url = http://betabeat.com/2012/05/09/with-new-b-corp-certification-etsy-raises-40m-for-international-growth/ | accessdate = 2012-05-09 }}</ref> This [[B Lab]] certification lapsed in 2017.<ref>https://qz.com/work/1146365/etsy-made-mistakes-from-which-other-b-corps-can-learn/</ref><!-- more info: https://observer.com/2017/09/etsy-b-corp-deadline/ --> Etsy's 2012 funds went towards expanding Etsy in international markets, including France, Germany, and Australia.<ref>{{cite news |title= Etsy Focuses on Growth Down Under |author= Gillian Tan |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/dealjournalaustralia/2012/06/12/etsy-focuses-on-growth-down-under/ |newspaper= The Wall Street Journal |date= June 12, 2012 |accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2013, Dickerson held an online Town Hall Meeting to announce that Etsy would now permit factory-made goods and drop shipping, provided the seller either designed or hired designers of the items, disclosed to Etsy their factory, disclosed that they used factories and took \"ownership\" of the process. In that meeting and afterward, Etsy claimed the meaning of the word \"handmade\" should be redefined to encompass factory made.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/townhall/2013/10/01|title=Town Hall: New Guidelines for Etsy Shops|work=Etsy}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Etsy purchased A Little Market, a French e-commerce site for handmade goods, foods, and wine, for a mix of cash and stock valued at less than $100 million. At the time the acquisition was the company's largest.<ref name=\"demos\">Telis Demos, [https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2014/06/23/etsy-acquires-french-market-in-biggest-deal-yet/ \"Etsy Acquires French Market in Biggest Deal Yet,\"] ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', June 23, 2014.</ref>\n\n=== IPO and investor lawsuit ===\nOn March 3, 2015, Etsy announced that it had filed for a $100 million [[IPO]].<ref name=\"ipo_vb\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/03/04/etsy-files-to-go-public-with-100m-ipo/|title=Etsy files to go public with $100M IPO|publisher=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=2015-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.etsy.com/news/2015/etsy-has-filed-a-registration-statement-for-an-ipo/|title=Etsy Has Filed a Registration Statement for an IPO|publisher=Etsy|accessdate=2015-03-04}}</ref> As of 2015, Etsy generated transactions worth US$1.93 billion on its platform, which has 54 million members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/03/04/etsys-54m-members-drove-1-93b-in-sales-last-year/|title=Etsy now has 54M members. They drove $1.93B in sales last year \u2013 VentureBeat \u2013 Business \u2013 by Harrison Weber|work=VentureBeat|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> Etsy went public on April 16, 2015, selling 13.3 million shares, while other stockholders including [[venture capital]] firms such as [[Accel Partners|Accel]] and [[Acton Capital Partners]] were selling the rest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crafts website company Etsy valued at $4 billion in market debut|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-etsyinc-ipo/crafts-website-company-etsy-valued-at-4-billion-in-market-debut-idUSKBN0N71T420150416|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> The company's valuation was $1.8 billion and raised $237 million in IPO proceeds.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gurley|first1=Bill|title=Etsy's IPO is a Milestone for New York's Startup Scene|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/04/16/etsys-ipo-is-a-milestone-for-new-yorks-startup-scene/|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>  Less than a month later, Etsy stock dropped more than 8%. The stock closed at $30 on its first day of trading on April 16 and dropped down to $20.32 as of May 11.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Long|first1=Heather|title=Etsy stock tanks 8% on fears of counterfeit goods|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/05/11/investing/etsy-stock-fall-counterfeit-warning/|publisher=CNN Money|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the IPO in 2015, a group of investors filed a class action lawsuit against Etsy claiming fraud. The suit claimed that Etsy's CEO and officers failed to disclose numerous problems with the site which could affect the stock price, among them that \"more than 5 percent of all merchandise for sale on Etsy\u2019s website may be either counterfeit or constitute trademark or copyright infringement\u201d and that \u201cbrands are increasingly pursuing sellers on Etsy for trademark or copyright infringement, jeopardizing listing fees and commissions\". The suit also claimed that Etsy management knew of the rampant trademark and copyright infringement but did little to stop it, and in fact worked to hide this information from potential investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/655838/etsy-hid-counterfeiting-problems-from-investors-suit-says|title=Etsy Hid Counterfeiting Problems From Investors, Suit Says \u2013 Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132019===\nIn September 2016, Etsy announced the acquisition of artificial intelligence startup Blackbird Technologies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/19/etsy-buys-blackbird-ai-to-bring-more-machine-learning-into-its-search-platform/|title=Etsy buys Blackbird Technologies to bring AI to its search|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> Etsy Inc. after experience a first-quarter loss in May 2017, replaced its chief executive and cut 8% of its workforce. Board member Josh Silverman was appointed CEO over Chad Dickerson.<ref name=wsj-sfadar>{{cite news |last=Safdar |first=Khadeeja |date=May 2, 2017 |title=Etsy Replaces Its CEO After Swinging to a Loss  |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/etsy-replaces-its-ceo-after-swinging-to-a-loss-1493761030 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|location= |access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the company's board replaced Dickerson as CEO with Josh Silverman, citing pressure from shareholders and poor profits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/etsy-replaces-ceo-cuts-jobs-amid-shareholder-pressure-47167426|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News|website=ABC News|access-date=2017-05-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512045447/http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/etsy-replaces-ceo-cuts-jobs-amid-shareholder-pressure-47167426|archive-date=2017-05-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Etsy acquired the music based marketplace [[Reverb.com|Reverb]] for $275 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/22/etsy-acquires-musical-instruments-site-reverb-for-275-million/|title=Etsy acquires musical instruments site Reverb for $275 million|last=Vega|first=Nicolas|date=2019-07-22|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Etsy issues a call to all sellers on the site to start making facemasks to combat COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/etsy-rallies-artisanal-troops-start-100050427.html|title=Etsy Rallies Its Artisanal Troops: \u2018Start Making Face Masks\u2019|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Ethos==\nIn an interview in August 2013, CEO Chad Dickerson emphasized the importance of human interaction and meaning from creativity in regard to his perspective on Etsy. Dickerson described the website as \"a platform that provides meaning to people, and an opportunity to validate their art, their craft\", and after spending time with Etsy users, Dickerson learned that \"all commerce is about real human interaction\". Dickerson also provided a summation of Etsy that is a further reflection of the company's relationship- and meaning-based ethos: \"At the end of every transaction, you get something real from a real person. There is an existential satisfaction to that.\"<ref name=\"Om\">{{cite web|title=Meet the man behind New York's other billion dollar internet company. This one makes money|url=http://gigaom.com/2013/08/23/meet-the-man-behind-new-yorks-other-billion-dollar-internet-company-this-one-makes-money/|work=GIGAOM|publisher=GIGAOM|accessdate=24 August 2013|author=Om Malik|date=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Competitors==\n\nAs of March, 2016, Etsy's top three competitors according to [[Hoovers Online]] are [[Amazon Handmade]], [[Craigslist]], and [[eBay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subscriber.hoovers.com/H/company360/competitorsList.html?companyId=158261000000000|title=Etsy, Inc Competitors List \u2013 Hoover's|website=subscriber.hoovers.com|page=Access Provided by the University of Pittsburgh|access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref> Etsy has been compared to \"a crafty cross between [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] and eBay\",<ref name=\"NYT-Ryzik-2007-6-24\"/> and to \"your grandma's basement\".<ref name=\"NYT-Slatalla-2007-1-18\">{{cite news |first= Michelle |last= Slatalla | authorlink = Michelle Slatalla |title= Rooting Around Grandma's Basement in Cyberspace |date= 2007-01-18 |work=The New York Times|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/18/fashion/18Online.html?ex=157680000&en=8b334fa53f7dd9da&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | accessdate= 2007-12-19 }}</ref> Etsy also has a number of direct competitors. {{ill|DaWanda|de}}, based in Germany, closed in August 2018, ezebee.com, based in Switzerland, is a global competitor, but also caters to freelancers and professionals<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.internetworld.de/Nachrichten/E-Commerce/Handel/Ossian-Vogel-ueber-die-Social-Commerce-Plattform-ezebee.com-Vom-Ansturm-ueberrannt-76476.html/ |title= ezebee vom Ansturm \u00fcberrannt |author= Till Dziallas  |date= 21 May 2013 |publisher= Internetworld Business |accessdate= }}</ref> Bonanza (formerly Bonanzle and 1000 Markets<ref>{{cite news |title= Bonanzle buys 1000 Markets, renames shopping site Bonanza |author= John Cook |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/blog/techflash/2010/09/bonanzle_buys_1000_markets_rebrands_as_bonanzacom.html?page=all |newspaper= Puget Sound Business Journal |date= September 21, 2010 |accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref>) is based in the United States and focuses on clothing and fashion, Zibbet and Made It which are based in Australia, iCraft is based in Canada,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pcworld.com/article/255698/the_5_best_online_marketplaces_for_selling_handmade_goods.html |title= The 5 Best Online Marketplaces for Selling Handmade Goods |author= Christopher Null |date= 18 May 2012 |work= Business |publisher= PCWorld |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> Artfire is based in the United States,<ref>{{cite news |title= The Etsy Wars |author= Jessica Bruder |url= http://money.cnn.com/2009/07/13/smallbusiness/etsy_wars.fsb/ |newspaper= CNNMoney |date= July 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> and Hello Pretty is an online craft marketplace targeted at [[South Africa]]ns.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.howwemadeitinafrica.com/how-an-online-startup-has-pulled-in-a-growing-number-of-buyers-and-sellers/29197/ | title= How an online startup has pulled in a growing number of buyers and sellers |author= Menno Gazendam |date= August 16, 2013 |accessdate=March 20, 2015}}</ref> Tindie is based in Portland, Oregon, and focuses on technology and electronics.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/geekmom/2012/07/tindie-electronic-tinkerers/ |title= tINDIE: Like Etsy For Electronic Tinkerers |author= Laura Grace Weldon |date= 3 July 2012 |work= GeekMom |publisher= WIRED |accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>  ArtYah is based in California, United States undergoing speedy growth and has worldwide sellers and consumers of handmade items, vintage and some craft supplies.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.craftmakerpro.com/business-tips/check-artyah-now/ |title= Why You Should Check Out ArtYah Now |author=Gary Caps |date= 22 June 2017 |accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAsked about competitors, Etsy's European CEO said, \"As far as I am concerned, the more people highlighting the value of supporting micro-producers and buying handmade and vintage directly from them, the better.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.exberliner.com/articles/five-questions-for...-etsy |title= Five questions for... |author= Dana Kikic |date= 13 September 2011 |publisher= Exberliner |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Seller issues==\n\n===Privacy===\nIn 2011, in an effort to add social networking features to Etsy, the company implemented features that allowed users to search other users' buying histories and to trace their purchasing transactions. Etsy thought this feature would allow Etsy users to connect to individuals with similar buying and/or selling histories and an automatic opt-in was applied to all users without the attainment of prior permission. Users of the service raised concerns over the feature's violation of privacy rights, but an official response was not released by the company.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etsy users irked after buyers, purchases exposed to the world|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2011/03/etsy-users-irked-after-buyers-purchases-exposed-to-the-world/|work=Ars Technica|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=7 November 2013|author=Jacqui Cheng|date=15 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Production outsourcing===\nOn Oct 1, 2013, Etsy changed its policy to allow sellers to outsource production to third parties and factories and to use shipping or fulfillment services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Why Etsy's Future depends on redefining 'handmade'|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/04/why-etsys-future-depends-on-leaving-behind-the-simply-handmade/|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> The new rules allow products to be labeled \"handmade\" as long as the original idea for that item \u2014 or its \"authorship\" as C.E.O. Dickerson says \u2014 comes from its respective seller. Further, the policy changes allow Etsy businesses to hire as many employees as they deem necessary (including workers in different locations) and allow sellers to ship orders via third-party couriers rather than the post office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etsy Relaxes Policies, Allows Outside Manufacturing|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/1/4790592/etsy-relaxes-seller-policies-allows-outside-manufacturing-shipping|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe move has prompted at least one Etsy competitor to distinguish itself by committing never to sell manufactured items.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etsys new policy means some items are \"handmade in spirit\"|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2013/10/30/240803436/etsys-new-policy-means-some-items-are-handmade-in-spirit|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Etsy made further changes to its manufacturing policy with the launch of Etsy Manufacturing, a marketplace allowing sellers to connect with outside manufacturers to fabricate their products. Manufacturers must be reviewed and approved by Etsy to ensure they adhere to certain criteria, although Etsy will not conduct visits or in-person inspections. Sellers must apply and be approved to work with any partners listed on Etsy Manufacturing and are required to disclose their use of outside manufacturers on their pages.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etsy Welcomes Manufacturers to Artisanal Fold|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/14/business/etsy-welcomes-manufacturers-to-artisanal-fold.html?_r=0}}</ref>\n\n=== Advertising requirements ===\nIn February 2020, Etsy announced a new \"risk free\" product advertising program, replacing an existing system allowing sellers to purchase ads on platforms such as [[Google Shopping]] from within Etsy. The company will automatically purchase advertising for products on \"high-traffic\" websites, with sales generated by these leads subject to a 15% cut of revenue from the total of the order. Etsy expected at least \"1 in 10\" leads to come from these ads. All sellers will be automatically opted into this program, but sellers with an annual revenue of $10,000 or higher (which will be subject to a 12% cut instead) are required to participate and may not opt out. The system has faced criticism from sellers, who have characterized the new system as a means for the company to further siphon revenue from its sellers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/26/21155193/etsy-advertising-program-angers-sellers-cut-of-sales|title=Etsy tells sellers it\u2019s going to advertise their goods and take a big cut of the sale|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|date=2020-02-26|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/etsy-offsite-ads-program-sellers-backlash/|title=Etsy sellers are furious over new mandatory ad fees|last=Yeo|first=Amanda|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vintage (design)]]\n* [[Vintage clothing]]\n* [[Tech companies in the New York City metropolitan region]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* David Gelles, [https://web.archive.org/web/20171126090111/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/25/business/etsy-josh-silverman.html \"Inside the Revolution at Etsy,\"] ''The New York Times'', November 25, 2017.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Etsy}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:2015 initial public offerings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|E-commerce website focused on handmade or vintage items}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Etsy\n| logo = Etsy_logo.svg\n| screenshot = \n| caption = \n| url = {{URL|etsy.com}}\n| commercial = Yes\n| type = [[E-commerce]]\n| registration = Required to buy or sell\n| owner = Etsy, Inc.\n| country = United States<ref>https://www.nasdaq.com/market-activity/ipos/overview?dealId=716408-77778</ref>\n| traded_as = {{NASDAQ|ETSY}}<br>[[S&P 400]] Component<br>[[Russell 1000 Index|Russell 1000 Component]]\n| author = Robert Kalin, Chris Maguire, Haim Schoppik, and later Jared Tarbell\n| launch_date = {{start date and age|2005|6|18}}\n| current_status = \n| alexa = {{Decrease}} 151 ({{as of|2020|04|11|alt=April 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/Etsy.com |title= Etsy.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate=2020-04-20 }}</ref>\n| revenue = US$603.7 million (2018)\n}}\n\n'''Etsy''' is an American [[e-commerce]] [[website]] focused on [[handicraft|handmade]] or [[Vintage (design)|vintage]] items and [[craft]] supplies. These items fall under a wide range of categories, including [[jewelry]], bags, clothing, [[home d\u00e9cor]] and furniture, toys, art, as well as craft supplies and tools. All vintage items must be at least 20 years old.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.etsy.com/help/article/483#vintage |title= Etsy Help: DOs and DON'Ts |author= Etsy |date= June 7, 2012 |publisher= Etsy |accessdate=16 June 2012}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> The site follows in the tradition of open [[craft fair]]s, giving sellers personal storefronts where they list their goods for a fee of US$0.20 per item.<ref name=\"NYT-Walker-2007-12-16\">{{cite news | first= Rob | last= Walker | authorlink= Rob Walker (journalist) | title= Handmade 2.0 | date= 2007-12-16 | url   =https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/magazine/16Crafts-t.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&ref=magazine&pagewanted=all | work = The New York Times Magazine | pages = | accessdate = 2007-12-17 }}</ref>\n\nAs of December 31, 2018, Etsy had over 60 million items in its marketplace,<ref name=\"sec.gov\">https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1370637/000137063719000028/etsy1231201810k.htm</ref> and the [[online marketplace]] for handmade and vintage goods connected 2.1 million sellers with 39.4 million buyers.<ref name=\"sec.gov\"/> At the end of 2018, Etsy had 874 employees.<ref name=\"sec.gov\"/> In 2018, Etsy had total sales, or Gross Merchandise Sales (GMS), of US$3.93 billion on the platform.<ref name=\"sec.gov\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Etsy garnered a revenue of US$603.7 million and registered a net income of US$41.25 million.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/etsy-inc-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2018-financial-results-300801469.html |title= Etsy, Inc. Reports Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2018 Financial Results |author= Etsy |date= February 25, 2019 |publisher= Etsy |accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref> The platform generates revenue primarily from three streams: its Marketplace revenue includes a fee of <ref name=\"etsy.com\">\"https://www.etsy.com/seller-news/2018-june-update?ref=SELLER_NEWS\"</ref> 5% of final sale value, which an Etsy seller pays for each completed transaction, on top of a listing fee of 20 cents per item; Seller Services, Etsy's fastest growing revenue stream, includes fees for services such as \"Promoted Listings\", payment processing, and purchases of shipping labels through the platform; while Other revenue includes fees received from [[wikt:third-party|third-party]] [[payment processors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amigobulls.com/stock-analysis-videos/etsy-ipo-all-you-need-to-know|title=Alibaba video, Etsy IPO All You Need To Know|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402171455/http://amigobulls.com/stock-analysis-videos/etsy-ipo-all-you-need-to-know|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Etsy disclosed that it paid US$32.5 million to purchase [[Blackbird Technologies]], a startup that developed [[AI]] software used for shopping context/search applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/03/etsy-paid-32-5-million-for-ai-startup-blackbird-technologies/|title=Etsy paid $32.5 million for AI startup Blackbird Technologies|website=VentureBeat|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== General ==\n\n=== Selling ===\nCreating a shop on Etsy is free; however, each listing that is posted in the shop costs $0.20. Each listing will remain on the shop's page for a maximum of 4 months, or until someone buys the product. The prices of products are set by the shop owner, but Etsy claims 5% of the final sale price of each listing.<ref name=\"etsy.com\" /> Shop owners are sent a bill at the end of every month detailing the fees Etsy has charged them, and they have until the 15th of the following month to pay the fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/sell|title=Etsy \u2013 Learn How to Sell on Etsy|work=Etsy}}</ref> Sellers can choose which payment options to offer buyers, including credit cards, debit cards, and [[PayPal]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/cart?ref=si_cart|title=Etsy \u2013 Shopping Cart|work=Etsy}}</ref>\n\n=== Buying ===\nOn the Etsy [[homepage]], potential buyers can type a \"product description\" into the search bar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/?ref=si_home|title=Etsy \u2013 Your place to buy and sell all things handmade, vintage, and supplies|work=Etsy}}</ref> or, alternatively, they can \"browse\" through a list of options on the left side of the homepage, which includes Art, Home & Living, Jewelry, Women, Men, Kids, Vintage, Weddings, Craft Supplies, Trending Items, Gift Ideas, Mobile Accessories, and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/blog/news/2012/better-ways-to-browse-a-new-look-at-the-marketplace|title=Better Ways to Browse: A New Look at the Marketplace|work=etsy.com}}</ref> Furthermore, buyers may choose from a list of categories by clicking on the \"categories\" link under \"More Ways to Shop\". This will bring the user to a page of over 30 categories, each containing subcategories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/categories?ref=fp_nav_colors|title=Etsy \u2013 Browse Shopping Categories|work=Etsy}}</ref>\n\nWhen a buyer views a product, they can choose to view the positive percentage feedback of each seller to determine the reliability of the shop. Once a buyer finds a product they would like to buy, they click \"Add to Cart\", and that product is added to their virtual \"Shopping Cart\". The buyer may then either continue shopping, or purchase the selected item. In order to purchase items, buyers do not have to have an account with Etsy, and can instead register with a [[Facebook]] or [[Google Account|Google account]].\n\nEtsy has received criticism for its handling of [[customer data]] and [[Internet privacy|privacy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2011/03/etsy-users-irked-after-buyers-purchases-exposed-to-the-world/?comments=1|title=Etsy users irked after buyers, purchases exposed to the world|publisher=}}</ref> {{As of|2016||df=|lc=|since=}}, according to the \"Privacy Policy\" section on the website: \"By using Etsy, you authorise Etsy to use your information in the United States, Ireland and any other country where Etsy operates \".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/uk/legal/privacy/|title=Privacy Policy \u2013 Our House Rules \u2013 Etsy|website=Etsy}}</ref>\n\n== Operations ==\n[[File:Etsy Labs.jpg|thumb|Etsy Labs community [[workspace]] area]]\n[[File:Etsy, Hudson, NY.jpg|thumb|Office in [[Hudson, New York]]]]\nEtsy is popular as a side-business,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/LIVING/personal/01/15/money.for.your.stuff/index.html|title=Turn your skills or your stuff into extra cash|last=Haley|first=Jen|date=2009-01-15|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=CNN}}</ref> as well as a place to buy goods made from [[recycle]]d and [[upcycle]]d materials,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2009/04/24/artists-share-love-earth-and-crafts/|title=Artists share love of Earth and crafts|last=Choi|first=April|date=2009-04-24|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=Columbia Missourian|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723130611/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2009/04/24/artists-share-love-earth-and-crafts/|archive-date=2012-07-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> along with less expensive or more unusual versions of [[mass-produced]] items.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/lifestyle/chi-tc-fash-etsy-0504-0503may03,0,3856316.story|title=An Etsy bitsy fashion secret: Spring trends, affordable and online|last=Arain|first=Fauzia|date=2009-05-03|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=Tribune Newspapers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510063256/http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/lifestyle/chi-tc-fash-etsy-0504-0503may03,0,3856316.story|archive-date=2009-05-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> The unique nature of many of the items for sale is part of their appeal to some shoppers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/people/magazine/17-03/st_thompson|title=Clive Thompson on the Revolution in Micromanufacturing|last=Thompson|first=Clive|date=2009-02-23|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=Wired Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/TECH/science/09/18/craft.revival/|title=A crafty way to beat the chain stores|last=Tutton|first=Mark|date=2008-09-19|accessdate=2009-05-12|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Product photos on Etsy tend to be [[editorial]] or [[Artistic photo|artistic]] instead of commercial catalog style.<ref name=\"inc-money2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/guides/2010/05/sell-handmade-crafts-on-etsy.html|title=How to Make Money on Etsy|last1=Silberman|first1=Lindsay|date=May 11, 2010|publisher=Inc.|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> Sellers can add tags to their products to help buyers find them,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://readwrite.com/2007/06/28/ebay_etsy_dawanda_lovli|title=Swap Meet 2.0: Selling Handmade Goods Online|last1=Catone|first1=Josh|date=June 28, 2007|publisher=ReadWriteWeb|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> and buyers can choose to search for items available locally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/01/business/la-fi-etsy-20110101|title=Online crafts marketplace is vast but not impersonal|author=Kelsey Ramos|date=January 1, 2011|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> Etsy staffers publish lists of featured items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/localnews/ci_16776130|title=Heavens to Etsy: Online artisan marketplace makes shopping local a cinch|last1=Copeland|first1=Laura|date=December 4, 2010|publisher=Santa Cruz Sentinel|accessdate=December 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613002640/http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/localnews/ci_16776130|archive-date=June 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMost sellers are women,<ref name=\"BusinessWeek-6-12-07\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/smallbiz/content/jun2007/sb20070611_488723.htm|title=Etsy: A Site for Artisans Takes Off|last=Miller|first=Kerry|date=2007-06-12|accessdate=2007-12-19|publisher=BusinessWeek}}</ref> who tend to be college-educated and in their twenties and thirties.<ref name=\"emarketer-recession2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1007066|title=Etsy Crafts a Recession Success|date=2009-05-01|publisher=eMarketer Digital Intelligence|accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref> Individual Etsy sellers decide which payment options to offer buyers; these options may include [[credit card]], [[cheque]], [[money order]], [[PayPal]], [[bank transfer]], and Etsy [[gift card]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/help/article/189|title=Etsy Help: How do I select payment methods for my shop?|author=Etsy|publisher=Etsy|accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etsy.com/help/article/2024|title=Etsy Help: How do I accept credit cards and Etsy Gift Cards in my shop?|author=Etsy|publisher=Etsy|accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nEtsy sellers range from [[hobbyists]] to [[professional]] artists who use the site to make a living.<ref>needs citation</ref> According to artists who have developed their Etsy stores into their primary jobs, scaling up production of handmade items can require [[Overtime|more than full-time work]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/17/fashion/17etsy.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all|title=That Hobby Looks Like a Lot of Work|author=Alex Williams|date=December 16, 2009|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref> especially during the [[holiday shopping season]].<ref name=\"businessweek-nosleep2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-12-05/no-sleep-till-christmas-etsy-sellers-haggard-holidays|title=No Sleep Till Christmas: Etsy Sellers' Haggard Holidays|author=John Tozzi|date=December 5, 2012|work=Small Business|publisher=Businessweek|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nEtsy's main office is in [[Dumbo, Brooklyn]], and it has hosted open crafting classes in the \"Etsy Labs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecommercebytes.com/cab/abu/y209/m04/abu0236/s02|title=Touring Etsy.com's Brooklyn Headquarters|author=Ina Steiner|date=April 5, 2009|publisher=EcommerceBytes|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> The site's technology, customer support, marketing, PR, business, and communications teams operate out of this office. Etsy Labs has a [[workspace]] that provides equipment and donated materials, where members gather to make items, take and teach [[workshop]]s, and attend special events.<ref name=\"NYT-Walker-2007-12-162\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/magazine/16Crafts-t.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&ref=magazine&pagewanted=all|title=Handmade 2.0|last=Walker|first=Rob|date=2007-12-16|work=The New York Times Magazine|accessdate=2007-12-17|pages=|authorlink=Rob Walker (journalist)}}</ref> Etsy also has an office in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.de/society/20100401-26269.html#.UM6F4OOe_Kw|title=Etsy gets made in Berlin|last1=Allen|first1=Kristen|date=April 1, 2012|publisher=[[The Local]] Germany|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, Etsy announced that it was taking steps to hire more women engineers to improve the gender balance of its team, as a website with majority women users but few women engineers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielnyegriffiths/2012/04/06/etsy-hacker-school/|title=Etsy To Fund \"Hacker School\" Grants For Women|author=Daniel Nye Griffiths|date=April 6, 2012|work=Tech|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 16, 2012}}</ref> By 2019, 30 percent of Etsy's engineers identified as \"women or non-binary\", and over 30 percent were people of color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://triplepundit.com/story/2019/etsy-shows-leadership-diversity-tech/81936/|title=Etsy Shows Leadership on Diversity in Tech|last=Mazzoni|first=Mary|date=January 22, 2019|website=TriplePundit|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\nEtsy was one of the main members of the Handmade Consortium, a 2007 effort to encourage buying handmade holiday gifts.<ref name=\"IHT-Walker-12-15-072\">{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/12/14/business/wbcraft.php|title=Craft capitalism: Just do it yourself|last=Walker|first=Rob|date=2007-12-15|accessdate=2007-12-19|publisher=International Herald Tribune|authorlink=Rob Walker (journalist)}}</ref> Etsy has partnered with the retail chain West Elm to sell some Etsy products in its stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/features/npr.php?id=167080018|title=Etsy Crafts A Strategy For Staying Handmade And Profitable|last1=Blair|first1=Elizabeth|date=December 13, 2012|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio News|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://life.nationalpost.com/2011/06/03/we-love-etsy-and-so-does-west-elm-%E2%80%94-the-store-will-host-etsy-sellers-june-4/|title=We love Etsy, and so does West Elm \u2014 the store will host Etsy sellers June 4|last1=Guthrie|first1=Becky|date=June 3, 2011|work=Homes|publisher=National Post|accessdate=December 16, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129115931/http://life.nationalpost.com/2011/06/03/we-love-etsy-and-so-does-west-elm-\u2014-the-store-will-host-etsy-sellers-june-4/|archive-date=January 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In December 2012, Etsy opened a temporary holiday storefront in [[SoHo]], New York City.<ref name=\"businessweek-nosleep2\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n===2005\u20132014===\n[[File:Etsy Work Space.jpg|thumb|Etsy staff at work, July 2010]]\n[[File:Etsy Lamps.jpg|thumb|Art in the Etsy office in [[Brooklyn]]]]\n\nThe site was launched in 2005<ref name=\"Marketing 2014\">{{cite book | title=Marketing 2014 | publisher=South Western Educational Publishing | author=Pride, Ferrell | year=2014 | pages=486 | isbn=978-1133939252}}</ref> by iospace, a small company composed of Robert Kalin, Chris Maguire, and Haim Schoppik. The initial version had taken two and a half months to build.<ref>{{cite web | first = Kat | last = Orland | title = Web 2.0 Awards (2006) \u2013 Interview with Robert Kalin of Etsy | publisher = [[SEOmoz]] | url = http://www.seomoz.org/web2.0/interview/etsy/2006 | accessdate = 2010-10-06 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100914204643/http://www.seomoz.org/web2.0/interview/etsy/2006 | archive-date = 2010-09-14 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Later Jared Tarbell joined the team. Former [[National Public Radio|NPR]] executive Maria Thomas joined as COO in 2008, was promoted to CEO and left Etsy in December 2009.  Robert Kalin resumed his role as CEO from December 2009 until July 2011.<ref name=\"Etsy-2008-07-22\">{{cite web | title=New Roles at Etsy Inc. | publisher=Etsy | date=2008-07-22 | url=http://www.etsy.com/storque/section/etsyNews/article/etsy-announcement-new-roles-at-etsy-inc/2268/ | work=Storque | accessdate=2008-07-28 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728093118/http://www.etsy.com/storque/section/etsyNews/article/etsy-announcement-new-roles-at-etsy-inc/2268/ | archive-date=2008-07-28 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Investors include Sean Meenan,<ref>Forbes 2013-08-07 by Adriana Lopez. Sean Meenan, Passion Before Profit, Etsy.com [https://www.forbes.com/sites/adrianalopez/2013/08/07/passion-before-profit-following-your-passion-is-the-essential-entrepreneurial-trait/]</ref> [[Albert Wenger]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/funding_round/etsy-series-a--56f16066#section-lead-investors|title=Series A Etsy|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> Spencer and Judson Ain, [[Union Square Ventures]], and founders of [[Flickr]] and [[Delicious (website)|Delicious]].<ref name=\"USV-2006-6-5\">{{cite web | first=Fred | last=Wilson | authorlink=Fred Wilson (financier) | title=Etsy | publisher=Union Square Ventures | date=2006-06-05 | url=http://www.unionsquareventures.com/2006/06/etsy_1.html | accessdate=2007-12-19 | url-status=dead | archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091005213249/http%3A//www.unionsquareventures.com/2006/06/etsy_1.html | archive-date=2009-10-05 | df= }}</ref>\n\nKalin said that he named the site Etsy because he \"wanted a nonsense word because I wanted to build the brand from scratch. I was watching Fellini's ''[[8 \u00bd]]'' and writing down what I was hearing. In Italian, you say ''etsi'' a lot. It means 'oh, yes' (actually it's \"''eh, si''\"). And in Latin and French, it means 'what if'.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/LIVING/04/22/website.name.origins.mf/index.html?hpt=C2 | title=How Etsy, eBay, Reddit got their names | author = Rob Lammle | date=2011-04-22 | work= Mental Floss | publisher = CNN }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Etsy means whatsy? 35 iconic brand names explained| author=Alex Dalenberg| date=December 2, 2014| publisher=Upstart Business Journal| accessdate=January 14, 2015| url=http://upstart.bizjournals.com/multimedia/interactives/2014/12/etsy-means-whatsy-35-iconic-brand-names-explained.html}}</ref>\n\nIn Etsy's first year, it attracted attention for frequently adding new tools and functionality to the site to help sellers gain exposure and traffic, including [[Adobe Flash]]-based visualizations and a [[Taxonomy (general)|taxonomy]] of categories with [[Tag (metadata)|tags]].<ref name=\"Techrunch-Arrington-2005-11-8\">{{cite web | first = Michael | last = Arrington | authorlink = Michael Arrington | title = Etsy \u2013 P2P Commerce with Tagging | publisher = Techcrunch | date = 2005-11-08 | url = https://techcrunch.com/2005/11/08/etsy-is-ebay-20/ | accessdate   =2007-12-19}}</ref> Etsy passed $1.7 million in sales in May 2007.<ref name=\"NYT-Ryzik-2007-6-24\">{{cite news | first= Melena | last= Ryzik | title= Where the Crafts Babes and D.I.Y. Dudes Are | date= 2007-06-24 |work=The New York Times| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/24/fashion/24renegade.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&ref=style&pagewanted=all&oref=slogin | accessdate=2007-12-19 }}</ref>  On July 29, Etsy had its one-millionth sale and anticipated its two-millionth sale would occur mid-December 2007. In November 2007, buyers spent $4.3 million purchasing 300,000 items for sale on Etsy, an increase of 43 percent from October 2007.<ref name=\"NYT-Walker-2007-12-16\"/> In June 2007, it expected to be profitable by the fall,<ref name=\"BusinessWeek-6-12-07\"/> but in December 2007 it was not a profitable company.<ref name=\"IHT-Walker-12-15-07\">{{cite news | first= Rob | last= Walker | authorlink= Rob Walker (journalist) |title= Craft capitalism: Just do it yourself |date= 2007-12-15 |publisher= International Herald Tribune |url= http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/12/14/business/wbcraft.php |accessdate= 2007-12-19 }}</ref> In January 2008, Etsy received an additional $27 million in funding from Union Square Ventures, [[Hubert Burda Media]], and [[Jim Breyer]].<ref name=\"CNET-McCarthy\">{{cite web | first = Caroline | last = McCarthy | title = Crafty commerce site Etsy gets $27 million in funding | publisher = CNET News | date = 2008-01-30 | url = http://www.news.com/8301-13577_3-9861216-36.html | work = The Social | accessdate = 2008-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, trouble at eBay, including a strike by some dissatisfied sellers, brought speculation that Etsy could be an increasing competitor.<ref>{{cite news | title = Ebay, After Meg | publisher = Knowledge@Wharton | date = 2008-02-19 | url = https://www.forbes.com/entrepreneurstechnology/2008/02/19/ebay-google-amazon-ent-tech-cx_kw_0219whartonebay.html | accessdate = 2008-02-27}}</ref> At the same time, however, some Etsy sellers expressed discontentment with how Etsy was handling complaints about stores.<ref>{{cite web | first = Meg | last = Marco | title = Sellers Growing Increasingly Unhappy With Lack Of Professionalism At Etsy | publisher = Consumerist | date = 2008-02-26 | url = http://consumerist.com/360889/sellers-growing-increasingly-unhappy-with-lack-of-professionalism-at-etsy | accessdate = 2008-02-27}}</ref> At the time, a comparison of the two websites included complaints that on Etsy, items are difficult to find, the interface \"feels slow\", and the buying and selling process is United States-centric.<ref name=\"Guardian-Schofiled-2008-2-18\">{{cite news | first= Jack | last= Schofield | authorlink = Jack Schofield (journalist) | title= Arts and crafts for the space age | date= 2008-02-18 | publisher= Guardian.co.uk | url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/feb/18/etsy.crafts | work = Netbytes | accessdate=2008-02-27 | location=London}}</ref> Other reviewers enjoyed using Etsy's specialized search options,<ref>{{cite news | first = Micki | last = Takac | title = Etsy's Handmade Goods Inspire the Shopper in All of Us | publisher = Invention and Technology News | date = 2009-02-16 | url = http://news.inventhelp.com/Articles/Internet/Inventions/etsy-shop-12587.aspx | accessdate = 2009-05-12 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090422130559/http://news.inventhelp.com/Articles/Internet/Inventions/etsy-shop-12587.aspx | archive-date = 2009-04-22 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | first = Arlene | last = Lott | title = Do You Etsy? | publisher = CBC.ca | date = 2009-02-24 | url = http://longlivetheinternet.com/do-you-etsy-viable-ecommerce-option/ | work = Steven and Chris| accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref> including the \"Shop Local\" tool.<ref>{{cite news | first = Alexander | last = Baxevanis | title = Etsy brings handmade crafts closer to home | publisher = Marketing Week | date = 2009-02-19 | url = http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/cgi-bin/item.cgi?id=64373&u=pg_dtl_art_news&m=271 | accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Rob Kalin ceded the position of CEO to Maria Thomas.<ref name=\"Storque-The-Long-View-2008-7-2\">{{cite web | first = Robert | last = Kalin | title = The Long View: Rob & Maria | publisher = Etsy | date = 2008-07-09 | url = http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/the-long-view-rob-maria-2150/ | work = Storque | accessdate = 2008-12-08 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081225103402/http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/the-long-view-rob-maria-2150/ | archive-date = 2008-12-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Some longtime Etsy employees left the company in August 2008, including founders Haim Schoppik and Chris Maguire.<ref name=\"Storque-A-Fond-Farewell-2008-12-8\">{{cite web | first = Chris | last = Maguire | authorlink = Chris Maguire | title = A Fond Farewell | publisher = Etsy | date = 2008-08-28 | url = http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/a-fond-farewell-2483/ | work = Storque | accessdate = 2008-12-08 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081225183223/http://www.etsy.com/storque/etsy-news/a-fond-farewell-2483/ | archive-date = 2008-12-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In September 2008, Etsy hired Chad Dickerson, who formerly worked at [[Yahoo!]], as Chief Technology Officer.<ref>{{cite news | first = Ina | last = Steiner | title = Touring Etsy.com's Brooklyn Headquarters | publisher = AuctionBytes.com | date = 2009-04-05 | url = http://www.auctionbytes.com/cab/abu/y209/m04/abu0236/s02 | accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref> The company acknowledged concerns about vendors selling other people's work as their own.<ref>{{cite news | first = Bobbie | last = Johnson | title = Etsy: eBay for arts and crafts | publisher = Guardian.co.uk | date = 2008-10-15 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/oct/15/etsy-arts-and-crafts-online | accessdate = 2009-05-12 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, users organized an \"etsyday\" promotion on [[Twitter]] that brought extra attention to the site.<ref>{{cite news | first = Geoffrey A. | last= Fowler | title = How #etsyday Grew on Twitter |publisher=The Wall Street Journal| date = 2009-04-24 | url = https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2009/04/24/how-etsyday-grew-on-twitter/ | work = Digits | accessdate = 2009-05-12 }}</ref> As of May 2009, it had approximately 60 employees and sales of $10 to 13 million per month,<ref name=\"emarketer-recession\">{{cite web | title = Etsy Crafts a Recession Success | publisher = eMarketer Digital Intelligence | date = 2009-05-01 | url = http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1007066 | accessdate = 2009-05-12}}</ref> possibly boosted by consumer interest in cheaper and more personalized goods due to the United States recession.<ref>{{cite news | first = Claire Cain | last = Miller | title = For Craft Sales, the Recession Is a Help |work=The New York Times| date   =2008-12-22 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/23/business/23craft.html?_r=2&partner=rss&pagewanted=all | accessdate= 2009-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Kalin said that the company is profitable and \"plans to go public, though not until at least next year\".<ref>{{cite news | first = Teri | last = Evans | title = Creating Etsy's Handmade Marketplace |work=The Wall Street Journal| date = 2010-03-30 | url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304370304575152133860888958 | accessdate = 2010-03-30}}</ref> Financial statements required to be filed by Etsy in order to go public show that due to reinvestment of annually increasing gross profits in [[marketing]], [[Web development|product development]], and [[SG&A|management]], the company has not reported a net profit as of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1370637/000119312515129455/d806992ds1a.htm#toc806992_9|title=Amendment No.2 to Form S-1|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Etsy said it had seven million registered users, and that it would continue to focus on a personal community feel as it grows larger, as that is part of what distinguishes it from eBay.<ref>{{cite news | first = Jenna | last = Wortham | title = Online Bazaar Builds on Its Base With Sense of Community |work=The New York Times| date = 2010-12-26 | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/27/technology/27etsy.html | accessdate = 2011-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, Etsy \"introduced a Facebook-style social networking system called People Search...to help buyers and sellers connect with each other and become friends\". By doing so, Etsy made any past purchase with feedback easily searchable, which caused many complaints. Etsy then made changes to the site to better guard information regarding users' purchases.<ref>{{cite web |last=Grant |first=Drew |title=Etsy's social media DIY-saster |url=http://proimexers.com/ |publisher=Professional Imexers|accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Chad Dickerson, CTO since September 2008, became CEO, upon the firing of Rob Kalin. Later CTOs were Kellan Elliot-McCrea and John Allspaw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitchensoap.com/2012/10/25/on-being-a-senior-engineer/|title=On Being A Senior Engineer|first1=I. like making things go! At the|last1=moment|first2=I. am Etsy's|last2=CTO|first3=I. just recently finished my master's degree in Human|last3=Factors|first4=Systems Safety at Lund|last4=University|date=25 October 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, a newspaper article about Etsy covered its fraud detection efforts;<ref name=\"WSJ-Crafts-Cops\">{{cite news | first = Sarah | last = Nassauer | title = Busted by the Crafts Cops | date= 2012-04-17 |work=The Wall Street Journal| url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304299304577349731690704306 | accessdate = 2012-04-26 }}</ref> Etsy had been criticized in the past for inconsistently applying its rules about items having to be handmade.<ref name=\"Etsy-Closings-2012-01-27\">{{cite news | first = Jeff | last = F. | title = Etsy Closes Azreal's Accomplice. Cites Policy Infringement | date= 2012-01-27 | publisher= Houston Press | url = http://blogs.houstonpress.com/artattack/2012/01/etsy_closes_azreals_accomplice.php | accessdate = 2012-01-27 }}</ref> Later in April 2012, the writer of Regretsy, a popular blog, did independent research into a specific featured vendor, Ecologica Malibu, and found evidence to accuse the vendor of being a reseller, which would be against the Etsy Terms of Service.<ref name=\"Regretsy-Killer-2012-04-21\">{{cite news | first = Helen | last = Killer | title = The Etsy Featured Reseller: Ecologica Malibu | date= 2012-04-21 | publisher= Regretsy | url = http://www.regretsy.com/2012/04/21/the-etsy-featured-reseller-ecologica-malibu/ | accessdate = 2012-04-21 }}</ref> The vendor asserted that it was in line with the Terms of Service, stating that the shop had simply failed to identify itself as a \"collective\" that included the work of several individuals, and many Etsy community members posted on the Etsy forum expressing unhappiness with the action (or lack of action) taken by Etsy.<ref>{{cite news | first = Chris | last = Morran | title = Etsy Features Seller Who May Be Blatantly Violating Etsy Policy | date= 2012-04-23 | publisher= The Consumerist | url = http://consumerist.com/2012/04/etsy-features-seller-who-may-be-blatantly-violating-etsy-policy.html | accessdate = 2012-04-26 }}</ref> As of June 2012, the vendor's account is no longer active on Etsy.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://betabeat.com/2012/06/controversial-etsy-seller-disappears-from-etsy/ |title= Controversial Etsy Seller Disappears From Etsy After High-Profile Protest |author= Adrianne Jeffries |date= June 5, 2012 |publisher= BetaBeat |accessdate=June 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Etsy raised $40 million in Series F funding, and announced the company had become a [[B Corporation certification|B Corp]].<ref>{{cite news | first = Jessica | last = Roy | title = With New B Corp. Certification, Etsy Raises $40M for International Growth | date= 2012-05-09 | publisher= Betabeat | url = http://betabeat.com/2012/05/09/with-new-b-corp-certification-etsy-raises-40m-for-international-growth/ | accessdate = 2012-05-09 }}</ref> This [[B Lab]] certification lapsed in 2017.<ref>https://qz.com/work/1146365/etsy-made-mistakes-from-which-other-b-corps-can-learn/</ref><!-- more info: https://observer.com/2017/09/etsy-b-corp-deadline/ --> Etsy's 2012 funds went towards expanding Etsy in international markets, including France, Germany, and Australia.<ref>{{cite news |title= Etsy Focuses on Growth Down Under |author= Gillian Tan |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/dealjournalaustralia/2012/06/12/etsy-focuses-on-growth-down-under/ |newspaper= The Wall Street Journal |date= June 12, 2012 |accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2013, Dickerson held an online Town Hall Meeting to announce that Etsy would now permit factory-made goods and drop shipping, provided the seller either designed or hired designers of the items, disclosed to Etsy their factory, disclosed that they used factories and took \"ownership\" of the process. In that meeting and afterward, Etsy claimed the meaning of the word \"handmade\" should be redefined to encompass factory made.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etsy.com/townhall/2013/10/01|title=Town Hall: New Guidelines for Etsy Shops|work=Etsy}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Etsy purchased A Little Market, a French e-commerce site for handmade goods, foods, and wine, for a mix of cash and stock valued at less than $100 million. At the time the acquisition was the company's largest.<ref name=\"demos\">Telis Demos, [https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2014/06/23/etsy-acquires-french-market-in-biggest-deal-yet/ \"Etsy Acquires French Market in Biggest Deal Yet,\"] ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', June 23, 2014.</ref>\n\n=== IPO and investor lawsuit ===\nOn March 3, 2015, Etsy announced that it had filed for a $100 million [[IPO]].<ref name=\"ipo_vb\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/03/04/etsy-files-to-go-public-with-100m-ipo/|title=Etsy files to go public with $100M IPO|publisher=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=2015-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.etsy.com/news/2015/etsy-has-filed-a-registration-statement-for-an-ipo/|title=Etsy Has Filed a Registration Statement for an IPO|publisher=Etsy|accessdate=2015-03-04}}</ref> As of 2015, Etsy generated transactions worth US$1.93 billion on its platform, which has 54 million members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/03/04/etsys-54m-members-drove-1-93b-in-sales-last-year/|title=Etsy now has 54M members. They drove $1.93B in sales last year \u2013 VentureBeat \u2013 Business \u2013 by Harrison Weber|work=VentureBeat|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> Etsy went public on April 16, 2015, selling 13.3 million shares, while other stockholders including [[venture capital]] firms such as [[Accel Partners|Accel]] and [[Acton Capital Partners]] were selling the rest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crafts website company Etsy valued at $4 billion in market debut|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-etsyinc-ipo/crafts-website-company-etsy-valued-at-4-billion-in-market-debut-idUSKBN0N71T420150416|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> The company's valuation was $1.8 billion and raised $237 million in IPO proceeds.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gurley|first1=Bill|title=Etsy's IPO is a Milestone for New York's Startup Scene|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/04/16/etsys-ipo-is-a-milestone-for-new-yorks-startup-scene/|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>  Less than a month later, Etsy stock dropped more than 8%. The stock closed at $30 on its first day of trading on April 16 and dropped down to $20.32 as of May 11.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Long|first1=Heather|title=Etsy stock tanks 8% on fears of counterfeit goods|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/05/11/investing/etsy-stock-fall-counterfeit-warning/|publisher=CNN Money|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the IPO in 2015, a group of investors filed a class action lawsuit against Etsy claiming fraud. The suit claimed that Etsy's CEO and officers failed to disclose numerous problems with the site which could affect the stock price, among them that \"more than 5 percent of all merchandise for sale on Etsy\u2019s website may be either counterfeit or constitute trademark or copyright infringement\u201d and that \u201cbrands are increasingly pursuing sellers on Etsy for trademark or copyright infringement, jeopardizing listing fees and commissions\". The suit also claimed that Etsy management knew of the rampant trademark and copyright infringement but did little to stop it, and in fact worked to hide this information from potential investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/655838/etsy-hid-counterfeiting-problems-from-investors-suit-says|title=Etsy Hid Counterfeiting Problems From Investors, Suit Says \u2013 Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132019===\nIn September 2016, Etsy announced the acquisition of artificial intelligence startup Blackbird Technologies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/19/etsy-buys-blackbird-ai-to-bring-more-machine-learning-into-its-search-platform/|title=Etsy buys Blackbird Technologies to bring AI to its search|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> Etsy Inc. after experience a first-quarter loss in May 2017, replaced its chief executive and cut 8% of its workforce. Board member Josh Silverman was appointed CEO over Chad Dickerson.<ref name=wsj-sfadar>{{cite news |last=Safdar |first=Khadeeja |date=May 2, 2017 |title=Etsy Replaces Its CEO After Swinging to a Loss  |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/etsy-replaces-its-ceo-after-swinging-to-a-loss-1493761030 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|location= |access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the company's board replaced Dickerson as CEO with Josh Silverman, citing pressure from shareholders and poor profits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/etsy-replaces-ceo-cuts-jobs-amid-shareholder-pressure-47167426|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News|website=ABC News|access-date=2017-05-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512045447/http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/etsy-replaces-ceo-cuts-jobs-amid-shareholder-pressure-47167426|archive-date=2017-05-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Etsy acquired the music based marketplace [[Reverb.com|Reverb]] for $275 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/22/etsy-acquires-musical-instruments-site-reverb-for-275-million/|title=Etsy acquires musical instruments site Reverb for $275 million|last=Vega|first=Nicolas|date=2019-07-22|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Ethos==\nIn an interview in August 2013, CEO Chad Dickerson emphasized the importance of human interaction and meaning from creativity in regard to his perspective on Etsy. Dickerson described the website as \"a platform that provides meaning to people, and an opportunity to validate their art, their craft\", and after spending time with Etsy users, Dickerson learned that \"all commerce is about real human interaction\". Dickerson also provided a summation of Etsy that is a further reflection of the company's relationship- and meaning-based ethos: \"At the end of every transaction, you get something real from a real person. There is an existential satisfaction to that.\"<ref name=\"Om\">{{cite web|title=Meet the man behind New York's other billion dollar internet company. This one makes money|url=http://gigaom.com/2013/08/23/meet-the-man-behind-new-yorks-other-billion-dollar-internet-company-this-one-makes-money/|work=GIGAOM|publisher=GIGAOM|accessdate=24 August 2013|author=Om Malik|date=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Competitors==\n\nAs of March, 2016, Etsy's top three competitors according to [[Hoovers Online]] are [[Amazon Handmade]], [[Craigslist]], and [[eBay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subscriber.hoovers.com/H/company360/competitorsList.html?companyId=158261000000000|title=Etsy, Inc Competitors List \u2013 Hoover's|website=subscriber.hoovers.com|page=Access Provided by the University of Pittsburgh|access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref> Etsy has been compared to \"a crafty cross between [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] and eBay\",<ref name=\"NYT-Ryzik-2007-6-24\"/> and to \"your grandma's basement\".<ref name=\"NYT-Slatalla-2007-1-18\">{{cite news |first= Michelle |last= Slatalla | authorlink = Michelle Slatalla |title= Rooting Around Grandma's Basement in Cyberspace |date= 2007-01-18 |work=The New York Times|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/18/fashion/18Online.html?ex=157680000&en=8b334fa53f7dd9da&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | accessdate= 2007-12-19 }}</ref> Etsy also has a number of direct competitors. {{ill|DaWanda|de}}, based in Germany, closed in August 2018, ezebee.com, based in Switzerland, is a global competitor, but also caters to freelancers and professionals<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.internetworld.de/Nachrichten/E-Commerce/Handel/Ossian-Vogel-ueber-die-Social-Commerce-Plattform-ezebee.com-Vom-Ansturm-ueberrannt-76476.html/ |title= ezebee vom Ansturm \u00fcberrannt |author= Till Dziallas  |date= 21 May 2013 |publisher= Internetworld Business |accessdate= }}</ref> Bonanza (formerly Bonanzle and 1000 Markets<ref>{{cite news |title= Bonanzle buys 1000 Markets, renames shopping site Bonanza |author= John Cook |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/blog/techflash/2010/09/bonanzle_buys_1000_markets_rebrands_as_bonanzacom.html?page=all |newspaper= Puget Sound Business Journal |date= September 21, 2010 |accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref>) is based in the United States and focuses on clothing and fashion, Zibbet and Made It which are based in Australia, iCraft is based in Canada,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pcworld.com/article/255698/the_5_best_online_marketplaces_for_selling_handmade_goods.html |title= The 5 Best Online Marketplaces for Selling Handmade Goods |author= Christopher Null |date= 18 May 2012 |work= Business |publisher= PCWorld |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> Artfire is based in the United States,<ref>{{cite news |title= The Etsy Wars |author= Jessica Bruder |url= http://money.cnn.com/2009/07/13/smallbusiness/etsy_wars.fsb/ |newspaper= CNNMoney |date= July 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> and Hello Pretty is an online craft marketplace targeted at [[South Africa]]ns.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.howwemadeitinafrica.com/how-an-online-startup-has-pulled-in-a-growing-number-of-buyers-and-sellers/29197/ | title= How an online startup has pulled in a growing number of buyers and sellers |author= Menno Gazendam |date= August 16, 2013 |accessdate=March 20, 2015}}</ref> Tindie is based in Portland, Oregon, and focuses on technology and electronics.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.wired.com/geekmom/2012/07/tindie-electronic-tinkerers/ |title= tINDIE: Like Etsy For Electronic Tinkerers |author= Laura Grace Weldon |date= 3 July 2012 |work= GeekMom |publisher= WIRED |accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>  ArtYah is based in California, United States undergoing speedy growth and has worldwide sellers and consumers of handmade items, vintage and some craft supplies.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.craftmakerpro.com/business-tips/check-artyah-now/ |title= Why You Should Check Out ArtYah Now |author=Gary Caps |date= 22 June 2017 |accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAsked about competitors, Etsy's European CEO said, \"As far as I am concerned, the more people highlighting the value of supporting micro-producers and buying handmade and vintage directly from them, the better.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.exberliner.com/articles/five-questions-for...-etsy |title= Five questions for... |author= Dana Kikic |date= 13 September 2011 |publisher= Exberliner |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Seller issues==\n\n===Privacy===\nIn 2011, in an effort to add social networking features to Etsy, the company implemented features that allowed users to search other users' buying histories and to trace their purchasing transactions. Etsy thought this feature would allow Etsy users to connect to individuals with similar buying and/or selling histories and an automatic opt-in was applied to all users without the attainment of prior permission. Users of the service raised concerns over the feature's violation of privacy rights, but an official response was not released by the company.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etsy users irked after buyers, purchases exposed to the world|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2011/03/etsy-users-irked-after-buyers-purchases-exposed-to-the-world/|work=Ars Technica|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=7 November 2013|author=Jacqui Cheng|date=15 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Production outsourcing===\nOn Oct 1, 2013, Etsy changed its policy to allow sellers to outsource production to third parties and factories and to use shipping or fulfillment services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Why Etsy's Future depends on redefining 'handmade'|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/04/why-etsys-future-depends-on-leaving-behind-the-simply-handmade/|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> The new rules allow products to be labeled \"handmade\" as long as the original idea for that item \u2014 or its \"authorship\" as C.E.O. Dickerson says \u2014 comes from its respective seller. Further, the policy changes allow Etsy businesses to hire as many employees as they deem necessary (including workers in different locations) and allow sellers to ship orders via third-party couriers rather than the post office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etsy Relaxes Policies, Allows Outside Manufacturing|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/1/4790592/etsy-relaxes-seller-policies-allows-outside-manufacturing-shipping|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe move has prompted at least one Etsy competitor to distinguish itself by committing never to sell manufactured items.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etsys new policy means some items are \"handmade in spirit\"|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2013/10/30/240803436/etsys-new-policy-means-some-items-are-handmade-in-spirit|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Etsy made further changes to its manufacturing policy with the launch of Etsy Manufacturing, a marketplace allowing sellers to connect with outside manufacturers to fabricate their products. Manufacturers must be reviewed and approved by Etsy to ensure they adhere to certain criteria, although Etsy will not conduct visits or in-person inspections. Sellers must apply and be approved to work with any partners listed on Etsy Manufacturing and are required to disclose their use of outside manufacturers on their pages.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etsy Welcomes Manufacturers to Artisanal Fold|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/14/business/etsy-welcomes-manufacturers-to-artisanal-fold.html?_r=0}}</ref>\n\n=== Advertising requirements ===\nIn February 2020, Etsy announced a new \"risk free\" product advertising program, replacing an existing system allowing sellers to purchase ads on platforms such as [[Google Shopping]] from within Etsy. The company will automatically purchase advertising for products on \"high-traffic\" websites, with sales generated by these leads subject to a 15% cut of revenue from the total of the order. Etsy expected at least \"1 in 10\" leads to come from these ads. All sellers will be automatically opted into this program, but sellers with an annual revenue of $10,000 or higher (which will be subject to a 12% cut instead) are required to participate and may not opt out. The system has faced criticism from sellers, who have characterized the new system as a means for the company to further siphon revenue from its sellers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/26/21155193/etsy-advertising-program-angers-sellers-cut-of-sales|title=Etsy tells sellers it\u2019s going to advertise their goods and take a big cut of the sale|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|date=2020-02-26|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/etsy-offsite-ads-program-sellers-backlash/|title=Etsy sellers are furious over new mandatory ad fees|last=Yeo|first=Amanda|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vintage (design)]]\n* [[Vintage clothing]]\n* [[Tech companies in the New York City metropolitan region]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* David Gelles, [https://web.archive.org/web/20171126090111/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/25/business/etsy-josh-silverman.html \"Inside the Revolution at Etsy,\"] ''The New York Times'', November 25, 2017.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Etsy}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:2015 initial public offerings]]\n", "name_user": "Gma5times", "label": "safe", "comment": "add request for COVID-19 masks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Etsy"}
{"title_page": "Austin Meadows", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| image       = Austin Meadows (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  = 255\n| caption     = Meadows in 2019\n| name        = Austin Meadows\n| team        = Tampa Bay Rays\n| number      = 17\n| position    = [[Outfielder]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1995|5|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| bats        = Left Homers\n| throws      = Left\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = May 18\n| debutyear   = 2018\n| debutteam   = Pittsburgh Pirates\n| statyear    = 2019 season\n| statleague  = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .291\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 39\n| stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 106\n| teams =\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Rays]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n| highlights = * [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2019]])\n}}\n'''Austin Wade Meadows''' (born May 3, 1995) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[outfielder]] for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played in MLB for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].\n\n==Career==\nMeadows grew up in [[Grayson, Georgia]], where he competed in [[baseball]] with [[Clint Frazier]].<ref name=Mayo>{{cite web|title=Rivals and pals, Frazier and Meadows create Draft buzz|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130509&content_id=47085694|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> He attended [[Grayson High School]], and led the school's baseball team to the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Class 6A State semi-finals as a junior, [[batting average (baseball)|hitting]] .390 with four [[home run]]s, 28 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] (RBIs), and 19 [[stolen base]]s.<ref name=PP>{{cite web|title=Pirates Draft Austin Meadows With the 9th Overall Pick|url=http://www.piratesprospects.com/2013/06/pirates-draft-austin-meadows-with-the-9th-overall-pick.html|publisher=Piratesprospects.com|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> Meadows was named a preseason First-Team High School All American by Rawlings and Perfect Game,<ref name=AA>{{cite web|title=2013 Rawlings Preseason Senior High School All Americans |url=http://www.perfectgame.org/all_americans/2013/allamerica.aspx |publisher=Perfect Game USA |accessdate=June 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615090719/http://perfectgame.org/all_americans/2013/allamerica.aspx |archivedate=June 15, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> and he hit .535 with 14 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]], one [[Triple (baseball)|triple]], four home runs and 28 RBIs in his senior season.<ref name=PP />\n\nMeadows also played [[American football|football]] as a [[running back]], [[wide receiver]], and [[Punter (football)|punter]] at Grayson where he was a teammate of [[Wayne Gallman]] and [[Robert Nkemdiche]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=David |title=Pirates prospect Austin Meadows was also high school football star |url=https://www.bradenton.com/sports/article140670103.html |accessdate=16 July 2019 |work=[[Bradenton Herald]] |date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Pittsburgh Pirates===\nMeadows was considered as one of the top prospects eligible for the [[2013 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/college/2013-top-100-draft-prospects-may-10-jonathan-gray-tops-mark-appel-for-top-sot/|title=2013 Top 100 Draft Prospects (May 10): Jonathan Gray Takes Top Spot - BaseballAmerica.com|date=May 10, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9255085/mark-appel-jonathan-gray-kris-bryant-top-prospects-2013-mlb-draft|title=Law: Top 100 draft prospects|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He was ultimately selected in the first round, with the ninth overall selection, by the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]. Meadows was committed to attend [[Clemson University]] to play [[college baseball]] for the [[Clemson Tigers baseball|Clemson Tigers]], but chose to forgo that commitment by signing with the Pirates, receiving a $3,029,600 [[signing bonus]] three weeks after the draft.<ref name=Sign>{{cite web|title=Pirates Agree to Terms with Austin Meadows|url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2013/06/pirates-nearing-deal-with-austin-meadows.html|publisher=mlbtraderumors.com|date=June 27, 2013|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter signing with the Pirates, Meadows played for the [[Gulf Coast Pirates]] of the [[Rookie-level]] [[Gulf Coast League]] and the [[Jamestown Jammers]] of the [[Class A-Short Season]] [[New York\u2013Penn League]] in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/pittsburgh-pirates-scouting-report-on-of-austin-meadows-031717|title=Pittsburgh Pirates Scouting Report on OF Austin Meadows \u2013 FOX Sports|date=March 17, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> compiling a combined .316 batting average with seven home runs and 22 RBIs in 48 games between both teams. He played for the [[West Virginia Power]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]] in 2014, but missed a significant portion of the season due to a [[hamstring]] injury,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/pirates/2015/04/02/Austin-Meadows-relishes-his-health-first-taste-of-major-leagues-with-Pirates/stories/201503310103|title=With Pirates, Austin Meadows relishes his health, first taste of majors|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> playing only 38 games, batting .322/.388/.486 with three home runs and 15 RBIs. He played for the [[Bradenton Marauders]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]] (FSL) in 2015, and was named an FSL All-Star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bradenton.com/sports/mlb/bradenton-marauders_/article34905960.html|title=Baseball \u2013 Meadows delivers on hype to become FSL All-Star for Marauders \u2013 Bradenton Herald|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He spent the final week of the season with the [[Altoona Curve]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]].<ref name=eye/> In 121 games for Bradenton he slashed .307/.357/.407 with seven home runs and 54 RBIs, and in six games for Altoona he batted 360. After the regular season, he played for the [[Glendale Desert Dogs]] of the [[Arizona Fall League]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Singer |first=Tom |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146753016/austin-meadows-headed-to-arizona-fall-league/ |title=Austin Meadows headed to Arizona Fall League &#124; MLB.com |publisher=M.mlb.com |date=January 20, 2016 |accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMeadows suffered a broken [[orbital bone]] in his right eye during spring training in 2016.<ref name=eye>{{cite web|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/sports/local-sports/2016/03/meadows-injures-eye/|title=Meadows injures eye |work=Altoona Mirror|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He returned to Altoona and earned a promotion to the [[Indianapolis Indians]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[International League]] in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/sports/altoona-curve/2016/06/pirates-promote-meadows-from-curve/|title=Pirates promote Meadows from Curve |work=Altoona Mirror|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> In 45 games for Altoona he batted .311 with six home runs and 23 RBIs in 45 games, and in 37 games for Indianapolis, he compiled a .214 batting average with six home runs and 34 RBIs. The Pirates invited Meadows to spring training in 2017.<ref name=vibe>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/pirates/2017/03/19/Pirates-prospect-Austin-Meadows-major-league-spring-training/stories/201703190060|title=Pirates top prospect Austin Meadows getting major-league 'vibe'|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Meadows returned to Indianapolis for the 2017 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/milb/news/pittsburgh-pirates-austin-meadows-ignoring-the-hype/c-224790146?tid=185364810|title=IL notes: Meadows ignoring the hype|publisher=MiLB.com|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> where he posted a .250 batting average with four home runs and 36 RBIs in 72 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=640457#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL|title=Austin Meadows Stats, Highlights, Bio - MiLB.com Stats - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|publisher=MiLB.com|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> He missed nearly two months of the season due to hamstring and oblique strains. The Pirates added him to their 40-man roster after the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rob Biertempfel |url=http://triblive.com/sports/pirates/12977361-74/pirates-put-austin-meadows-on-40-man-roster-gift-ngoepe-traded |title=Pirates put Austin Meadows on 40-man roster; Gift Ngoepe traded |publisher=TribLIVE |date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Austin Meadows (43423910741) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Meadows with the Pirates in 2018]]\n[[MLB.com]] ranked Meadows as Pittsburgh's second best prospect going into the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/pirates-2018-top-30-prospects-led-by-keller/c-266878356?tid=151437456|title=New No. 1 Keller leads Pirates Top 30 Prospects list|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> He began the season with Indianapolis and was promoted to the major leagues to make his debut on May 18.<ref>{{cite web|author=3:41&nbsp;pm ET |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/23533618/pittsburgh-pirates-call-top-prospect-austin-meadows |title=Pittsburgh Pirates to call up top OF prospect Austin Meadows |publisher=Espn.com |date= |accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref> He recorded his first major league hit off of [[Tyson Ross]], as well as his first stolen base, that same night.  On May 20, 2018, he hit his first major league home run off of [[Jordan Lyles]].<ref>{{cite web|author=3:35&nbsp;pm ET |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/playbyplay?gameId=380520123 |title=San Diego Padres at Pittsburgh Pirates Boxscore |publisher=Espn.com |date= |accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Meadows was named the [[National League Rookie of the Month]] for the month of May after batting .409 with four home runs, seven RBIs, three doubles, and three stolen bases in 13 games during the month.<ref>http://triblive.com/sports/pirates/13717106-74/austin-meadows-named-national-league-rookie-of-the-month</ref>\n\n===Tampa Bay Rays===\nOn July 31, 2018, Meadows was traded to the [[Tampa Bay Rays]], along with [[Tyler Glasnow]] and a [[player to be named later]], later revealed to be [[Shane Baz]], for [[Chris Archer]] and was optioned to Triple-A Durham.<ref>http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/24246116/chris-archer-traded-pittsburgh-pirates-tampa-bay-rays</ref> Meadows was promoted to the Tampa Bay Rays on September 19. In ten games with the Rays, hit .250/.308/.417 with a [[home run]] and four [[Run batted in|runs batted in]].<ref name=\"baseball-reference.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/meadoau01.shtml|title=Austin Meadows Stats  {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\nMeadows ended the season slashing .287/.325/.461 with six [[home run]]s and 17 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] over 59 games.\n\nThe next year he made his first All-star game.<ref name=\"baseball-reference.com\"/> Meadows ended the season with career highs offensively. He led the team in average (.291), home runs (33), runs (83) and 89 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] in 138 games.\n\n==Personal life==\nMeadows' mother, Staci, played [[softball]] for [[Georgia Southern University]] and [[Georgia State University]], and works as an [[elementary school]] teacher in Grayson. His father, Kenny, played baseball and football for [[Morehead State University]]. His brother, Parker, was drafted by the [[Detroit Tigers]] in the second round of the [[2018 MLB draft]] and currently plays in their organization. Meadows married his wife, Alexis, in December 2018.\n\nMeadows grew up an [[Atlanta Braves]] fan.<ref>https://www.ajc.com/sports/baseball/baseball-draft-goes-through-loganville/SBt4ij5i8F5yiiSY0vgkWO/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=640457|espn=33197|br=m/meadoau01|fangraphs=15672|brm=meadow000aus|retro=M/Pmeada001}}\n*{{twitter|austin_meadows|Austin Meadows}}\n\n{{2013 MLB Draft}}\n{{Pittsburgh Pirates first-round draft picks}}\n{{Tampa Bay Rays roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meadows, Austin}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Loganville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball outfielders]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Rays players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Jamestown Jammers players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Pirates players]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Power players]]\n[[Category:Bradenton Marauders players]]\n[[Category:Altoona Curve players]]\n[[Category:Glendale Desert Dogs players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Black Bears players]]\n[[Category:Durham Bulls players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| image       = Austin Meadows (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  = 255\n| caption     = Meadows in 2019\n| name        = Austin Meadows\n| team        = Tampa Bay Rays\n| number      = 17\n| position    = [[Outfielder]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1995|5|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| bats        = Left\n| throws      = Left\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = May 18\n| debutyear   = 2018\n| debutteam   = Pittsburgh Pirates\n| statyear    = 2019 season\n| statleague  = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .291\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 39\n| stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 106\n| teams =\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Rays]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n| highlights = * [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2019]])\n}}\n'''Austin Wade Meadows''' (born May 3, 1995) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[outfielder]] for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played in MLB for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].\n\n==Career==\nMeadows grew up in [[Grayson, Georgia]], where he competed in [[baseball]] with [[Clint Frazier]].<ref name=Mayo>{{cite web|title=Rivals and pals, Frazier and Meadows create Draft buzz|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130509&content_id=47085694|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> He attended [[Grayson High School]], and led the school's baseball team to the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Class 6A State semi-finals as a junior, [[batting average (baseball)|hitting]] .390 with four [[home run]]s, 28 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] (RBIs), and 19 [[stolen base]]s.<ref name=PP>{{cite web|title=Pirates Draft Austin Meadows With the 9th Overall Pick|url=http://www.piratesprospects.com/2013/06/pirates-draft-austin-meadows-with-the-9th-overall-pick.html|publisher=Piratesprospects.com|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> Meadows was named a preseason First-Team High School All American by Rawlings and Perfect Game,<ref name=AA>{{cite web|title=2013 Rawlings Preseason Senior High School All Americans |url=http://www.perfectgame.org/all_americans/2013/allamerica.aspx |publisher=Perfect Game USA |accessdate=June 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615090719/http://perfectgame.org/all_americans/2013/allamerica.aspx |archivedate=June 15, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> and he hit .535 with 14 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]], one [[Triple (baseball)|triple]], four home runs and 28 RBIs in his senior season.<ref name=PP />\n\nMeadows also played [[American football|football]] as a [[running back]], [[wide receiver]], and [[Punter (football)|punter]] at Grayson where he was a teammate of [[Wayne Gallman]] and [[Robert Nkemdiche]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=David |title=Pirates prospect Austin Meadows was also high school football star |url=https://www.bradenton.com/sports/article140670103.html |accessdate=16 July 2019 |work=[[Bradenton Herald]] |date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Pittsburgh Pirates===\nMeadows was considered as one of the top prospects eligible for the [[2013 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/college/2013-top-100-draft-prospects-may-10-jonathan-gray-tops-mark-appel-for-top-sot/|title=2013 Top 100 Draft Prospects (May 10): Jonathan Gray Takes Top Spot - BaseballAmerica.com|date=May 10, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9255085/mark-appel-jonathan-gray-kris-bryant-top-prospects-2013-mlb-draft|title=Law: Top 100 draft prospects|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He was ultimately selected in the first round, with the ninth overall selection, by the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]. Meadows was committed to attend [[Clemson University]] to play [[college baseball]] for the [[Clemson Tigers baseball|Clemson Tigers]], but chose to forgo that commitment by signing with the Pirates, receiving a $3,029,600 [[signing bonus]] three weeks after the draft.<ref name=Sign>{{cite web|title=Pirates Agree to Terms with Austin Meadows|url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2013/06/pirates-nearing-deal-with-austin-meadows.html|publisher=mlbtraderumors.com|date=June 27, 2013|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter signing with the Pirates, Meadows played for the [[Gulf Coast Pirates]] of the [[Rookie-level]] [[Gulf Coast League]] and the [[Jamestown Jammers]] of the [[Class A-Short Season]] [[New York\u2013Penn League]] in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/pittsburgh-pirates-scouting-report-on-of-austin-meadows-031717|title=Pittsburgh Pirates Scouting Report on OF Austin Meadows \u2013 FOX Sports|date=March 17, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> compiling a combined .316 batting average with seven home runs and 22 RBIs in 48 games between both teams. He played for the [[West Virginia Power]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]] in 2014, but missed a significant portion of the season due to a [[hamstring]] injury,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/pirates/2015/04/02/Austin-Meadows-relishes-his-health-first-taste-of-major-leagues-with-Pirates/stories/201503310103|title=With Pirates, Austin Meadows relishes his health, first taste of majors|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> playing only 38 games, batting .322/.388/.486 with three home runs and 15 RBIs. He played for the [[Bradenton Marauders]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]] (FSL) in 2015, and was named an FSL All-Star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bradenton.com/sports/mlb/bradenton-marauders_/article34905960.html|title=Baseball \u2013 Meadows delivers on hype to become FSL All-Star for Marauders \u2013 Bradenton Herald|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He spent the final week of the season with the [[Altoona Curve]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]].<ref name=eye/> In 121 games for Bradenton he slashed .307/.357/.407 with seven home runs and 54 RBIs, and in six games for Altoona he batted 360. After the regular season, he played for the [[Glendale Desert Dogs]] of the [[Arizona Fall League]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Singer |first=Tom |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146753016/austin-meadows-headed-to-arizona-fall-league/ |title=Austin Meadows headed to Arizona Fall League &#124; MLB.com |publisher=M.mlb.com |date=January 20, 2016 |accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMeadows suffered a broken [[orbital bone]] in his right eye during spring training in 2016.<ref name=eye>{{cite web|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/sports/local-sports/2016/03/meadows-injures-eye/|title=Meadows injures eye |work=Altoona Mirror|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He returned to Altoona and earned a promotion to the [[Indianapolis Indians]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[International League]] in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/sports/altoona-curve/2016/06/pirates-promote-meadows-from-curve/|title=Pirates promote Meadows from Curve |work=Altoona Mirror|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> In 45 games for Altoona he batted .311 with six home runs and 23 RBIs in 45 games, and in 37 games for Indianapolis, he compiled a .214 batting average with six home runs and 34 RBIs. The Pirates invited Meadows to spring training in 2017.<ref name=vibe>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/pirates/2017/03/19/Pirates-prospect-Austin-Meadows-major-league-spring-training/stories/201703190060|title=Pirates top prospect Austin Meadows getting major-league 'vibe'|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Meadows returned to Indianapolis for the 2017 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/milb/news/pittsburgh-pirates-austin-meadows-ignoring-the-hype/c-224790146?tid=185364810|title=IL notes: Meadows ignoring the hype|publisher=MiLB.com|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> where he posted a .250 batting average with four home runs and 36 RBIs in 72 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=640457#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL|title=Austin Meadows Stats, Highlights, Bio - MiLB.com Stats - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|publisher=MiLB.com|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> He missed nearly two months of the season due to hamstring and oblique strains. The Pirates added him to their 40-man roster after the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rob Biertempfel |url=http://triblive.com/sports/pirates/12977361-74/pirates-put-austin-meadows-on-40-man-roster-gift-ngoepe-traded |title=Pirates put Austin Meadows on 40-man roster; Gift Ngoepe traded |publisher=TribLIVE |date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Austin Meadows (43423910741) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Meadows with the Pirates in 2018]]\n[[MLB.com]] ranked Meadows as Pittsburgh's second best prospect going into the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/pirates-2018-top-30-prospects-led-by-keller/c-266878356?tid=151437456|title=New No. 1 Keller leads Pirates Top 30 Prospects list|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> He began the season with Indianapolis and was promoted to the major leagues to make his debut on May 18.<ref>{{cite web|author=3:41&nbsp;pm ET |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/23533618/pittsburgh-pirates-call-top-prospect-austin-meadows |title=Pittsburgh Pirates to call up top OF prospect Austin Meadows |publisher=Espn.com |date= |accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref> He recorded his first major league hit off of [[Tyson Ross]], as well as his first stolen base, that same night.  On May 20, 2018, he hit his first major league home run off of [[Jordan Lyles]].<ref>{{cite web|author=3:35&nbsp;pm ET |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/playbyplay?gameId=380520123 |title=San Diego Padres at Pittsburgh Pirates Boxscore |publisher=Espn.com |date= |accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Meadows was named the [[National League Rookie of the Month]] for the month of May after batting .409 with four home runs, seven RBIs, three doubles, and three stolen bases in 13 games during the month.<ref>http://triblive.com/sports/pirates/13717106-74/austin-meadows-named-national-league-rookie-of-the-month</ref>\n\n===Tampa Bay Rays===\nOn July 31, 2018, Meadows was traded to the [[Tampa Bay Rays]], along with [[Tyler Glasnow]] and a [[player to be named later]], later revealed to be [[Shane Baz]], for [[Chris Archer]] and was optioned to Triple-A Durham.<ref>http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/24246116/chris-archer-traded-pittsburgh-pirates-tampa-bay-rays</ref> Meadows was promoted to the Tampa Bay Rays on September 19. In ten games with the Rays, hit .250/.308/.417 with a [[home run]] and four [[Run batted in|runs batted in]].<ref name=\"baseball-reference.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/meadoau01.shtml|title=Austin Meadows Stats  {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\nMeadows ended the season slashing .287/.325/.461 with six [[home run]]s and 17 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] over 59 games.\n\nThe next year he made his first All-star game.<ref name=\"baseball-reference.com\"/> Meadows ended the season with career highs offensively. He led the team in average (.291), home runs (33), runs (83) and 89 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] in 138 games.\n\n==Personal life==\nMeadows' mother, Staci, played [[softball]] for [[Georgia Southern University]] and [[Georgia State University]], and works as an [[elementary school]] teacher in Grayson. His father, Kenny, played baseball and football for [[Morehead State University]]. His brother, Parker, was drafted by the [[Detroit Tigers]] in the second round of the [[2018 MLB draft]] and currently plays in their organization. Meadows married his wife, Alexis, in December 2018.\n\nMeadows grew up an [[Atlanta Braves]] fan.<ref>https://www.ajc.com/sports/baseball/baseball-draft-goes-through-loganville/SBt4ij5i8F5yiiSY0vgkWO/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=640457|espn=33197|br=m/meadoau01|fangraphs=15672|brm=meadow000aus|retro=M/Pmeada001}}\n*{{twitter|austin_mea